ecial). Most of their content was short stories. However, they did also have some comic strips, increasingly so as the years progressed. During the period of the First Doctor, however, there was only one strip, in the annual for 1967. \n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border:none\"\n|-\n\n|'''#''' ||'''Title''' ||'''Companions''' ||'''Featuring''' ||'''Annual Year'''||'''Date'''  || '''Format''' || '''Writer''' || '''Artist''' \n|-\n\n| 01 || \"Mission for Duh\" || None || TBA || 1967 ||September/October 1966  || TBA || TBA || TBA\n|-\n\n|}\n\n== ''Doctor Who Magazine'' comic strips ==\n\n=== ''Doctor Who Magazine'' ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! # !! Title !! Featuring !! Writer !!width=\"120\"|Release Date\n{{Episode list\n|Title=Operation Proteus\n|Aux1=Susan\n|Aux2=\n|Aux3=\n|EpisodeNumber=1\n|ShortSummary=\n|LineColor=DBE9F4\n|-\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|Title=Food for Thought\n|Aux1=Ben and Polly\n|Aux2=\n|Aux3=\n|EpisodeNumber=2\n|ShortSummary=\n|LineColor=DBE9F4\n|-\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|Title=Flashback\n|Aux1=The Seventh Doctor and Benny\n|Aux2=\n|Aux3=Winter 1992\n|EpisodeNumber=1\n|ShortSummary=\n|LineColor=DBE9F4\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|Title=Are You Listening?\n|Aux1=Steven and Vicki\n|Aux2=\n|Aux3=Summer 1993\n|EpisodeNumber=2\n|ShortSummary=\n|LineColor=DBE9F4\n}}\n|}\n\n===Doctor Who Yearbook===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! # !! Title !! Featuring !! Writer !!width=\"120\"|Release Date\n{{Episode list\n|Title=A Religious Experience\n|Aux1=\n|Aux2=\n|Aux3=1994\n|EpisodeNumber=1\n|ShortSummary=\n|LineColor=DBE9F4\n}}\n|}\n\n===Non Parodic===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! # !! Title !! Featuring !! Writer !!width=\"120\"|Release Date\n{{Episode list\n|Title=Timeslip\n|Aux1=\n|Aux2=\n|Aux3=\n|EpisodeNumber=1\n|ShortSummary=\n|LineColor=DBE9F4\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|Title=Funhouse\n|Aux1=\n|Aux2=\n|Aux3=\n|EpisodeNumber=2\n|ShortSummary=\n|LineColor=DBE9F4\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|Title=Time and Time Again\n|Aux1=Jamie and Zoe \n|Aux2=\n|Aux3=1967\n|EpisodeNumber=3\n|ShortSummary=\n|LineColor=DBE9F4\n}}\n|}\n\n===Both (Non Parodic/Parodic)===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! # !! Title !! Featuring !! Writer !!width=\"120\"|Release Date\n{{Episode list\n|Title=Happy Deathday\n|Aux1=\n|Aux2=\n|Aux3=\n|EpisodeNumber=1\n|ShortSummary=\n|LineColor=DBE9F4\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|Title=Death to the Doctor!\n|Aux1=\n|Aux2=\n|Aux3=\n|EpisodeNumber=2\n|ShortSummary=\n|LineColor=DBE9F4\n}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Doctor Who comic stories]]\n* [[Second Doctor comic stories]]\n* [[Third Doctor comic stories]]\n* [[Fourth Doctor comic strips]]\n* [[Fifth Doctor comic stories]]\n* [[Sixth Doctor comic stories]]\n* [[Seventh Doctor comic stories]]\n* [[Eighth Doctor comic stories]]\n* [[War Doctor Comic Stories|War Doctor comic stories]]\n* [[Ninth Doctor comic stories]]\n* [[Tenth Doctor comic stories]]\n* [[Eleventh Doctor comic stories]]\n* [[Twelfth Doctor comic stories]]\n\n==References==\n'''General'''\n{{refbegin}}\n*Ainsworth, John, \"Behind the Frame\" [I: Polystyle strips (1960s)] in ''Doctor Who Classic Comics'' [Issue 1], 9 December 1992, pp. 20-21\n*Ainsworth, John, \"Frame Count\" [I: First Doctor Polystyle strips] in ''Doctor Who Classic Comics'' [Issue 1], 9 December 1992, p. 19\n*Bentham, Jeremy, \"Doctor Who Comics\"/\"Comics Checklist\" [Polystyle First Doctor] in ''Doctor Who Monthly'' (Issue 62), March 1982, pp. 15-18; 23\n*Hearn, Marcus (director), ''Stripped for Action - The First Doctor'' documentary feature with John Ainsworth (Comics Historian); Alan Barnes (Former ''Doctor Who Magazine'' Editor); Jeremy Bentham (Comics Historian); Gary Russell (Former ''Doctor Who Magazine'' Editor); Bill Mevin (Comics Artist), on ''Doctor Who: The Time Meddler'' (DVD), 16 mins., 2008 \n*Scoones, Paul, ''The Comic Strip Companion: The Unofficial and Unauthorised Guide to Doctor Who in Comics: 1964-1979'', Prestatyn: Telos, 2012\n\n{{refend}}\n\n'''Specific'''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Doctor Who}}\n\n[[Category:Comics based on Doctor Who]]\n[[Category:Works based on Doctor Who|Comics]]\n[[Category:Comics based on television series]]\n[[Category:Comics about time travel]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n'''First Doctor comic stories''' refers to the [[List of Doctor Who comic stories|comic strips]] devoted to the long-running British [[science fiction television]] series ''[[Doctor Who]]'', using the likeness of the [[First Doctor]] [[William Hartnell]]. The strip was launched in [[Polystyle Publications|Polystyle's]] ''[[TV Comic]]'' on 14 November 1964, less than a year after the television series began broadcasting and was the first original [[Doctor Who spin-offs|spin-off]] media from the show.<ref name=\"Scoones2012-16\">\"Scoones (2012), p. 16</ref> This strip began what has become known as the '[[Doctor Who Polystyle comic strip|Polystyle era]]': running from 1964 to 1979.<ref name=\"Scoones2012-11\">\"Scoones (2012), p. 11</ref> The First Doctor starred in this strip running parallel with his appearance on the television show, ending in December 1966, after which ''TV Comic'' began creating strips for the [[Second Doctor]]. The franchise to print a regular comic strip passed to ''[[Doctor Who Magazine]]'' (then ''Doctor Who Weekly'') in 1979, and was opened up to multiple franchises in the mid-2000s. During this time, the First Doctor has made various guest appearances as well as starring in some one-off comic strips. \n\n== Polystyle comic strips (1964-1966) ==\n\n=== History ===\n\n''TV Comic'', according to ''Doctor Who'' historian Jeremy Bentham, 'had grown up in the wake of commercial television. Just as publications like ''[[Radio Fun]]'' had blossomed during the golden years of the wireless so ''TV Comic'' began catering for young readerships who watched and liked children's programmes on [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]].<ref name=\"BenthamDWCI-15\">\"Bentham, \"Doctor Who Comics\" (March 1982), p. 15</ref> ''TV Comic'' - despite only having previously featured spin-offs of ITV programmes, decided to pitch for ''Doctor Who'' with the [[BBC]], and despite initial reticence from the channel, eventually struck a deal.<ref name=\"BenthamDWCI-16\">\"Bentham, \"Doctor Who Comics\" (March 1982), p. 16</ref> The strip launched in issue 674 with a cover date of 14 November 1964; hitting the shelves - according to ''Doctor Who'' comics historian Paul Scoones - on 8 November 1964.<ref name=\"Scoones2012-16\">\"Scoones (2012), p. 16</ref> This means that the ''Doctor Who'' comic strip in ''TV Comic'' was officially the first spin-off media from the show - the first novelization ''[[The_Daleks#In_print|Doctor Who in an exciting adventure with the Daleks]]'' not being released until later the same week on 12 November.<ref name=\"Scoones2012-16\">\"Scoones (2012), p. 16</ref> One immediate difference from the TV show was that the Doctor would be referred to in-strip as 'Doctor Who'.\n\nThere were other differences too. The rights to use ''Doctor Who'' applied 'then, as now' only applied to the likeness of the actor playing the Doctor and the TARDIS, and the portrayal of any other characters - be they companions or adversaries - would have been a separate negotiation and an increased cost, even prohibitive for companions who would appear in every installment.<ref name=\"BenthamDWCI-16\">\"Bentham, \"Doctor Who Comics\" (March 1982), p. 16</ref> Accordingly, the Doctor was given new companions in the first strip, \"The Klepton Parasites\", two grandchildren Gillian and John. Regarding ''Doctor Who'' foes, the situation was very similar. During the First Doctor period of the ''TV Comic'' strip, only the inhabitants of [[Vortis (Doctor Who)|Vortis]] from \"[[The Web Planet]]\" (1965) - the [[List_of_Doctor_Who_universe_creatures_and_aliens_(Q\u2013Z)#Zarbi|Zarbi]] and [[List_of_Doctor_Who_universe_creatures_and_aliens_(H\u2013P)#Menoptra|Menoptra]] - made it into a story. The Doctor's greatest adversaries - the [[Dalek|Daleks]] - could not appear for another reason. This was that creator ([[Terry Nation]]) had 'a separate copyright' for the creatures, and had negotiated a deal with ''[[TV Century 21]]'' (aka ''TV21'') comics around the same time for their own strip; and copyright could 'only be held by one company at any one time' for the same format.<ref name=\"BenthamDWCI-17\">\"Bentham, \"Doctor Who Comics\" (March 1982), p. 17</ref> \"[[Dalek_comic_strips,_illustrated_annuals_and_graphic_novels#Comics|The Daleks]]\" strip appeared in issue 1 of ''TV21'' (23 January 1965), and ran for one hundred and four installments, each a page long, ending in issue 104 (14 January 1967).\n\n=== Writers and Artists ===\n\n'''''Artists:''''' There were three artists during the ''TV Comic'' First Doctor period. '''Neville Main''' was the first to draw the First Doctor (and thus to draw any incarnation of the Doctor).<ref name=\"Scoones2012-23-61\">\"Scoones (2012), pp. 23-61</ref> Main drew the first 9 stories (46 episodes) of the ''TVC'' strip, plus one single episode strip for the 1965 ''TVC Holiday Special'' and two single episode strips for the 1965 ''TVC Annual 1966''. '''Bill Mevin''' took over for the middle of the run, producing 7 stories (28 episodes) for ''TVC'' between October 1965 and April 1966.<ref name=\"Scoones2012-62-75\">\"Scoones (2012), pp. 62-75</ref> Although he produced no ''TVC Holiday Special'' or ''TVC Annual'' strips during this time, he returned later in 1966 to draw one of the two strips single episode strips for that year's ''TVC Annual 1967''.<ref name=\"Scoones2012-91\">\"Scoones (2012), p. 91</ref> After Mevin's relatively short tenure, the ''TVC'' strip was taken on by '''John Canning''' who produced 8 stories (36 episodes) plus two single episode strips for the 1966 ''TVC Holiday Special'' and one of the two single episode strips for the 1966 ''TVC Annual 1967''.<ref name=\"Scoones2012-77-96\">\"Scoones (2012), pp. 77-96</ref> Canning was thus the last of the three artists to draw the First Doctor for ''TVC'', and, furthermore, would go on to kick off the Second Doctor run which began late December 1966.<ref name=\"Scoones2012-100\">\"Scoones (2012), p. 100</ref>\n\n'''''Writers:''''' The situation with the scripts is more complex. Writing in 1982, Jeremy Bentham, the first researcher of ''Doctor Who'' comic strips, commented that in 'those days the notion of a strip having a separate writer was strictly the prerogative of American comic books'.<ref name=\"BenthamDWCI-16\">\"Bentham, \"Doctor Who Comics\" (March 1982), p. 16</ref> However, this view was later revised. John Ainsworth, another comic strip historian, said in an interview: 'There's quite a mystery surrounding around who actually wrote the scripts for the early Hartnell ''Doctor Who'' strips, or indeed, all the Hartnell ''Doctor Who'' strips. It was thought that the artists wrote them, but, after talking to [...] one of the artists, Bill Mevin [...] he doesn't know who wrote them but he knows he did actually work from scripts someone else provided'<ref name=\"Stripped for Action-00:07:01-00:07:24\">''Stripped for Action'' (2008), 00:07:01-00:07:24</ref> In the same documentary, Mevin confirmed this saying, ''TVC'' strips were 'a production line [...] a conveyor belt. I'd get a script and I'd draw it'.<ref name=\"Stripped for Action-00:07:24-00:08:27\">''Stripped for Action'' (2008), 00:07:24-00:08:27</ref>\n\n'''''Style:''''' Bentham describes Main's output thus: very simplistic in style, consisting of basic line illustrations drawn in a very cartoonish way. During his 45 week stint on the strip he never quite captured the likeness of Hartnell [...] He was, however, quite an inventive storywriter.<ref name=\"BenthamDWCI-16\">\"Bentham, \"Doctor Who Comics\" (March 1982), p. 16</ref>\n\n=== List of comic strips ===\n\nThe list below is of all the First Doctor comic strips that appeared in ''TV Comic'' (''TVC'') as well the yearly ''TV Comic Holiday Special'' (''TVCHS'') and ''TV Comic Annual'' (''TVCA''). The order is that designated by the publication date, as integrated by Paul Scoones.<ref name=\"Scoones2012-7\">\"Scoones (2012), p. 7</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border:none\"\n|-\n\n|style=\"background:#ebebeb\"|'''#'''{{ref label|TVC_a|a|}} ||style=\"background:#ebebeb\"|'''Title'''{{ref label|TVC_b|b|}} ||style=\"background:#ebebeb\"|'''Companions''' ||style=\"background:#ebebeb\"|'''Featuring''' ||style=\"background:#ebebeb\"|'''Pub.''' ||style=\"background:#ebebeb\"| '''Issues''' ||style=\"background:#ebebeb\"|'''Ep#''' ||style=\"background:#ebebeb\"|'''Date''' ||style=\"background:#ebebeb\"| '''Format''' ||style=\"background:#ebebeb\"| '''Writer''' || style=\"background:#ebebeb\"|'''Artist''' \n|-\n\n| 01 || \"The Klepton Parasites\" || Gillian/John || Kleptons || ''TVC'' ||674 - 683 || 10|| 14 Nov 1964 - 16 Jan 1965  || B&W || ? || Neville Main\n|-\n\n| 02 || \"The Therovian Quest\" || Gillian/John || Therovians || ''TVC'' ||684 - 689 || 6|| 23 Jan - 27 Feb 1965 || B&W || ? || Neville Main\n|-\n\n| 03 || \"The Hijackers of Thrax\" || Gillian/John || TBA || ''TVC'' ||690 - 692 || 3|| 6 - 20 Mar 1965 || B&W || ? || Neville Main\n|-\n\n| 04 || \"On the Web Planet\" || Gillian/John || Zarbi/Menoptra || ''TVC'' ||693 - 698 || 6|| 27 Mar - 1 May 1965 || B&W || ? || Neville Main\n|-\n\n| 05 || \"The Gyros\" || Gillian/John || TBA || ''TVC'' ||699 - 704 || 6|| 8 May - 12 Jun 1965 || B&W || David Motton || Neville Main\n|-\n\n|style=\"background:#f2f2f2\"| 06 ||style=\"background:#f2f2f2\"| \"Prisoners of Gritog\" ||style=\"background:#f2f2f2\"| Gillian/John || style=\"background:#f2f2f2\"|TBA || style=\"background:#f2f2f2\"|''TVCHS'' ||style=\"background:#f2f2f2\"|HS 1965 ||style=\"background:#f2f2f2\"| 1||style=\"background:#f2f2f2\"| May 1965 || style=\"background:#f2f2f2\"|Duo ||style=\"background:#f2f2f2\"|