{"title_page": "History of rail transport in China", "text_new": ":''This article is part of the [[history of rail transport by country]] series.<br>''\n\nThe '''history of rail transport in China''' began in the late nineteenth century during the [[Qing Dynasty]]. Since then, it has become one of the largest rail networks in the world.<ref>http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/business/2012-12/04/c_132019195.htm</ref>\n\n==Qing dynasty==\nThe first railways in China were built during the [[Qing dynasty]] in the late 19th century, after extensive railway networks were already in place in Europe, North America, [[History of rail transport in India|India]] and [[History of rail transport in Japan|Japan]].<ref name=TLNJ>(Chinese) [http://www.china-review.com/LiShiPinDaoA.asp?id=31577 \"\u4e2d\u56fd\u94c1\u8def\u7684\u53d1\u5c55\u5386\u7a0b\" ''\u4e2d\u56fd\u94c1\u8def\u5e74\u9274''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130430145006/http://www.china-review.com/LiShiPinDaoA.asp?id=31577 |date=2013-04-30 }} 2000 edition</ref> The late arrival of railways in China was due both to the lack of industrialization and skeptical attitude of the Qing government.<ref name=TLNJ/>  Although diverse and prominent personages such as [[Lin Zexu]] and [[Taiping Rebellion|Taiping rebel]] [[Hong Rengan]] called for the building of railways in China in the mid-19th century, the conservative Qing court considered steam engines to be \"clever but useless\" contraptions, and resisted the railways, which would \"deprive us of defensive barriers, harm our fields and interfere with our ''[[feng shui]]''.<ref name=TLNJ/> In the 1860s, Chinese laborers helped build the [[Central Pacific Railroad]] in the United States.\n\n===Early efforts===\n[[File:OpeningDay.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The opening of the short-lived Woosung Road, the first railway in China, between Shanghai and Wusong in 1876.]]\nIn 1865, a British merchant built a 600-meter long [[narrow gauge]] railroad outside the [[Xuanwumen (Beijing)|Xuanwu Gate]] in [[Beijing]] to demonstrate the technology to the imperial court.<ref>(Chinese) [http://www.xinhuanet.com/politics/2016-03/30/c_128848805.htm \u6768\u5f81, \"\u6614\u65e5\u5317\u4eac\u57ce\u7684\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\uff1a\u5929\u575b\u706b\u8f66\u7ad9\u53ea\u7528\u4e86\u4e24\u5e74\"  \u5317\u4eac\u665a\u62a5] 2016-03-30</ref><ref>(Chinese) [https://books.google.com.hk/books?id=AuJyDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT27&lpg=PT27&dq=1865+%E5%AE%A3%E6%AD%A6%E9%97%A8+%E9%93%81%E8%B7%AF&source=bl&ots=Ssk_MeHK0k&sig=ACfU3U0Gg9098r1COTp11rP785K4BCWIoA&hl=zh-CN&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj_ifiJiZLnAhWQMN4KHREWBEoQ6AEwA3oECFgQAQ#v=onepage&q=1865%20%E5%AE%A3%E6%AD%A6%E9%97%A8%20%E9%93%81%E8%B7%AF&f=false \u51af\u529b\u5f3a\uff0c \u51af\u51a0\u8c6a, ''\u7ea2\u8272\u8bb0\u5fc6\uff1a\u4e2d\u4e1c\u94c1\u8def\u4e0a\u7684\u4e2d\u56fd\u68a6'' Beijing Book Co. Inc. 2015]</ref><ref name=\"WangYong\">(Chinese) [http://history.sina.com.cn/bk/gds/2014-01-11/215465697.shtml \u738b\u52c7, \"\u6148\u79a7\u7528\u592a\u76d1\u62c9\u706b\u8f66\u917f\u4e16\u754c\u94c1\u8def\u53f2\u6700\u5927\u7b11\u8bdd\" \u300a\u7687\u57ce\u6839\u4e0b\u7684\u4eac\u5473\u6587\u5316\u300b \u65f6\u4e8b\u51fa\u7248\u793e]  2014-01-11</ref>  The court found it \"exceedingly special and strange in the utmost\" and promptly had the railway dismantled.<ref name=WangYong/>\n\nThe first railroad to operate commercially in China opened in [[Shanghai]] in July 1876.  The railway, known as the [[Woosung Road]], ran from the [[Shanghai International Settlement|American Concession]] in the present-day [[Zhabei District]] to [[Wusong|Woosung]] in the present-day [[Baoshan District, Shanghai|Baoshan District]] and was built by the British trading firm, [[History of Jardine, Matheson & Co.|Jardine, Matheson and Co.]]<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20030821131914/http://www.hkrs.org.hk/newsletter/thrutrain/tt9809/ewoosung.htm]</ref>  Construction took place without approval from the Qing government, which had paid 285,000 [[tael]]s of silver for the railroad<ref name=TLNJ/> and had it dismantled in October 1877.<ref>[http://www.hkrs.org.hk/index_e.htm] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161016154506/http://www.hkrs.org.hk/index_e.htm |date=2016-10-16 }} Hong Kong Railway Society website - English version, under Member's Corner : Feature Articles</ref><ref>{{cite journal|jstor=311679|title=Confucian Patriotism and the Destruction of the Woosung Railway, 1877|first=David|last=Pong|date=1 January 1973|publisher=|journal=Modern Asian Studies|volume=7|issue=4|pages=647\u2013676|doi=10.1017/s0026749x00013469}}</ref><ref>Woosung Road \u2013 the story of China\u2019s First Railway\u201d by Peter Crush, published Hong Kong 1999 ({{ISBN|962-85532-1-6}})</ref>  The rails and rolling stock were later shipped to Taiwan. In late 1884, Jardine, Matheson arranged a loan of 500 million taels of silver to the Chinese government in late 1884 \"for the purpose of building railways\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Chinese Railway Loan|work=Evening Telegraph|date=2 December 1884 |accessdate=8 July 2014 |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000453/18841202/041/0003| publisher = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nThe first railway to endure was the [[Kaiping Tramway and Imperial Railways of North China]]. Initially, a 10 kilometre (6.2&nbsp;mi) line from [[Tangshan]] to [[Xugezhuang]] built in 1881 to transport coal from the coal mine in Tangshan, this line was extended to [[Tianjin]] in 1888 and [[Shanhaiguan District|Shanhaiguan]] and [[Suizhong]] in 1894. This railway became known as the \"Guanneiwai Railway\" (literally, inner and outer Shanhaiguan railway).  The railway was backed by the powerful [[Viceroy of Zhili]], [[Li Hongzhang]], who overcame objections from conservative ministers.  To secure the support of the [[Empress Dowager]] for railway construction,  Li Hongzhang imported a small train set from Germany and built a {{convert|2|km}} [[narrow gauge]] railway from her residence in [[Zhongnanhai]] to her dining hall in [[Beihai Park|Beihai]] in 1888.<ref name=\"Dong2002p35\">{{cite book |last=Dong| first=Madeleine Yue|editor-first=Joseph W| editor-last=Esherick|title=Remaking the Chinese City: Modernity and National Identity, 1900-1950|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|year=2002 |pages=35|chapter=Chapter 8: Defining Beiping - Urban Reconstruction and National Identity, 1928-1936|isbn=0-8248-2518-7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JYaQ0tsBP30C&pg=PA123&dq=beiping#v=onepage&q=palace%20museum&f=false|ref=Dong 2002}}</ref>  The Empress, concerned that the locomotive's noise would disturb the [[geomancy]] or ''[[fengshui]]'' of the imperial city, required the train be pulled by [[eunuchs]] instead of steam engine.<ref name=\"Dong2002p35\"/>\n\nThe next effort was made by [[Taiwan]] Governor [[Liu Mingchuan]]. From 1887 to 1893, {{convert|107|km}} of railway tracks were laid from [[Keelung]] to [[Taipei]] to [[Hsinchu]]. However, this railway was later demolished for modernization when Taiwan was under [[Taiwan under Japanese rule|Japanese rule]].\n\n===Rapid development during 1895-1911===\n[[File:Namitibridge.jpg|right|thumb|The [[Faux Namti Bridge]] on the [[Yunnan\u2013Vietnam Railway]] was built by France in 1906.]]\n[[File:South Manchuria Railway LOC 03283.jpg|thumb|A train on [[South Manchuria Railway]]]]\nQing China's defeat in the [[First Sino-Japanese War]] greatly stimulated the railway development as the government both recognized the importance of modernization and was compelled by foreign powers to grant concessions to build railways along with settlement and mineral rights.  The imperial powers then took to building railways in their spheres of influence. The railroads already built in 1900 had a total length of only 292 miles. Another 4000 miles were in the planning stage.<ref>''Appletons' annual cyclopaedia and register of important events of the year 1901'' (1902) p 151.</ref>\n\nThe British built the Shanghai-Nanjing Railway (1905-1908) and [[Kowloon-Canton Railway]] (completed 1911).  The French built the [[Sino-Vietnamese Railway]] (1904\u201310), an 855&nbsp;km {{RailGauge|1000mm}} line to connect Kunming with Vietnam, then a colony of French Indochina.  The Germans built the [[Jiaoji Railway]] in Shandong Province.  British and German industrialists jointly built the [[Tianjin\u2013Pukou Railway]]. The Americans built the [[Canton - Sam Shui Railway]] in Guangdong in 1902\u201304.  Czarist Russia built the [[China Eastern Railway]] (1897-1901) as a shortcut for the [[Trans-Siberian Railway]] and the [[Southern Manchuria Railway]] to [[Port Arthur, China|Port Arthur]].  To prevent domination by bigger powers, the Qing Court gave the rights to the Lugouqiao-Hankou Railway to Belgians.  The Japanese initially received numerous concessions along the coast of Fujian and Guangdong, and built the [[Chao Chow and Swatow Railway]] (1904\u201306).  After winning the [[Russo-Japanese War]] in 1904, the Japanese took over the southern section of the China Eastern Railway (from Changchun to Port Arthur) and the entire Southern Manchuria Railway.\n\nBy 1911, there were around 9,000&nbsp;km of rails in China. Most of the rails used the {{RailGauge|1435mm|allk=on}}.\n[[File:KCRC early railway network of China.jpg|thumb|230px|left|Map showing early railway expansion in China.]]\n[[File:Hankou-Dazhimen-Station-0238.jpg|right|thumb|Hankou Dazhimen Station, the original southern terminal of the [[Jinghan Railway]]]]\n\nThe imperial capital, [[Beijing]], was designed as the center of the Chinese railway network. Several lines radiated out from Beijing. Three main lines are [[Jingguang railway|Beijing-Hankou Railway]], [[Jingha railway|Beijing-Fengtian Railway]], and [[Tianjin-Pukou Railway]]. Jinghan railway was from eh Beijing to [[Hankou]]. The construction started in 1897 and was completed in 1906. The Guangneiwai railway was extended west to Beijing and east to [[Shenyang|Fengtian]] by 1912 and renamed as Beijing-Fengtian Railway. The Tianjin-Pukou Railway, built from 1908&ndash;1912.  It ran from Tianjin, which was connected by the Beijing-Fengtian Railway, to [[Pukou]] across the Yangtze River from Nanjing.\n\n===Railway protection movement and the Xinhai Revolution===\n{{main|Railway Protection Movement}}\n[[File:Zhangtianyoux.jpg|left|upright|thumbnail|[[Zhan Tianyou]], the \"father of China's railways\"]]\nThe rapid expansion of foreign railroad ownership and operation in China aroused strong public resentment and led to calls for domestic development of railways.<ref name=WangYong/>  To help local economies develop and retain earnings from railways, the Qing government in 1904 permitted local provinces to organize their own railway companies and raise funds by selling shares to the public.  From 1904\u20131907, 15 provincial governments formed their own railway building companies and raised funds by selling shares to citizens and levying taxes.<ref name=WangYong/>   The [[Jingbao railway|Beijing-Zhangjiakou Railway]] built from 1905\u201309, was the first railway to be designed and built indigenously. The chief engineer was [[Zhan Tianyou]], who is known as the Father of China's Railways.  The [[Shanghai-Hangzhou Railway]], 189&nbsp;km in length and completed in 1909, was financed by the provincial governments of Jiangsu and Zhejiang.<ref>[http://mikes.railhistory.railfan.net/r076.html Travelling By Train In China<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  The Zhengding-Taiyuan Railway, originally planned to run from Zhengding County in Hebei Province, was routed from Shijiazhuang instead and opened in 1907.\n\nIn 1911, when some of the provincial railway ventures fell into bankruptcy, the foreign powers pressed the Qing government to permit them to take over the ventures.<ref name=WangYong/>  In May 1911, the Qing government sought to nationalize these locally controlled railway companies and pledge their railway concessions to foreign banks in exchange for loans.  The nationalization order provoked fierce public opposition that led to the [[Railway Protection Movement]], which contributed to the outbreak of the [[Xinhai Revolution]].  Troops sent to Sichuan from neighboring Hubei weakened defenses in [[Wuhan]] where revolutionaries launched the [[Wuchang Uprising]]. The ensuing [[Xinhai Revolution]] toppled the Qing Dynasty.\n\n==Republic of China==\n{{See also|Rail transport in Taiwan|Taiwan_Railways_Administration#History}}\nAfter founding the [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|Republic of China]] on January 1, 1912, Dr. [[Sun Yat-sen]] agreed to cede the provisional presidency to Yuan Shikai in exchange for the latter's assistance in securing the abdication of Qing court.  Sun believed that a national railway network was key to the modernization of China.  He sought and received from Yuan Shikai, the portfolio of railway development for the new republic.\n\nFrom 1928 to 1937, the Republican government in Nanjing built 3,600&nbsp;km of railway inside the [[Great Wall]].<ref name=TLNJ/> [[Manchuria]], located beyond the wall, had 900&nbsp;km of railways built from 1928 until 1931, when the [[Mukden Incident|region was captured by Japan]].<ref name=TLNJ/>\n\n===World War II===\n[[File:Bombing a chinese railway.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Longhai Railway]] bombed during the Second Sino-Japanese War]]\nDuring the [[Second Sino-Japanese War]] of 1937\u20131945, the Republican government dismantled a number of railways to slow the Japanese advance and added 1,900&nbsp;km of railways, mostly in the interior of China after coastal regions were occupied.<ref name=TLNJ/>  Among the completed lines were the [[Longhai Railway]] (Lingbao-Tongguan and Xi'an-Baoji sections), Zhejiang-Jiangxi Railway (Hangzhou-Pingxiang section) and the Guangdong-Hankou Railway (Zhuzhou-Shaoguan section).<ref name=TLNJ/>  The Shanxi warlord [[Yan Xishan]] built the narrow gauge [[Datong-Puzhou Railway]] across Shanxi Province.  The Japanese occupiers, using forced labor, built 5,700&nbsp;km of railway in [[Manchuria]] and [[Rehe Province]] and 900&nbsp;km of railway in [[China Proper]].<ref name=TLNJ/>\n\nIn 1941, construction began of the [[Yunnan Burma Railway]], an attempt to link British occupied [[Burma]] with [[Kunming]] in [[Yunnan]] province. Ultimately, however, the project was aborted.\n\n===1945-1949===\nIn 1945, just after the [[Second Sino-Japanese War]], the Chinese mainland had 27,000&nbsp;km of rail, and it was estimated about 23,000&nbsp;km was usable. By 1948, the number of usable kilometers of rail was estimated at only 8,000&nbsp;km due to the [[Chinese Civil War]]. The [[Communist Party of China|Communists]] actively sabotaged rail lines to disrupt the ruling [[Kuomintang|Nationalists]] (Kuomintang), and the Nationalists scavenged lesser used railways in order to repair the most important ones.<ref name=\"GeoRev\">Norton S. Ginsburg,\n''[[Geographical Review]]'', Vol. 41, No. 3 (Jul., 1951), pp. 470-474</ref>\n\n==People's Republic of China==\n[[File:Chengyu Railway Opening ceremony 2.jpg|250px|right|thumb|Opening ceremony of the [[Chengdu\u2013Chongqing Railway]], the first railway built in China after 1949.]]\n\nIn 1951, after extensive investment in reconstruction, the Communists, who established the [[People's Republic of China]] (PRC) in October 1949, had restored the usable network to about 22,000&nbsp;km. Most of the early reconstruction (about 11,000&nbsp;km) was in Manchuria because [[Manchuria#After World War II|Soviet and Japanese occupation]] there reduced the amount of sabotage between the fighting parties, allowing for quick repairs.<ref name=\"GeoRev\"/>\n\nOn October 14, 1949, the cross-border service on the [[Kowloon-Canton Railway]] was suspended as a result of the [[Chinese Revolution (1949)|communist revolution]], and it was not resumed until April 4, 1979.\n[[File:Wuhan Yangtze River Bridge - the railway level.jpg|230px|left|thumb|A train on [[Wuhan Yangtze River Bridge]] - a first fixed railway link across the river]]\nIn fact, when the PRC was established in 1949, China had constructed 27,380&nbsp;km of railway, but only 24,090&nbsp;km was kept, including 10,309&nbsp;km in the northeastern part of China, and 919&nbsp;km in [[Taiwan]].<ref>\u4e2d\u570b\u9435\u8def1863\uff0d1949:\u5728\u611a\u6627\u3001\u5c08\u5236\u3001\u4fb5\u7565\u4e0b\u6399\u624e(\u4e00), \u8881\u5049\u6642</ref>\n\n===Railway construction in the 1950s===\nThe end to decades of warfare in China allowed railway construction to proceed on a large scale.  In the 1950s, the government initiated numerous railway building projects to fill in missing links in the country's rail network.  The new government undertook a vigorous railway building campaign.  From 1952, when the first railway of the People's Republic, the [[Chengdu\u2013Chongqing Railway]] entered operation, to the end of the [[Five-year plans of the People's Republic of China|First Five Year Plan]] in 1957, {{convert|6100|km|mi|0|abbr=off}} of railroads were built, accounting for 18% of the national total.<ref name=TLNJ/> The lines completed during this period include the final sections of the [[Longhai Railway|Longhai]] and [[Hukun Railway|Xianggui]] Railways, the [[Litang\u2013Zhanjiang Railway|Litang\u2013Zhanjiang]], [[Yingtan\u2013Xiamen Railway|Yingtan\u2013Xiamen]], [[Lancun\u2013Yantai Railway|Lancun\u2013Yantai]] and [[Xiaoshan\u2013Ningbo Railway]]s.<ref name=TLNJ/>   These lines, along with the [[Baoji\u2013Chengdu Railway]] (completed in 1958) and the 1,900&nbsp;km [[Lanzhou\u2013Xinjiang Railway]] to [[Urumqi]] (completed in 1962), extended the national rail network to the Northwest and Southwest, and added connections between the coast and interior.<ref name=TLNJ/>\nIn 1957, passenger trains averaged 34.8&nbsp;km/h and freight trains averaged 25.2&nbsp;km/h.<ref name=TLNJ/>\n\n===The Great Leap Forward===\n[[File:China Railroads 1961.jpg|right|thumb|300px|Map of China's railway network in 1961]]\nThe launch of the [[Great Leap Forward]] in 1958 was intended to rapidly expand railway transport, but produced counterproductive results.<ref name=TLNJ/>  The shipment of freight, which was not quite 300 million tons in 1957, was targeted to reach 900 million tons by 1959 and 3 billion tons by 1972.<ref name=TLNJ/>  The length of newly planned railways rose from 20,000&nbsp;km to 70,000, and 120,000&nbsp;km over the next 15 years.<ref name=TLNJ/>  To reach these targets, the railroads were pushed beyond their capacity.<ref name=TLNJ/>\n\nWithout experimentation, freight trains on all major lines increased carrying load from 2,700 tons to 3,600 tons without adding power to locomotives.<ref name=TLNJ/>  This caused trains to backslide on slopes, damage to rolling stock and steam engines to dry boil.<ref name=TLNJ/>  On time rates fell precipitously.<ref name=TLNJ/>  The railways did set new records, 1.4 billion passenger rides and 1.5 billion tons of freight delivered in the three years between 1958 and 1960, some 200 million passengers and 0.5 billion tons more than the five years from 1953 to 1958, but the freight load fell to 345 million tons in 1962.<ref name=TLNJ/>  The economic disclocation caused by the Great Leap Forward slowed down railway construction.  Numerous lines such as the [[Dazhou-Chengdu Railway]] were delayed for decades as a result.\n\nRail operations were revamped in 1961 and performance improved.<ref name=TLNJ/>  In 1965, freight carried reached 480 million tons and the system set a new record for net income.<ref name=TLNJ/>  The [[Sino-Soviet split]] prompted the leadership to shift railway building toward the \"Third Line\", in the mountainous regions of the interior, away from the east coast and Soviet border.\n\n===Cultural Revolution===\nThe launch of the Cultural Revolution in 1966 brought political turmoil to the country and disruptions to railway operations.<ref name=TLNJ/>  In the fall of 1966, by Chairman Mao's edict, the Red Guards from around the country could travel on trains for free.  To prevent political factional fighting to spread into the railways, the national railways were assigned to the command of the military in the summer of 1967.<ref name=TLNJ/>  Railway management and operations, nevertheless, slipped rapidly.<ref name=TLNJ/>  Accident rates rose 25% from 1966 to 1967, and another 20% from 1967 to 1968.<ref name=TLNJ/>  Premier [[Zhou Enlai]] and other moderate leaders pushed back against leftist-radical management of the railway and operations began to improve in 1969.<ref name=TLNJ/>  In 1973, the system shipped 800 million tons, a new record.<ref name=TLNJ/>   In 1974, however, the [[Gang of Four]] with the [[Criticize Lin, Criticize Confucius|Criticize Lin, Criticize Confucius Campaign]], reasserted the leftist line and railway performance plummted again.<ref name=TLNJ/>  From the summer of 1974 to early 1975, railway hubs in [[Xuzhou]], [[Changsha]], [[Guiyang]], and [[Baotou]] experienced freight bottlenecks.  In April 1975, Deng Xiaoping took control of the leadership and directed the railways to focus on productivity and safety.<ref name=TLNJ/>  In April 1975, the railways' coal carrying targets were met for the first time in nearly five years.<ref name=TLNJ/>  In early 1976, after Deng Xiaoping was removed from power and the Gang of Four reasserted control, railway performance declined again.<ref name=TLNJ/>  Compared to 1975, freight fell by 46.3 million tons year-on-year, accidents rose by 17% and tax revenues paid to the state fell by 740 million.<ref name=TLNJ/>\n\nDespite the turmoil of the [[Cultural Revolution]] and slowdown in rail construction at home, the Chinese Railway Ministry and the Rail Corps managed to build a 1,860&nbsp;km railway across [[Tanzania]] and [[Zambia]].  The [[TAZARA Railway]] was by far the largest foreign aid project undertaken by China in Africa.  As many as 56,000 Chinese engineers and workers were sent overseas from 1968 to 1975.\n\nAfter the Cultural Revolution ended and the [[Chinese economic reform|economic reforms]] were launched in 1978, the railways were reorganized and rededicated to improving safety, performance, technology and profitability.<ref name=TLNJ/>  These principles have guided the railway's operations in the decades since.<ref name=TLNJ/>\n\nIn 1998, passenger trains averaged 54.5&nbsp;km/h and freight trains averaged 31.8&nbsp;km/h.<ref name=TLNJ/>\n\n===Slowdown in the 1980s===\nAfter China initiated market-oriented economic reforms in 1978, railway building slowed as state funds were directed toward higher return investments.  It was not until the 1990s, after more than a decade of economic growth, that the state could commit the funds to renew large-scale railway building.\n\n===Railway building boom since 1990===\nIn 1990, the Lanxin Railway was extended by the [[Northern Xinjiang Railway]] to the [[Rail transport in Kazakhstan|Kazakh]] border.  In 1999, the [[Southern Xinjiang Railway]] brought railway service to [[Kashgar]] in the far west.\n\nThe railway to [[Tibet Autonomous Region|Tibet]] however, was more difficult to build due to the high altitude and terrain. Rail lines were first extended to [[Xining]] in [[Qinghai]], and by 1984 another section between Xining and [[Golmud]] was completed. It was not until 2006 that the whole of the [[Qingzang railway]] was finished, linking [[Lhasa]] with rest of China. Since then, every province-level entity in the People's Republic of China has a railway network.\n\n===End of the steam era===\n[[File:Train and traffic going to the Great Wall.jpg|right|thumb|250px|A steam locomotive and a diesel locomotive near the [[Badaling]] [[Great Wall]] in Beijing in 1979.]]\nBefore the 1980s, due to the low labor cost, ease of manufacture, and cheap coal price, [[steam locomotive]]s dominated the Chinese railways. During the 1980s and 90s, [[diesel locomotive|diesel]] and [[electric locomotive]]s gradually replaced steam engines on the main lines. On some provincial rails, however, steam locomotives were not retired until the 21st century. In December 2005, the world's last regular revenue mainline steam train finished its journey {{Citation needed|date=March 2007}} on the [[Jitong railway]], marking the end of the steam era. Nevertheless, there are still some steam locomotives used on the industrial railways in China.\n\nAs a part of infrastructure upgrade, China in 2007 opened its first [[China Railway High-speed|high-speed rail]] lines using trains with origins in Canada, France, Germany and Japan.\n\n===Network length table===\n{{Historical populations\n| title= Rail track length\n| percentages = pagr\n| align = center\n| pop_name=km\n| cols = 4\n| source= [http://www.360doc.com/content/11/0924/16/5931940_150892508.shtml \u5386\u53f2\u7edf\u8ba1:\u91d1\u7816\u56fd\u5bb6\u5386\u5e74\u94c1\u8def\u8425\u4e1a\u91cc\u7a0b\u6bd4\u8f83(1838\uff5e2010)]{{bull}}[http://data.stats.gov.cn/search.htm?s=\u94c1\u8def\u8425\u4e1a\u91cc\u7a0b Search for \u94c1\u8def\u8425\u4e1a\u91cc\u7a0b at National Bureau of Statistics of China]/[http://data.stats.gov.cn/easyquery.htm?cn=C01&zb=A0G02 Overview]{{bull}}[http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2016-01/18/c_135021027.htm Facts and figures about China's railway development ({{FormatDate|2016-01-18}})]{{Ref label|notes1|a|}}{{bull}}[http://www.mot.gov.cn/tongjishuju/tielu/201905/P020190530365089148979.pdf 2018 Rail Statistics Public Report]\n| 1948 |12768\n| 1949 |21800\n| 1950 |22200\n| 1951 |22300\n| 1952 |22900\n| 1953 |23800\n| 1954 |24500\n| 1955 |25600\n| 1956 |26500\n| 1957 |26700\n| 1958 |30200\n| 1959 |32300\n| 1960 |33900\n| 1961 |34500\n| 1962 |34600\n| 1963 |35000\n| 1964 |35300\n| 1965 |36400\n| 1966 |37800\n| 1967 |38600\n| 1968 |38800\n| 1969 |39300\n| 1970 |41000\n| 1979 |53000\n| 1980 |53300\n| 1981 |53900\n| 1982 |52900\n| 1983 |54100\n| 1984 |54500\n| 1985 |55000\n| 1986 |55700\n| 1987 |55800\n| 1988 |56100\n| 1989 |56900\n| 1990 |57800\n| 1991 |57800\n| 1992 |58100\n| 1993 |58600\n| 1994 |59000\n| 1995 |62400\n| 1996 |64900\n| 1997 |66000\n| 1998 |66400\n| 1999 |67394\n| 2000 |68700\n| 2001 |70100\n| 2002 |71900\n| 2003 |73000\n| 2004 |74400\n| 2005 |75400\n| 2006 |77100\n| 2007 |77966\n| 2008 |79687\n| 2009 |85818\n| 2010 |90504\n| 2012 |97600\n| 2013 |103144\n| 2014 |111800\n| 2015 |120970\n| 2016 |124000\n| 2017 |127000\n| 2018 |131000\n}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Transport in China]]\n*[[Rail transport in the People's Republic of China]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070311005643/http://www.hkrs.org.hk/  The Chinese Eastern Railway - A Glimpse of History by Peter Crush] Click \"English\" and then select \"Feature Articles\"\n*[[Kaiping Tramway]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{refbegin}}\n* a. {{note|notes1}} There is a significant discrepancy in the total length of China's railways reported by ''China Statistical Yearbook'' ({{convert|120970|km|abbr=on}} at year end 2015)<ref name=Yearbook>[http://www.stats.gov.cn/tjsj/ndsj/2016/html/1604EN.jpg ''China Statistical Yearbook 2016'' \"Length of Transport Routes at Year-end by Region (2015)\"] Accessed 2017-02-16</ref> and the ''CIA Factbook'' ({{convert|191270|km|abbr=on}} in 2014).<ref name=\"Factbook\">[https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2121rank.html#ch ''CIA World Factbook'' \"Country Comparison:Railways\"] Accessed 2017-02-16</ref> The ''CIA Factbook'' figure is based on \"the total length of the railway network ''and of its component parts.''\"<ref name=\"Factbook\"/>  The ''Statistical Yearbook'' figure includes \"the total length of the trunk line for passenger and freight transportation in full operation or temporary operation\" and measures the actual route distance between the midpoints of railway stations.<ref name=\"Yearbook Note in Chinese\">(Chinese) [http://data.stats.gov.cn/search.htm?s=%E9%93%81%E8%B7%AF%E8%90%A5%E4%B8%9A%E9%87%8C%E7%A8%8B \u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u56fd\u5bb6\u7edf\u8ba1\u5c40\uff0c\"\u56fd\u5bb6\u6570\u636e\uff0c\u5e74\u5ea6\u6570\u636e\uff0c\u94c1\u8def\u8425\u4e1a\u91cc\u7a0b\uff08\u4e07\u516c\u91cc\uff09\uff0c\u6307\u793a\u89e3\u91ca\"] Accessed 2017-02-16</ref><ref name=\"Yearbook Note in English\">[http://data.stats.gov.cn/english/easyquery.htm?cn=C01 National Bureau of Statistics of China, ''National Data'', Annual Data, Length of Transport Routes, Length of Railways in Operation (10000 km), Explanatory Notes of Indicators\"] Accessed 2017-02-16</ref> Any double-tracked route or route with a return track of shorter distance is counted using the length of the original route.<ref name=\"Yearbook Note in Chinese\"/><ref name=\"Yearbook Note in English\"/>  The length of any return tracks, other tracks within stations, maintenance and service tracks (such as those used to turn trains around), tracks of fork lines, special purpose lines and non-revenue connecting lines are excluded.<ref name=\"Yearbook Note in Chinese\"/><ref name=\"Yearbook Note in English\"/> The ''Statistical Yearbook'' provides cross-year and cross-regional breakdowns of railway length and its figures are presented in China railway articles.<ref name=\"Yearbook Note in Chinese\"/><ref name=\"Yearbook Note in English\"/>\n{{refend}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* David Pong, \"Confucian patriotism and the destruction of the Woosung railway, 1877.\" ''Modern Asian Studies'' 7.3 (1973): 647\u2013676.\n* {{cite book|author=Jim Harter|title=World Railways of the Nineteenth Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ESnBiR7vLPQC&pg=PA223|year=2005|publisher=JHU Press|page=223}}\n* [http://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/5385284 How the Railroad is Modernising Asia], The Advertiser, Adelaide, S. Australia, 22 March 1913. N.B.: A historical article is of approx. 1,500 words, covering approx. a dozen Asian countries.\n* [http://i1103.photobucket.com/albums/g468/chinarail1/Book-Cover_zpsa6c1e53f.jpg Woosung Road - the story of China's First Railway] By Peter Crush, published in Hong Kong 1999.\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090430114355/http://cars.rails.com.cn/ China Academy of Railway Sciences]\n\n{{-}}\n{{Asia in topic|History of rail transport in}}\n{{Transport in China}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of Rail Transport In China}}\n[[Category:History of rail transport in China| ]]\n", "text_old": ":''This article is part of the [[history of rail transport by country]] series.<br>''\n\nThe '''history of rail transport in China''' began in the late nineteenth century during the [[Qing Dynasty]]. Since then, it has become one of the largest rail networks in the world.<ref>http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/business/2012-12/04/c_132019195.htm</ref>\n\n==Qing dynasty==\nThe first railways in China were built during the [[Qing dynasty]] in the late 19th century, after extensive railway networks were already in place in Europe, North America, [[History of rail transport in India|India]] and [[History of rail transport in Japan|Japan]].<ref name=TLNJ>(Chinese) [http://www.china-review.com/LiShiPinDaoA.asp?id=31577 \"\u4e2d\u56fd\u94c1\u8def\u7684\u53d1\u5c55\u5386\u7a0b\" ''\u4e2d\u56fd\u94c1\u8def\u5e74\u9274''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130430145006/http://www.china-review.com/LiShiPinDaoA.asp?id=31577 |date=2013-04-30 }} 2000 edition</ref> The late arrival of railways in China was due both to the lack of industrialization and skeptical attitude of the Qing government.<ref name=TLNJ/>  Although diverse and prominent personages such as [[Lin Zexu]] and [[Taiping Rebellion|Taiping rebel]] [[Hong Rengan]] called for the building of railways in China in the mid-19th century, the conservative Qing court considered steam engines to be \"clever but useless\" contraptions, and resisted the railways, which would \"deprive us of defensive barriers, harm our fields and interfere with our ''[[feng shui]]''.<ref name=TLNJ/> In the 1860s, Chinese laborers helped build the [[Central Pacific Railroad]] in the United States.\n\n===Early efforts===\n[[File:OpeningDay.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The opening of the short-lived Woosung Road, the first railway in China, between Shanghai and Wusong in 1876.]]\nIn 1865, a British merchant built a 600-meter long [[narrow gauge]] railroad outside the [[Xuanwumen (Beijing)|Xuanwu Gate]] in [[Beijing]] to demonstrate the technology to the imperial court.<ref>(Chinese) [http://www.xinhuanet.com/politics/2016-03/30/c_128848805.htm \u6768\u5f81, \"\u6614\u65e5\u5317\u4eac\u57ce\u7684\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\uff1a\u5929\u575b\u706b\u8f66\u7ad9\u53ea\u7528\u4e86\u4e24\u5e74\"  \u5317\u4eac\u665a\u62a5] 2016-03-30</ref><ref>(Chinese) [https://books.google.com.hk/books?id=AuJyDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT27&lpg=PT27&dq=1865+%E5%AE%A3%E6%AD%A6%E9%97%A8+%E9%93%81%E8%B7%AF&source=bl&ots=Ssk_MeHK0k&sig=ACfU3U0Gg9098r1COTp11rP785K4BCWIoA&hl=zh-CN&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj_ifiJiZLnAhWQMN4KHREWBEoQ6AEwA3oECFgQAQ#v=onepage&q=1865%20%E5%AE%A3%E6%AD%A6%E9%97%A8%20%E9%93%81%E8%B7%AF&f=false \u51af\u529b\u5f3a\uff0c \u51af\u51a0\u8c6a, ''\u7ea2\u8272\u8bb0\u5fc6\uff1a\u4e2d\u4e1c\u94c1\u8def\u4e0a\u7684\u4e2d\u56fd\u68a6'' Beijing Book Co. Inc. 2015]</ref><ref name=\"WangYong\">(Chinese) [http://history.sina.com.cn/bk/gds/2014-01-11/215465697.shtml \u738b\u52c7, \"\u6148\u79a7\u7528\u592a\u76d1\u62c9\u706b\u8f66\u917f\u4e16\u754c\u94c1\u8def\u53f2\u6700\u5927\u7b11\u8bdd\" \u300a\u7687\u57ce\u6839\u4e0b\u7684\u4eac\u5473\u6587\u5316\u300b \u65f6\u4e8b\u51fa\u7248\u793e]  2014-01-11</ref>  The court found it \"exceedingly special and strange in the utmost\" and promptly had the railway dismantled.<ref name=WangYong/>\n\nThe first railroad to operate commercially in China opened in [[Shanghai]] in July 1876.  The railway, known as the [[Woosung Road]], ran from the [[Shanghai International Settlement|American Concession]] in the present-day [[Zhabei District]] to [[Wusong|Woosung]] in the present-day [[Baoshan District, Shanghai|Baoshan District]] and was built by the British trading firm, [[History of Jardine, Matheson & Co.|Jardine, Matheson and Co.]]<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20030821131914/http://www.hkrs.org.hk/newsletter/thrutrain/tt9809/ewoosung.htm]</ref>  Construction took place without approval from the Qing government, which had paid 285,000 [[tael]]s of silver for the railroad<ref name=TLNJ/> and had it dismantled in October 1877.<ref>[http://www.hkrs.org.hk/index_e.htm] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161016154506/http://www.hkrs.org.hk/index_e.htm |date=2016-10-16 }} Hong Kong Railway Society website - English version, under Member's Corner : Feature Articles</ref><ref>{{cite journal|jstor=311679|title=Confucian Patriotism and the Destruction of the Woosung Railway, 1877|first=David|last=Pong|date=1 January 1973|publisher=|journal=Modern Asian Studies|volume=7|issue=4|pages=647\u2013676|doi=10.1017/s0026749x00013469}}</ref><ref>Woosung Road \u2013 the story of China\u2019s First Railway\u201d by Peter Crush, published Hong Kong 1999 ({{ISBN|962-85532-1-6}})</ref>  The rails and rolling stock were later shipped to Taiwan. In late 1884, Jardine, Matheson arranged a loan of 500 million taels of silver to the Chinese government in late 1884 \"for the purpose of building railways\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Chinese Railway Loan|work=Evening Telegraph|date=2 December 1884 |accessdate=8 July 2014 |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000453/18841202/041/0003| publisher = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nThe first railway to endure was the [[Kaiping Tramway and Imperial Railways of North China]]. Initially, a 10 kilometre (6.2&nbsp;mi) line from [[Tangshan]] to [[Xugezhuang]] built in 1881 to transport coal from the coal mine in Tangshan, this line was extended to [[Tianjin]] in 1888 and [[Shanhaiguan District|Shanhaiguan]] and [[Suizhong]] in 1894. This railway became known as the \"Guanneiwai Railway\" (literally, inner and outer Shanhaiguan railway).  The railway was backed by the powerful [[Viceroy of Zhili]], [[Li Hongzhang]], who overcame objections from conservative ministers.  To secure the support of the [[Empress Dowager]] for railway construction,  Li Hongzhang imported a small train set from Germany and built a {{convert|2|km}} [[narrow gauge]] railway from her residence in [[Zhongnanhai]] to her dining hall in [[Beihai Park|Beihai]] in 1888.<ref name=\"Dong2002p35\">{{cite book |last=Dong| first=Madeleine Yue|editor-first=Joseph W| editor-last=Esherick|title=Remaking the Chinese City: Modernity and National Identity, 1900-1950|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|year=2002 |pages=35|chapter=Chapter 8: Defining Beiping - Urban Reconstruction and National Identity, 1928-1936|isbn=0-8248-2518-7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JYaQ0tsBP30C&pg=PA123&dq=beiping#v=onepage&q=palace%20museum&f=false|ref=Dong 2002}}</ref>  The Empress, concerned that the locomotive's noise would disturb the [[geomancy]] or ''[[fengshui]]'' of the imperial city, required the train be pulled by [[eunuchs]] instead of steam engine.<ref name=\"Dong2002p35\"/>\n\nThe next effort was made by [[Taiwan]] Governor [[Liu Mingchuan]]. From 1887 to 1893, {{convert|107|km}} of railway tracks were laid from [[Keelung]] to [[Taipei]] to [[Hsinchu]]. However, this railway was later demolished for modernization when Taiwan was under [[Taiwan under Japanese rule|Japanese rule]].\n\n===Rapid development during 1895-1911===\n[[File:Namitibridge.jpg|right|thumb|The [[Faux Namti Bridge]] on the [[Yunnan\u2013Vietnam Railway]] was built by France in 1906.]]\n[[File:South Manchuria Railway LOC 03283.jpg|thumb|A train on [[South Manchuria Railway]]]]\nQing China's defeat in the [[First Sino-Japanese War]] greatly stimulated the railway development as the government both recognized the importance of modernization and was compelled by foreign powers to grant concessions to build railways along with settlement and mineral rights.  The imperial powers then took to building railways in their spheres of influence. The railroads already built in 1900 had a total length of only 292 miles. Another 4000 miles were in the planning stage.<ref>''Appletons' annual cyclopaedia and register of important events of the year 1901'' (1902) p 151.</ref>\n\nThe British built the Shanghai-Nanjing Railway (1905-1908) and [[Kowloon-Canton Railway]] (completed 1911).  The French built the [[Sino-Vietnamese Railway]] (1904\u201310), an 855&nbsp;km {{RailGauge|1000mm}} line to connect Kunming with Vietnam, then a colony of French Indochina.  The Germans built the [[Jiaoji Railway]] in Shandong Province.  British and German industrialists jointly built the [[Tianjin\u2013Pukou Railway]]. The Americans built the [[Canton - Sam Shui Railway]] in Guangdong in 1902-04.  Czarist Russia built the [[China Eastern Railway]] (1897-1901) as a shortcut for the [[Trans-Siberian Railway]] and the [[Southern Manchuria Railway]] to [[Port Arthur, China|Port Arthur]].  To prevent domination by bigger powers, the Qing Court gave the rights to the Lugouqiao-Hankou Railway to Belgians.  The Japanese initially received numerous concessions along the coast of Fujian and Guangdong, and built the [[Chao Chow and Swatow Railway]] (1904\u201306).  After winning the [[Russo-Japanese War]] in 1904, the Japanese took over the southern section of the China Eastern Railway (from Changchun to Port Arthur) and the entire Southern Manchuria Railway.\n\nBy 1911, there were around 9,000&nbsp;km of rails in China. Most of the rails used the {{RailGauge|1435mm|allk=on}}.\n[[File:KCRC early railway network of China.jpg|thumb|230px|left|Map showing early railway expansion in China.]]\n[[File:Hankou-Dazhimen-Station-0238.jpg|right|thumb|Hankou Dazhimen Station, the original southern terminal of the [[Jinghan Railway]]]]\n\nThe imperial capital, [[Beijing]], was designed as the center of the Chinese railway network. Several lines radiated out from Beijing. Three main lines are [[Jingguang railway|Beijing-Hankou Railway]], [[Jingha railway|Beijing-Fengtian Railway]], and [[Tianjin-Pukou Railway]]. Jinghan railway was from eh Beijing to [[Hankou]]. The construction started in 1897 and was completed in 1906. The Guangneiwai railway was extended west to Beijing and east to [[Shenyang|Fengtian]] by 1912 and renamed as Beijing-Fengtian Railway. The Tianjin-Pukou Railway, built from 1908&ndash;1912.  It ran from Tianjin, which was connected by the Beijing-Fengtian Railway, to [[Pukou]] across the Yangtze River from Nanjing.\n\n===Railway protection movement and the Xinhai Revolution===\n{{main|Railway Protection Movement}}\n[[File:Zhangtianyoux.jpg|left|upright|thumbnail|[[Zhan Tianyou]], the \"father of China's railways\"]]\nThe rapid expansion of foreign railroad ownership and operation in China aroused strong public resentment and led to calls for domestic development of railways.<ref name=WangYong/>  To help local economies develop and retain earnings from railways, the Qing government in 1904 permitted local provinces to organize their own railway companies and raise funds by selling shares to the public.  From 1904-1907, 15 provincial governments formed their own railway building companies and raised funds by selling shares to citizens and levying taxes.<ref name=WangYong/>   The [[Jingbao railway|Beijing-Zhangjiakou Railway]] built from 1905\u201309, was the first railway to be designed and built indigenously. The chief engineer was [[Zhan Tianyou]], who is known as the Father of China's Railways.  The [[Shanghai-Hangzhou Railway]], 189&nbsp;km in length and completed in 1909, was financed by the provincial governments of Jiangsu and Zhejiang.<ref>[http://mikes.railhistory.railfan.net/r076.html Travelling By Train In China<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  The Zhengding-Taiyuan Railway, originally planned to run from Zhengding County in Hebei Province, was routed from Shijiazhuang instead and opened in 1907.\n\nIn 1911, when some of the provincial railway ventures fell into bankruptcy, the foreign powers pressed the Qing government to permit them to take over the ventures.<ref name=WangYong/>  In May 1911, the Qing government sought to nationalize these locally controlled railway companies and pledge their railway concessions to foreign banks in exchange for loans.  The nationalization order provoked fierce public opposition that led to the [[Railway Protection Movement]], which contributed to the outbreak of the [[Xinhai Revolution]].  Troops sent to Sichuan from neighboring Hubei weakened defenses in [[Wuhan]] where revolutionaries launched the [[Wuchang Uprising]]. The ensuing [[Xinhai Revolution]] toppled the Qing Dynasty.\n\n==Republic of China==\n{{See also|Rail transport in Taiwan|Taiwan_Railways_Administration#History}}\nAfter founding the [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|Republic of China]] on January 1, 1912, Dr. [[Sun Yat-sen]] agreed to cede the provisional presidency to Yuan Shikai in exchange for the latter's assistance in securing the abdication of Qing court.  Sun believed that a national railway network was key to the modernization of China.  He sought and received from Yuan Shikai, the portfolio of railway development for the new republic.\n\nFrom 1928 to 1937, the Republican government in Nanjing built 3,600&nbsp;km of railway inside the [[Great Wall]].<ref name=TLNJ/> [[Manchuria]], located beyond the wall, had 900&nbsp;km of railways built from 1928 until 1931, when the [[Mukden Incident|region was captured by Japan]].<ref name=TLNJ/>\n\n===World War II===\n[[File:Bombing a chinese railway.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Longhai Railway]] bombed during the Second Sino-Japanese War]]\nDuring the [[Second Sino-Japanese War]] of 1937-1945, the Republican government dismantled a number of railways to slow the Japanese advance and added 1,900&nbsp;km of railways, mostly in the interior of China after coastal regions were occupied.<ref name=TLNJ/>  Among the completed lines were the [[Longhai Railway]] (Lingbao-Tongguan and Xi'an-Baoji sections), Zhejiang-Jiangxi Railway (Hangzhou-Pingxiang section) and the Guangdong-Hankou Railway (Zhuzhou-Shaoguan section).<ref name=TLNJ/>  The Shanxi warlord [[Yan Xishan]] built the narrow gauge [[Datong-Puzhou Railway]] across Shanxi Province.  The Japanese occupiers, using forced labor, built 5,700&nbsp;km of railway in [[Manchuria]] and [[Rehe Province]] and 900&nbsp;km of railway in [[China Proper]].<ref name=TLNJ/>\n\nIn 1941, construction began of the [[Yunnan Burma Railway]], an attempt to link British occupied [[Burma]] with [[Kunming]] in [[Yunnan]] province. Ultimately, however, the project was aborted.\n\n===1945-1949===\nIn 1945, just after the [[Second Sino-Japanese War]], the Chinese mainland had 27,000&nbsp;km of rail, and it was estimated about 23,000&nbsp;km was usable. By 1948, the number of usable kilometers of rail was estimated at only 8,000&nbsp;km due to the [[Chinese Civil War]]. The [[Communist Party of China|Communists]] actively sabotaged rail lines to disrupt the ruling [[Kuomintang|Nationalists]] (Kuomintang), and the Nationalists scavenged lesser used railways in order to repair the most important ones.<ref name=\"GeoRev\">Norton S. Ginsburg,\n''[[Geographical Review]]'', Vol. 41, No. 3 (Jul., 1951), pp. 470-474</ref>\n\n==People's Republic of China==\n[[File:Chengyu Railway Opening ceremony 2.jpg|250px|right|thumb|Opening ceremony of the [[Chengdu\u2013Chongqing Railway]], the first railway built in China after 1949.]]\n\nIn 1951, after extensive investment in reconstruction, the Communists, who established the [[People's Republic of China]] (PRC) in October 1949, had restored the usable network to about 22,000&nbsp;km. Most of the early reconstruction (about 11,000&nbsp;km) was in Manchuria because [[Manchuria#After World War II|Soviet and Japanese occupation]] there reduced the amount of sabotage between the fighting parties, allowing for quick repairs.<ref name=\"GeoRev\"/>\n\nOn October 14, 1949, the cross-border service on the [[Kowloon-Canton Railway]] was suspended as a result of the [[Chinese Revolution (1949)|communist revolution]], and it was not resumed until April 4, 1979.\n[[File:Wuhan Yangtze River Bridge - the railway level.jpg|230px|left|thumb|A train on [[Wuhan Yangtze River Bridge]] - a first fixed railway link across the river]]\nIn fact, when the PRC was established in 1949, China had constructed 27,380&nbsp;km of railway, but only 24,090&nbsp;km was kept, including 10,309&nbsp;km in the northeastern part of China, and 919&nbsp;km in [[Taiwan]].<ref>\u4e2d\u570b\u9435\u8def1863\uff0d1949:\u5728\u611a\u6627\u3001\u5c08\u5236\u3001\u4fb5\u7565\u4e0b\u6399\u624e(\u4e00), \u8881\u5049\u6642</ref>\n\n===Railway construction in the 1950s===\nThe end to decades of warfare in China allowed railway construction to proceed on a large scale.  In the 1950s, the government initiated numerous railway building projects to fill in missing links in the country's rail network.  The new government undertook a vigorous railway building campaign.  From 1952, when the first railway of the People's Republic, the [[Chengdu\u2013Chongqing Railway]] entered operation, to the end of the [[Five-year plans of the People's Republic of China|First Five Year Plan]] in 1957, {{convert|6100|km|mi|0|abbr=off}} of railroads were built, accounting for 18% of the national total.<ref name=TLNJ/> The lines completed during this period include the final sections of the [[Longhai Railway|Longhai]] and [[Hukun Railway|Xianggui]] Railways, the [[Litang\u2013Zhanjiang Railway|Litang\u2013Zhanjiang]], [[Yingtan\u2013Xiamen Railway|Yingtan\u2013Xiamen]], [[Lancun\u2013Yantai Railway|Lancun\u2013Yantai]] and [[Xiaoshan\u2013Ningbo Railway]]s.<ref name=TLNJ/>   These lines, along with the [[Baoji\u2013Chengdu Railway]] (completed in 1958) and the 1,900&nbsp;km [[Lanzhou\u2013Xinjiang Railway]] to [[Urumqi]] (completed in 1962), extended the national rail network to the Northwest and Southwest, and added connections between the coast and interior.<ref name=TLNJ/>\nIn 1957, passenger trains averaged 34.8&nbsp;km/h and freight trains averaged 25.2&nbsp;km/h.<ref name=TLNJ/>\n\n===The Great Leap Forward===\n[[File:China Railroads 1961.jpg|right|thumb|300px|Map of China's railway network in 1961]]\nThe launch of the [[Great Leap Forward]] in 1958 was intended to rapidly expand railway transport, but produced counterproductive results.<ref name=TLNJ/>  The shipment of freight, which was not quite 300 million tons in 1957, was targeted to reach 900 million tons by 1959 and 3 billion tons by 1972.<ref name=TLNJ/>  The length of newly planned railways rose from 20,000&nbsp;km to 70,000, and 120,000&nbsp;km over the next 15 years.<ref name=TLNJ/>  To reach these targets, the railroads were pushed beyond their capacity.<ref name=TLNJ/>\n\nWithout experimentation, freight trains on all major lines increased carrying load from 2,700 tons to 3,600 tons without adding power to locomotives.<ref name=TLNJ/>  This caused trains to backslide on slopes, damage to rolling stock and steam engines to dry boil.<ref name=TLNJ/>  On time rates fell precipitously.<ref name=TLNJ/>  The railways did set new records, 1.4 billion passenger rides and 1.5 billion tons of freight delivered in the three years between 1958 and 1960, some 200 million passengers and 0.5 billion tons more than the five years from 1953 to 1958, but the freight load fell to 345 million tons in 1962.<ref name=TLNJ/>  The economic disclocation caused by the Great Leap Forward slowed down railway construction.  Numerous lines such as the [[Dazhou-Chengdu Railway]] were delayed for decades as a result.\n\nRail operations were revamped in 1961 and performance improved.<ref name=TLNJ/>  In 1965, freight carried reached 480 million tons and the system set a new record for net income.<ref name=TLNJ/>  The [[Sino-Soviet split]] prompted the leadership to shift railway building toward the \"Third Line\", in the mountainous regions of the interior, away from the east coast and Soviet border.\n\n===Cultural Revolution===\nThe launch of the Cultural Revolution in 1966 brought political turmoil to the country and disruptions to railway operations.<ref name=TLNJ/>  In the fall of 1966, by Chairman Mao's edict, the Red Guards from around the country could travel on trains for free.  To prevent political factional fighting to spread into the railways, the national railways were assigned to the command of the military in the summer of 1967.<ref name=TLNJ/>  Railway management and operations, nevertheless, slipped rapidly.<ref name=TLNJ/>  Accident rates rose 25% from 1966 to 1967, and another 20% from 1967 to 1968.<ref name=TLNJ/>  Premier [[Zhou Enlai]] and other moderate leaders pushed back against leftist-radical management of the railway and operations began to improve in 1969.<ref name=TLNJ/>  In 1973, the system shipped 800 million tons, a new record.<ref name=TLNJ/>   In 1974, however, the [[Gang of Four]] with the [[Criticize Lin, Criticize Confucius|Criticize Lin, Criticize Confucius Campaign]], reasserted the leftist line and railway performance plummted again.<ref name=TLNJ/>  From the summer of 1974 to early 1975, railway hubs in [[Xuzhou]], [[Changsha]], [[Guiyang]], and [[Baotou]] experienced freight bottlenecks.  In April 1975, Deng Xiaoping took control of the leadership and directed the railways to focus on productivity and safety.<ref name=TLNJ/>  In April 1975, the railways' coal carrying targets were met for the first time in nearly five years.<ref name=TLNJ/>  In early 1976, after Deng Xiaoping was removed from power and the Gang of Four reasserted control, railway performance declined again.<ref name=TLNJ/>  Compared to 1975, freight fell by 46.3 million tons year-on-year, accidents rose by 17% and tax revenues paid to the state fell by 740 million.<ref name=TLNJ/>\n\nDespite the turmoil of the [[Cultural Revolution]] and slowdown in rail construction at home, the Chinese Railway Ministry and the Rail Corps managed to build a 1,860&nbsp;km railway across [[Tanzania]] and [[Zambia]].  The [[TAZARA Railway]] was by far the largest foreign aid project undertaken by China in Africa.  As many as 56,000 Chinese engineers and workers were sent overseas from 1968 to 1975.\n\nAfter the Cultural Revolution ended and the [[Chinese economic reform|economic reforms]] were launched in 1978, the railways were reorganized and rededicated to improving safety, performance, technology and profitability.<ref name=TLNJ/>  These principles have guided the railway's operations in the decades since.<ref name=TLNJ/>\n\nIn 1998, passenger trains averaged 54.5&nbsp;km/h and freight trains averaged 31.8&nbsp;km/h.<ref name=TLNJ/>\n\n===Slowdown in the 1980s===\nAfter China initiated market-oriented economic reforms in 1978, railway building slowed as state funds were directed toward higher return investments.  It was not until the 1990s, after more than a decade of economic growth, that the state could commit the funds to renew large-scale railway building.\n\n===Railway building boom since 1990===\nIn 1990, the Lanxin Railway was extended by the [[Northern Xinjiang Railway]] to the [[Rail transport in Kazakhstan|Kazakh]] border.  In 1999, the [[Southern Xinjiang Railway]] brought railway service to [[Kashgar]] in the far west.\n\nThe railway to [[Tibet Autonomous Region|Tibet]] however, was more difficult to build due to the high altitude and terrain. Rail lines were first extended to [[Xining]] in [[Qinghai]], and by 1984 another section between Xining and [[Golmud]] was completed. It was not until 2006 that the whole of the [[Qingzang railway]] was finished, linking [[Lhasa]] with rest of China. Since then, every province-level entity in the People's Republic of China has a railway network.\n\n===End of the steam era===\n[[File:Train and traffic going to the Great Wall.jpg|right|thumb|250px|A steam locomotive and a diesel locomotive near the [[Badaling]] [[Great Wall]] in Beijing in 1979.]]\nBefore the 1980s, due to the low labor cost, ease of manufacture, and cheap coal price, [[steam locomotive]]s dominated the Chinese railways. During the 1980s and 90s, [[diesel locomotive|diesel]] and [[electric locomotive]]s gradually replaced steam engines on the main lines. On some provincial rails, however, steam locomotives were not retired until the 21st century. In December 2005, the world's last regular revenue mainline steam train finished its journey {{Citation needed|date=March 2007}} on the [[Jitong railway]], marking the end of the steam era. Nevertheless, there are still some steam locomotives used on the industrial railways in China.\n\nAs a part of infrastructure upgrade, China in 2007 opened its first [[China Railway High-speed|high-speed rail]] lines using trains with origins in Canada, France, Germany and Japan.\n\n===Network length table===\n{{Historical populations\n| title= Rail track length\n| percentages = pagr\n| align = center\n| pop_name=km\n| cols = 4\n| source= [http://www.360doc.com/content/11/0924/16/5931940_150892508.shtml \u5386\u53f2\u7edf\u8ba1:\u91d1\u7816\u56fd\u5bb6\u5386\u5e74\u94c1\u8def\u8425\u4e1a\u91cc\u7a0b\u6bd4\u8f83(1838\uff5e2010)]{{bull}}[http://data.stats.gov.cn/search.htm?s=\u94c1\u8def\u8425\u4e1a\u91cc\u7a0b Search for \u94c1\u8def\u8425\u4e1a\u91cc\u7a0b at National Bureau of Statistics of China]/[http://data.stats.gov.cn/easyquery.htm?cn=C01&zb=A0G02 Overview]{{bull}}[http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2016-01/18/c_135021027.htm Facts and figures about China's railway development ({{FormatDate|2016-01-18}})]{{Ref label|notes1|a|}}{{bull}}[http://www.mot.gov.cn/tongjishuju/tielu/201905/P020190530365089148979.pdf 2018 Rail Statistics Public Report]\n| 1948 |12768\n| 1949 |21800\n| 1950 |22200\n| 1951 |22300\n| 1952 |22900\n| 1953 |23800\n| 1954 |24500\n| 1955 |25600\n| 1956 |26500\n| 1957 |26700\n| 1958 |30200\n| 1959 |32300\n| 1960 |33900\n| 1961 |34500\n| 1962 |34600\n| 1963 |35000\n| 1964 |35300\n| 1965 |36400\n| 1966 |37800\n| 1967 |38600\n| 1968 |38800\n| 1969 |39300\n| 1970 |41000\n| 1979 |53000\n| 1980 |53300\n| 1981 |53900\n| 1982 |52900\n| 1983 |54100\n| 1984 |54500\n| 1985 |55000\n| 1986 |55700\n| 1987 |55800\n| 1988 |56100\n| 1989 |56900\n| 1990 |57800\n| 1991 |57800\n| 1992 |58100\n| 1993 |58600\n| 1994 |59000\n| 1995 |62400\n| 1996 |64900\n| 1997 |66000\n| 1998 |66400\n| 1999 |67394\n| 2000 |68700\n| 2001 |70100\n| 2002 |71900\n| 2003 |73000\n| 2004 |74400\n| 2005 |75400\n| 2006 |77100\n| 2007 |77966\n| 2008 |79687\n| 2009 |85818\n| 2010 |90504\n| 2012 |97600\n| 2013 |103144\n| 2014 |111800\n| 2015 |120970\n| 2016 |124000\n| 2017 |127000\n| 2018 |131000\n}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Transport in China]]\n*[[Rail transport in the People's Republic of China]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070311005643/http://www.hkrs.org.hk/  The Chinese Eastern Railway - A Glimpse of History by Peter Crush] Click \"English\" and then select \"Feature Articles\"\n*[[Kaiping Tramway]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{refbegin}}\n* a. {{note|notes1}} There is a significant discrepancy in the total length of China's railways reported by ''China Statistical Yearbook'' ({{convert|120970|km|abbr=on}} at year end 2015)<ref name=Yearbook>[http://www.stats.gov.cn/tjsj/ndsj/2016/html/1604EN.jpg ''China Statistical Yearbook 2016'' \"Length of Transport Routes at Year-end by Region (2015)\"] Accessed 2017-02-16</ref> and the ''CIA Factbook'' ({{convert|191270|km|abbr=on}} in 2014).<ref name=\"Factbook\">[https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2121rank.html#ch ''CIA World Factbook'' \"Country Comparison:Railways\"] Accessed 2017-02-16</ref> The ''CIA Factbook'' figure is based on \"the total length of the railway network ''and of its component parts.''\"<ref name=\"Factbook\"/>  The ''Statistical Yearbook'' figure includes \"the total length of the trunk line for passenger and freight transportation in full operation or temporary operation\" and measures the actual route distance between the midpoints of railway stations.<ref name=\"Yearbook Note in Chinese\">(Chinese) [http://data.stats.gov.cn/search.htm?s=%E9%93%81%E8%B7%AF%E8%90%A5%E4%B8%9A%E9%87%8C%E7%A8%8B \u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u56fd\u5bb6\u7edf\u8ba1\u5c40\uff0c\"\u56fd\u5bb6\u6570\u636e\uff0c\u5e74\u5ea6\u6570\u636e\uff0c\u94c1\u8def\u8425\u4e1a\u91cc\u7a0b\uff08\u4e07\u516c\u91cc\uff09\uff0c\u6307\u793a\u89e3\u91ca\"] Accessed 2017-02-16</ref><ref name=\"Yearbook Note in English\">[http://data.stats.gov.cn/english/easyquery.htm?cn=C01 National Bureau of Statistics of China, ''National Data'', Annual Data, Length of Transport Routes, Length of Railways in Operation (10000 km), Explanatory Notes of Indicators\"] Accessed 2017-02-16</ref> Any double-tracked route or route with a return track of shorter distance is counted using the length of the original route.<ref name=\"Yearbook Note in Chinese\"/><ref name=\"Yearbook Note in English\"/>  The length of any return tracks, other tracks within stations, maintenance and service tracks (such as those used to turn trains around), tracks of fork lines, special purpose lines and non-revenue connecting lines are excluded.<ref name=\"Yearbook Note in Chinese\"/><ref name=\"Yearbook Note in English\"/> The ''Statistical Yearbook'' provides cross-year and cross-regional breakdowns of railway length and its figures are presented in China railway articles.<ref name=\"Yearbook Note in Chinese\"/><ref name=\"Yearbook Note in English\"/>\n{{refend}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* David Pong, \"Confucian patriotism and the destruction of the Woosung railway, 1877.\" ''Modern Asian Studies'' 7.3 (1973): 647-676.\n* {{cite book|author=Jim Harter|title=World Railways of the Nineteenth Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ESnBiR7vLPQC&pg=PA223|year=2005|publisher=JHU Press|page=223}}\n* [http://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/5385284 How the Railroad is Modernising Asia], The Advertiser, Adelaide, S. Australia, 22 March 1913. N.B.: A historical article is of approx. 1,500 words, covering approx. a dozen Asian countries.\n* [http://i1103.photobucket.com/albums/g468/chinarail1/Book-Cover_zpsa6c1e53f.jpg Woosung Road - the story of China's First Railway] By Peter Crush, published in Hong Kong 1999.\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090430114355/http://cars.rails.com.cn/ China Academy of Railway Sciences]\n\n{{-}}\n{{Asia in topic|History of rail transport in}}\n{{Transport in China}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of Rail Transport In China}}\n[[Category:History of rail transport in China| ]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1902-04 \u2192 1902\u201304 (4)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_rail_transport_in_China"}
{"title_page": "Is Paris Burning? (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1966 film}}\n{{other uses|Is Paris Burning? (disambiguation)|Paris Is Burning (disambiguation)}}\n{{more citations needed|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Is Paris Burning?\n| image          = Paris1324.jpg\n| caption        = American theatrical poster\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Orson Welles]]\n* [[Jean-Paul Belmondo]]\n* [[Alain Delon]]\n* [[Kirk Douglas]]\n* [[Gert Frobe]]\n* [[Bruno Cremer]]\n* [[Pierre Vaneck]]\n* [[Leslie Caron]]\n* [[Glenn Ford]]\n* [[Anthony Perkins]]\n* [[Jean-Pierre Cassel]]\n}}\n| director       = [[Ren\u00e9 Cl\u00e9ment]]\n| producer       = Paul Graetz\n| writer         = {{ubl|[[Gore Vidal]]|[[Francis Ford Coppola]]|[[Jean Aurenche]]|[[Pierre Bost]]|Claude Brul\u00e9}}\n| music          = [[Maurice Jarre]]\n| cinematography = [[Marcel Grignon]]\n| editing        = [[Robert Lawrence (film editor)|Robert Lawrence]]\n| studio         = {{ubl|Marianne Productions|Transcontinental Films}}\n| distributor    = [[Paramount Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1966|10|26|France|1966|11|10|U.S.|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 173 minutes\n| country        = {{ubl|France|United States}}\n| gross          = $37.1 million<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpbox-office.com/fichfilm.php?id=9165|title=Paris br\u00fble-t-il ? (1966)- JPBox-Office|first=|last=JP|website=www.jpbox-office.com}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Is Paris Burning?''''' ({{lang-fr|'''Paris br\u00fble-t-il ?'''}}) is a 1966 French-American [[Epic film|epic]] [[Historical drama|historical]] [[war film]] about the [[liberation of Paris]] in August 1944 by the [[French Resistance]] and the [[Free French Forces]] during [[World War II]]. A French-American co-production, it is directed by French filmmaker [[Ren\u00e9 Cl\u00e9ment]], with a screenplay by [[Gore Vidal]], [[Francis Ford Coppola]], [[Jean Aurenche]], [[Pierre Bost]], and Claude Brul\u00e9; adapted from [[Is Paris Burning? (book)|the book of the same title]] by [[Larry Collins (writer)|Larry Collins]] and [[Dominique Lapierre]]. The film stars an international [[ensemble cast]] that includes French ([[Jean-Paul Belmondo]], [[Alain Delon]], [[Bruno Cremer]], [[Pierre Vaneck]], [[Jean-Pierre Cassel]], [[Leslie Caron]], [[Charles Boyer]], [[Yves Montand]]), American ([[Orson Welles]], [[Kirk Douglas]], [[Glenn Ford]], [[Robert Stack]], [[Anthony Perkins]], [[George Chakiris]]), and German ([[Gert Fr\u00f6be]], [[Hannes Messemer]], [[Ernst Fritz F\u00fcrbringer]], [[Harry Meyen]]) stars.\n\nThe film was released in France on October 26, 1966 and in the United States on November 10, 1966. It received general positive reviews, and was the fourth most popular movie of the year in France in 1966.<ref name=\"delon\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> It was nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography (Black and White)]] and [[Academy Award for Best Production Design|Academy Award for Best Art Direction]] at the [[40th Academy Awards]], and a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Score]].\n\n==Plot==\nShortly after the failed [[20 July plot]] to assassinate him in 1944, [[Adolf Hitler]], appoints ''[[General der Infanterie]]'' [[Dietrich von Choltitz]] as military governor of occupied Paris. Hitler believes Choltitz will obey his order that [[Allies of World War II|the Allies]] should not be allowed to capture Paris without the Germans destroying it completely, similar to the [[planned destruction of Warsaw]].\n\nThe [[French Resistance]] learn that the Allies are not planning to take Paris, but are heading straight to Germany instead. The two factions within the Resistance react to this news differently. The [[Gaullism|Gaullists]] under [[Jacques Chaban-Delmas]] want to wait and see, while the [[French Communist Party|Communists]] under Colonel [[Rol-Tanguy]] want to take action. The Communists force the issue by calling for a general uprising by the citizens of Paris and by occupying important government buildings. The Gaullists go along with this plan of action once it is set in motion.\n\nInitially, Choltitz is intent on following Hitler's order to level the city. After his troops fail to dislodge the Resistance from the [[Prefecture of Police of Paris|Prefecture of Police]], he orders the [[Luftwaffe]] to bomb the building but withdraws the order at the urging of the Swedish Consul, [[Raoul Nordling]], who points out that bombs that miss the Prefecture risk destroying nearby culturally invaluable buildings such as the [[Notre Dame de Paris|Notre Dame Cathedral]]. Choltitz accepts a truce offer from the Resistance (conceived by the Gaullist faction), but the Communists want to keep on fighting, in spite of a lack of ammunition. The truce is, therefore, shortened to one day and the fighting resumes.\n\nAfter learning that the Germans plan to destroy Paris (the [[Eiffel Tower]] and other landmarks are rigged with explosives), a messenger from the Resistance is sent across enemy lines to contact the Americans. He informs the Allies that the Resistance has already taken control of parts of the city and implores them to provide support to prevent the uprising being crushed as was [[Warsaw Uprising|then happening in Warsaw]]. He adds that France would never forgive the destruction of Paris. Afterwards General [[Omar Bradley]] gives the [[2nd Armored Division (France)|2nd Armored Division]] under General [[Philippe Leclerc]] the go-ahead to rush on Paris.\n\nAs the military situation deteriorates, Choltitz delays the order to destroy Paris, believing that Hitler is insane and that the war is lost, making the destruction of Paris a futile gesture. He chooses instead to surrender shortly after the Allies enter the city.\n\nAs the Free French Forces and De Gaulle [[Liberation of Paris|parade down]] the streets of Paris, greeted by cheering crowds, a phone receiver off the hook is seen with a voice in German repeatedly asking \"Is Paris burning?\" From the air, Paris is seen, its buildings still intact and standing, followed by a sudden switch from black and white to color.\n\n==Cast==\n==== French resistance ====\n{{cast listing|\n* [[Jean-Paul Belmondo]] as Yvon \"Pierrelot\" Morandat, [[Free France|Free French]] adjunct\n* [[Alain Delon]] as [[Jacques Chaban-Delmas]], [[Gaullism|Gaullist]] [[general of brigade]]\n* [[Bruno Cremer]] as Col. [[Henri Rol-Tanguy]], commander of ''[[Francs-Tireurs et Partisans]]''\n* [[Charles Boyer]] as Dr. Robert Monod\n* [[Pierre Vaneck]] as Maj. Roger Cocteau-Gallois, ''[[Ceux de la R\u00e9sistance]]''\n* [[Pierre Dux]] as [[Alexandre Parodi|Alexandre \"Cerat\" Parodi]], delegate of [[French Committee of National Liberation]]\n* [[Leslie Caron]] as Fran\u00e7oise Labe\n* [[Jean-Pierre Cassel]] as Lt. Henri Karcher, [[Free French forces]]\n* [[Yves Montand]] as Marcel Bizien, [[Free French forces]]\n* [[Claude Rich]] as Gen. [[Philippe Leclerc]], [[Free French forces]]\n* [[Marie Versini]] as Claire Morandat\n* [[Michel Piccoli]] as [[Edgard Pisani]]\n* [[Claude Dauphin (actor)|Claude Dauphin]] as Col. Edmond Lebel\n* [[Daniel G\u00e9lin]] as Yves Bayet\n* [[Georges Staquet]] as [[Captain (armed forces)|Capt.]] [[Raymond Dronne]], [[Free French forces]]\n* [[Serge Rousseau]] as [[Pierre Georges|Pierre \"Colonel Fabien\" Gorges]], ''[[Francs-Tireurs et Partisans]]''\n* [[Georges G\u00e9ret]] as \"Commander Georges\"\n* [[Jean N\u00e9groni]] as [[Pierre Villon]]\n* [[Michael Lonsdale]] as Jacques Debu-Bridel\n* [[Michel Etcheverry]] as [[Prefect (France)|Prefet]] Charles Luizet\n* [[Sacha Pito\u00ebff]] as [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Joliot-Curie]]\n* [[Simone Signoret]] as a Cafe Proprietress\n* [[Paul Crauchet]] as a [[Curate|Cur\u00e9]]\n* Roger Lumont as Claude \"Jade Amicol\" Arnould\n* F\u00e9lix Marten as Georges Landrieu\n* Tony Taffin as Bernard Lab\u00e9\n* [[Bernard Fresson]] as a [[Free French forces|Free French]] liaison officer\n}}\n==== Allied forces ====\n{{cast listing|\n* [[Orson Welles]] as [[Raoul Nordling]], Swedish consul to France\n* [[Kirk Douglas]] as [[General (United States)|Gen.]] [[George Patton|George S. Patton]]\n* [[Glenn Ford]] as [[Brigadier general (United States)|Brig. Gen.]] [[Omar Bradley]]\n* [[Robert Stack]] as [[Brigadier general (United States)|Brig. Gen.]] [[Edwin L. Sibert|Edwin Sibert]]\n* [[Anthony Perkins]] as Sgt. Warren, infantryman\n* [[E.G. Marshall]] as Powell, intelligence officer\n* Skip Ward as Charlie, infantryman\n* [[Billy Kearns]] as [[Colonel|Col.]] [[Charles R. Codman|Charles Codman]], aide to Gen. Patton\n* [[George Chakiris]] as a Tank Sergeant\n}}\n==== German occupation ====\n{{cast listing|\n* [[Gert Fr\u00f6be]] as ''[[General der Infanterie]]'' [[Dietrich von Choltitz]], military governor of Paris\n* [[Hannes Messemer]] as ''[[Generaloberst]]'' [[Alfred Jodl]]\n* [[Ernst Fritz F\u00fcrbringer]] as ''[[Generalleutnant]]'' [[Hans von Boineburg-Lengsfeld]]\n* [[Jean-Louis Trintignant]] as \"Captain Serge\", [[Vichy]] anti-partisan operative\n* Billy Frick as [[Adolf Hitler]]\n* [[Harry Meyen]] as ''[[Leutnant]]'' von Arnim\n* [[Claus Holm]] as Huhm\n* [[Joachim Hansen (actor)|Joachim Hansen]] as the Commandant of [[Fresnes Prison]]\n* Konrad Georg as ''[[Generalfeldmarschall]]'' [[Walter Model]], commander of [[Army Group North Ukraine]]\n* Peter Jacob as ''[[General of the Infantry (Germany)|General der Infanterie]]'' [[Wilhelm Burgdorf]]\n* [[Wolfgang Preiss]] as ''[[Hauptmann]]'' Ebernach\n* [[G\u00fcnter Meisner]] as the [[Waffen-SS|''Waffen''-SS]] Commandant in [[Pantin]]\n* [[Helmuth Schneider]] as a metro adjunct\n* [[Karl-Otto Alberty]] and Peter Neusser as [[Waffen-SS|''Waffen''-SS]] Officers\n}}\n== Production ==\nThe film is based on the best-selling book by [[Larry Collins (writer)|Larry Collins]] and [[Dominique Lapierre]] and was directed by [[Ren\u00e9 Cl\u00e9ment]], from a screenplay by [[Gore Vidal]] and [[Francis Ford Coppola]].<ref>Paris Officialdom Burning Over Rash of War Pictures\nScheuer, Philip K. Los Angeles Times (1923-Current File) [Los Angeles, Calif] 10 Oct 1965: b3.</ref>\n\nThe film was shot in black and white mainly because, although the French authorities would allow [[Flag of Germany#Nazi Germany and World War II (1933\u201345)|Nazi swastika flags]] to be displayed on public buildings for key shots, they would not permit those flags to be in their original red color; as a result, green swastika flags were used, which photographed adequately in black and white but would have been entirely the wrong color.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}} However, the closing credits feature aerial shots of Paris in color.\n\nThe production was filmed in 180 sites throughout Paris; including [[Rue de la Huchette]], [[Place des Vosges]], [[Les Invalides]], [[Place de la Concorde]], [[Notre-Dame de Paris|Notre-Dame]], the [[Latin Quarter, Paris|Latin Quarter]], and [[Mus\u00e9e Carnavalet]]. According to screenwriter [[Francis Ford Coppola]], the film's production was strictly controlled by [[Charles de Gaulle]]. The latter would only permit location filming in Paris (which was, of course, crucial) if his rules were obeyed to the letter. In particular, he was anxious to minimize the part played in the Liberation by the French Communist Party; it was, said Coppola, blatant political censorship.\n\nClaude Rich plays two parts: General [[Philippe Leclerc de Hauteclocque|Leclerc]], with a moustache, and Lt. Pierre de la Fouchardi\u00e8re, without a moustache.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}} He is credited at the end only with the part of Leclerc. His role as the young lieutenant is not by chance: Claude Rich, as a teenager, was watching soldiers in the street when the real-life Pierre de la Fouchardi\u00e8re called him into a building to protect him.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}} Actor [[Orson Welles]] repeatedly clashed with director [[Ren\u00e9 Cl\u00e9ment]], refusing to speak directly to whom despite being fluent in French. Reportedly, Welles was upset that Clement had been given such a large budget for a project, while he had been struggling to find financing for his projects.\n\nAs the film had a predominately French cast, all sequences featuring French and German actors were filmed in their native French and German languages respectively, which was then dubbed into English, while all the sequences with the American actors (including Orson Welles) were filmed in English.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}} Separate French and English-language dubs were produced for their respective territories.\n\n== Music ==\nThe score was composed by [[Maurice Jarre]]. Jarre's music for \"The Paris Waltz\" had words added later by Maurice Vidalin and became a patriotic anthem sung by [[Mireille Mathieu]] under the title ''Paris en col\u00e8re''.\n\n==Reception==\nThe film was the fourth most popular movie of the year in France in 1966.<ref name=\"delon\">[https://translate.google.com/translate?anno=2&depth=1&rurl=translate.google.com.au&sl=fr&tl=en&u=http://www.boxofficestory.com/box-office-charles-bronson-c22551631/11 Box office information for Alain Delon films] at Box Office Story</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://translate.google.com/translate?sl=fr&tl=en&u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.boxofficestory.com%2Fbox-office-alain-delon-c22669761%2F20&sandbox=1|title=French Box Office 1966|website=Box Office Story}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nThe film was nominated for two [[Academy Awards]]:<ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite web |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/25423/Is-Paris-Burning-/awards |title=NY Times: Is Paris Burning? |accessdate=26 December 2008|work=New York Times}}</ref>\n* [[Academy Award for Best Production Design|Best Art Direction]] ([[Willy Holt]], [[Marc Fr\u00e9d\u00e9rix]], and [[Pierre Guffroy]])\n* [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]] ([[Marcel Grignon]])\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe film was spoofed in ''[[Mad (magazine)|Mad]]'' magazine, in the September 1967 issue (#113), under the title \"Is Paris Boring?\"<ref name=\"autogenerated13\">{{cite web|url=http://madcoversite.com/mad113.html|title=Doug Gilford's Mad Cover Site - Mad #113|website=madcoversite.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[Larry Collins (writer)|Larry Collins]] and [[Dominique Lapierre]], ''Is Paris Burning?'', New York:  Pocket Books, 1965.\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0060814}}\n* [http://www.lefilmguide.com/review/paris-brule-t-il-1966.html ''Is Paris Burning?'']{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} at Le Film Guide\n\n{{Operation Overlord}}\n{{Ren\u00e9 Cl\u00e9ment}}\n{{Gore Vidal}}\n{{Francis Ford Coppola}}\n\n[[Category:1966 films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:English-language French films]]\n[[Category:Films about the French Resistance]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Ren\u00e9 Cl\u00e9ment]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1944]]\n[[Category:Films set in Paris]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Paris]]\n[[Category:French epic films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:French war films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Jean Aurenche]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Pierre Bost]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Francis Ford Coppola]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Gore Vidal]]\n[[Category:War epic films]]\n[[Category:Western Front of World War II films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Maurice Jarre]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Adolf Hitler]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of George S. Patton]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1966 film}}\n{{other uses|Is Paris Burning? (disambiguation)|Paris Is Burning (disambiguation)}}\n{{more citations needed|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Is Paris Burning?\n| image          = Paris1324.jpg\n| caption        = American theatrical poster\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Orson Welles]]\n* [[Jean-Paul Belmondo]]\n* [[Alain Delon]]\n* [[Kirk Douglas]]\n* [[Gert Frobe]]\n* [[Bruno Cremer]]\n* [[Pierre Vaneck]]\n* [[Leslie Caron]]\n* [[Glenn Ford]]\n* [[Anthony Perkins]]\n* [[Jean-Pierre Cassel]]\n}}\n| director       = [[Ren\u00e9 Cl\u00e9ment]]\n| producer       = Paul Graetz\n| writer         = {{ubl|[[Gore Vidal]]|[[Francis Ford Coppola]]|[[Jean Aurenche]]|[[Pierre Bost]]|Claude Brul\u00e9}}\n| music          = [[Maurice Jarre]]\n| cinematography = [[Marcel Grignon]]\n| editing        = [[Robert Lawrence (film editor)|Robert Lawrence]]\n| studio         = {{ubl|Marianne Productions|Transcontinental Films}}\n| distributor    = [[Paramount Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1966|10|26|France|1966|11|10|U.S.|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 173 minutes\n| country        = {{ubl|France|United States}}\n| gross          = $37.1 million<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpbox-office.com/fichfilm.php?id=9165|title=Paris br\u00fble-t-il ? (1966)- JPBox-Office|first=|last=JP|website=www.jpbox-office.com}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Is Paris Burning?''''' ({{lang-fr|'''Paris br\u00fble-t-il ?'''}}) is a 1966 [[Epic film|epic]] [[Historical film|historical]] [[war film]] about the [[liberation of Paris]] in August 1944 by the [[French Resistance]] and the [[Free French Forces]] during [[World War II]]. A French-American co-production, it is directed by French filmmaker [[Ren\u00e9 Cl\u00e9ment]], with a screenplay by [[Gore Vidal]], [[Francis Ford Coppola]], [[Jean Aurenche]], [[Pierre Bost]], and Claude Brul\u00e9; adapted from [[Is Paris Burning? (book)|the book of the same title]] by [[Larry Collins (writer)|Larry Collins]] and [[Dominique Lapierre]]. The film stars an international [[ensemble cast]] that includes French ([[Jean-Paul Belmondo]], [[Alain Delon]], [[Bruno Cremer]], [[Pierre Vaneck]], [[Jean-Pierre Cassel]], [[Leslie Caron]], [[Charles Boyer]], [[Yves Montand]]), American ([[Orson Welles]], [[Kirk Douglas]], [[Glenn Ford]], [[Robert Stack]], [[Anthony Perkins]], [[George Chakiris]]), and German ([[Gert Fr\u00f6be]], [[Hannes Messemer]], [[Ernst Fritz F\u00fcrbringer]], [[Harry Meyen]]) stars.\n\nThe film was released in France on October 26, 1966 and in the United States on November 10, 1966. It received general positive reviews, and was the fourth most popular movie of the year in France in 1966.<ref name=\"delon\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> It was nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography (Black and White)]] and [[Academy Award for Best Production Design|Academy Award for Best Art Direction]] at the [[40th Academy Awards]], and a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Score]].\n\n==Plot==\nShortly after the failed [[20 July plot]] to assassinate him in 1944, [[Adolf Hitler]], appoints ''[[General der Infanterie]]'' [[Dietrich von Choltitz]] as military governor of occupied Paris. Hitler believes Choltitz will obey his order that [[Allies of World War II|the Allies]] should not be allowed to capture Paris without the Germans destroying it completely, similar to the [[planned destruction of Warsaw]].\n\nThe [[French Resistance]] learn that the Allies are not planning to take Paris, but are heading straight to Germany instead. The two factions within the Resistance react to this news differently. The [[Gaullism|Gaullists]] under [[Jacques Chaban-Delmas]] want to wait and see, while the [[French Communist Party|Communists]] under Colonel [[Rol-Tanguy]] want to take action. The Communists force the issue by calling for a general uprising by the citizens of Paris and by occupying important government buildings. The Gaullists go along with this plan of action once it is set in motion.\n\nInitially, Choltitz is intent on following Hitler's order to level the city. After his troops fail to dislodge the Resistance from the [[Prefecture of Police of Paris|Prefecture of Police]], he orders the [[Luftwaffe]] to bomb the building but withdraws the order at the urging of the Swedish Consul, [[Raoul Nordling]], who points out that bombs that miss the Prefecture risk destroying nearby culturally invaluable buildings such as the [[Notre Dame de Paris|Notre Dame Cathedral]]. Choltitz accepts a truce offer from the Resistance (conceived by the Gaullist faction), but the Communists want to keep on fighting, in spite of a lack of ammunition. The truce is, therefore, shortened to one day and the fighting resumes.\n\nAfter learning that the Germans plan to destroy Paris (the [[Eiffel Tower]] and other landmarks are rigged with explosives), a messenger from the Resistance is sent across enemy lines to contact the Americans. He informs the Allies that the Resistance has already taken control of parts of the city and implores them to provide support to prevent the uprising being crushed as was [[Warsaw Uprising|then happening in Warsaw]]. He adds that France would never forgive the destruction of Paris. Afterwards General [[Omar Bradley]] gives the [[2nd Armored Division (France)|2nd Armored Division]] under General [[Philippe Leclerc]] the go-ahead to rush on Paris.\n\nAs the military situation deteriorates, Choltitz delays the order to destroy Paris, believing that Hitler is insane and that the war is lost, making the destruction of Paris a futile gesture. He chooses instead to surrender shortly after the Allies enter the city.\n\nAs the Free French Forces and De Gaulle [[Liberation of Paris|parade down]] the streets of Paris, greeted by cheering crowds, a phone receiver off the hook is seen with a voice in German repeatedly asking \"Is Paris burning?\" From the air, Paris is seen, its buildings still intact and standing, followed by a sudden switch from black and white to color.\n\n==Cast==\n==== French resistance ====\n{{cast listing|\n* [[Jean-Paul Belmondo]] as Yvon \"Pierrelot\" Morandat, [[Free France|Free French]] adjunct\n* [[Alain Delon]] as [[Jacques Chaban-Delmas]], [[Gaullism|Gaullist]] [[general of brigade]]\n* [[Bruno Cremer]] as Col. [[Henri Rol-Tanguy]], commander of ''[[Francs-Tireurs et Partisans]]''\n* [[Charles Boyer]] as Dr. Robert Monod\n* [[Pierre Vaneck]] as Maj. Roger Cocteau-Gallois, ''[[Ceux de la R\u00e9sistance]]''\n* [[Pierre Dux]] as [[Alexandre Parodi|Alexandre \"Cerat\" Parodi]], delegate of [[French Committee of National Liberation]]\n* [[Leslie Caron]] as Fran\u00e7oise Labe\n* [[Jean-Pierre Cassel]] as Lt. Henri Karcher, [[Free French forces]]\n* [[Yves Montand]] as Marcel Bizien, [[Free French forces]]\n* [[Claude Rich]] as Gen. [[Philippe Leclerc]], [[Free French forces]]\n* [[Marie Versini]] as Claire Morandat\n* [[Michel Piccoli]] as [[Edgard Pisani]]\n* [[Claude Dauphin (actor)|Claude Dauphin]] as Col. Edmond Lebel\n* [[Daniel G\u00e9lin]] as Yves Bayet\n* [[Georges Staquet]] as [[Captain (armed forces)|Capt.]] [[Raymond Dronne]], [[Free French forces]]\n* [[Serge Rousseau]] as [[Pierre Georges|Pierre \"Colonel Fabien\" Gorges]], ''[[Francs-Tireurs et Partisans]]''\n* [[Georges G\u00e9ret]] as \"Commander Georges\"\n* [[Jean N\u00e9groni]] as [[Pierre Villon]]\n* [[Michael Lonsdale]] as Jacques Debu-Bridel\n* [[Michel Etcheverry]] as [[Prefect (France)|Prefet]] Charles Luizet\n* [[Sacha Pito\u00ebff]] as [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Joliot-Curie]]\n* [[Simone Signoret]] as a Cafe Proprietress\n* [[Paul Crauchet]] as a [[Curate|Cur\u00e9]]\n* Roger Lumont as Claude \"Jade Amicol\" Arnould\n* F\u00e9lix Marten as Georges Landrieu\n* Tony Taffin as Bernard Lab\u00e9\n* [[Bernard Fresson]] as a [[Free French forces|Free French]] liaison officer\n}}\n==== Allied forces ====\n{{cast listing|\n* [[Orson Welles]] as [[Raoul Nordling]], Swedish consul to France\n* [[Kirk Douglas]] as [[General (United States)|Gen.]] [[George Patton|George S. Patton]]\n* [[Glenn Ford]] as [[Brigadier general (United States)|Brig. Gen.]] [[Omar Bradley]]\n* [[Robert Stack]] as [[Brigadier general (United States)|Brig. Gen.]] [[Edwin L. Sibert|Edwin Sibert]]\n* [[Anthony Perkins]] as Sgt. Warren, infantryman\n* [[E.G. Marshall]] as Powell, intelligence officer\n* Skip Ward as Charlie, infantryman\n* [[Billy Kearns]] as [[Colonel|Col.]] [[Charles R. Codman|Charles Codman]], aide to Gen. Patton\n* [[George Chakiris]] as a Tank Sergeant\n}}\n==== German occupation ====\n{{cast listing|\n* [[Gert Fr\u00f6be]] as ''[[General der Infanterie]]'' [[Dietrich von Choltitz]], military governor of Paris\n* [[Hannes Messemer]] as ''[[Generaloberst]]'' [[Alfred Jodl]]\n* [[Ernst Fritz F\u00fcrbringer]] as ''[[Generalleutnant]]'' [[Hans von Boineburg-Lengsfeld]]\n* [[Jean-Louis Trintignant]] as \"Captain Serge\", [[Vichy]] anti-partisan operative\n* Billy Frick as [[Adolf Hitler]]\n* [[Harry Meyen]] as ''[[Leutnant]]'' von Arnim\n* [[Claus Holm]] as Huhm\n* [[Joachim Hansen (actor)|Joachim Hansen]] as the Commandant of [[Fresnes Prison]]\n* Konrad Georg as ''[[Generalfeldmarschall]]'' [[Walter Model]], commander of [[Army Group North Ukraine]]\n* Peter Jacob as ''[[General of the Infantry (Germany)|General der Infanterie]]'' [[Wilhelm Burgdorf]]\n* [[Wolfgang Preiss]] as ''[[Hauptmann]]'' Ebernach\n* [[G\u00fcnter Meisner]] as the [[Waffen-SS|''Waffen''-SS]] Commandant in [[Pantin]]\n* [[Helmuth Schneider]] as a metro adjunct\n* [[Karl-Otto Alberty]] and Peter Neusser as [[Waffen-SS|''Waffen''-SS]] Officers\n}}\n== Production ==\nThe film is based on the best-selling book by [[Larry Collins (writer)|Larry Collins]] and [[Dominique Lapierre]] and was directed by [[Ren\u00e9 Cl\u00e9ment]], from a screenplay by [[Gore Vidal]] and [[Francis Ford Coppola]].<ref>Paris Officialdom Burning Over Rash of War Pictures\nScheuer, Philip K. Los Angeles Times (1923-Current File) [Los Angeles, Calif] 10 Oct 1965: b3.</ref>\n\nThe film was shot in black and white mainly because, although the French authorities would allow [[Flag of Germany#Nazi Germany and World War II (1933\u201345)|Nazi swastika flags]] to be displayed on public buildings for key shots, they would not permit those flags to be in their original red color; as a result, green swastika flags were used, which photographed adequately in black and white but would have been entirely the wrong color.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}} However, the closing credits feature aerial shots of Paris in color.\n\nThe production was filmed in 180 sites throughout Paris; including [[Rue de la Huchette]], [[Place des Vosges]], [[Les Invalides]], [[Place de la Concorde]], [[Notre-Dame de Paris|Notre-Dame]], the [[Latin Quarter, Paris|Latin Quarter]], and [[Mus\u00e9e Carnavalet]]. According to screenwriter [[Francis Ford Coppola]], the film's production was strictly controlled by [[Charles de Gaulle]]. The latter would only permit location filming in Paris (which was, of course, crucial) if his rules were obeyed to the letter. In particular, he was anxious to minimize the part played in the Liberation by the French Communist Party; it was, said Coppola, blatant political censorship.\n\nClaude Rich plays two parts: General [[Philippe Leclerc de Hauteclocque|Leclerc]], with a moustache, and Lt. Pierre de la Fouchardi\u00e8re, without a moustache.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}} He is credited at the end only with the part of Leclerc. His role as the young lieutenant is not by chance: Claude Rich, as a teenager, was watching soldiers in the street when the real-life Pierre de la Fouchardi\u00e8re called him into a building to protect him.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}} Actor [[Orson Welles]] repeatedly clashed with director [[Ren\u00e9 Cl\u00e9ment]], refusing to speak directly to whom despite being fluent in French. Reportedly, Welles was upset that Clement had been given such a large budget for a project, while he had been struggling to find financing for his projects.\n\nAs the film had a predominately French cast, all sequences featuring French and German actors were filmed in their native French and German languages respectively, which was then dubbed into English, while all the sequences with the American actors (including Orson Welles) were filmed in English.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}} Separate French and English-language dubs were produced for their respective territories.\n\n== Music ==\nThe score was composed by [[Maurice Jarre]]. Jarre's music for \"The Paris Waltz\" had words added later by Maurice Vidalin and became a patriotic anthem sung by [[Mireille Mathieu]] under the title ''Paris en col\u00e8re''.\n\n==Reception==\nThe film was the fourth most popular movie of the year in France in 1966.<ref name=\"delon\">[https://translate.google.com/translate?anno=2&depth=1&rurl=translate.google.com.au&sl=fr&tl=en&u=http://www.boxofficestory.com/box-office-charles-bronson-c22551631/11 Box office information for Alain Delon films] at Box Office Story</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://translate.google.com/translate?sl=fr&tl=en&u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.boxofficestory.com%2Fbox-office-alain-delon-c22669761%2F20&sandbox=1|title=French Box Office 1966|website=Box Office Story}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nThe film was nominated for two [[Academy Awards]]:<ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite web |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/25423/Is-Paris-Burning-/awards |title=NY Times: Is Paris Burning? |accessdate=26 December 2008|work=New York Times}}</ref>\n* [[Academy Award for Best Production Design|Best Art Direction]] ([[Willy Holt]], [[Marc Fr\u00e9d\u00e9rix]], and [[Pierre Guffroy]])\n* [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]] ([[Marcel Grignon]])\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe film was spoofed in ''[[Mad (magazine)|Mad]]'' magazine, in the September 1967 issue (#113), under the title \"Is Paris Boring?\"<ref name=\"autogenerated13\">{{cite web|url=http://madcoversite.com/mad113.html|title=Doug Gilford's Mad Cover Site - Mad #113|website=madcoversite.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[Larry Collins (writer)|Larry Collins]] and [[Dominique Lapierre]], ''Is Paris Burning?'', New York:  Pocket Books, 1965.\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0060814}}\n* [http://www.lefilmguide.com/review/paris-brule-t-il-1966.html ''Is Paris Burning?'']{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} at Le Film Guide\n\n{{Operation Overlord}}\n{{Ren\u00e9 Cl\u00e9ment}}\n{{Gore Vidal}}\n{{Francis Ford Coppola}}\n\n[[Category:1966 films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:English-language French films]]\n[[Category:Films about the French Resistance]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Ren\u00e9 Cl\u00e9ment]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1944]]\n[[Category:Films set in Paris]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Paris]]\n[[Category:French epic films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:French war films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Jean Aurenche]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Pierre Bost]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Francis Ford Coppola]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Gore Vidal]]\n[[Category:War epic films]]\n[[Category:Western Front of World War II films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Maurice Jarre]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Adolf Hitler]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of George S. Patton]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Is_Paris_Burning%3F_(film)"}
{"title_page": "California State Polytechnic University, Pomona", "text_new": "{{About||the liberal arts college in Claremont, California|Pomona College|Cal Poly San Luis Obispo in San Luis Obispo, California|California Polytechnic State University}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name = California State Polytechnic University, Pomona\n|image_name = Cal Poly Seal.svg\n|image_size = 150px\n|motto = Learn By Doing<ref>{{cite web |title=Undergraduate Program |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~sci/computer-science/undergraduate-program/index.shtml |publisher=[[Cal Poly Pomona]] |accessdate=20 March 2019}}</ref>\n|established = 1938 (as Cal Poly Voorhis Unit in [[San Dimas, California]])<ref name=\"Tracing\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cpp.edu/~library/specialcollections/history/tracing.html |title=Tracing Cal Poly's roots |work=Cal Poly Pomona University Library |accessdate=February 28, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100601164351/http://www.cpp.edu/~library/specialcollections/history/tracing.html |archivedate=June 1, 2010 }}</ref>\n|type = [[Public university|Public]]<br />[[State University|State]]<br />[[Institute of Technology (United States)#Polytechnic universities|Polytechnic]]\n| endowment = $101.6 million (2019)<ref name=NACUBO>As of June 30, 2019. {{cite web |url=https://www.nacubo.org/-/media/Nacubo/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2019-NTSE-Endowment-Market-Values--FINAL-January-30-2020.ashx|title=U.S. and Canadian Institutions Listed by Fiscal Year (FY) 2019 Endowment Market Value and Change in Endowment Market Value from FY 2018 to FY 2019 |publisher=National Association of College and University Business Officers and TIAA |access-date=February 3, 2020}}</ref>\n|faculty = 1,330 (Fall 2017)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cpp.edu/~arar/campus-data/FTES/FTE-FacultyWithStatusDetail/FTE-FacultyWithStatusDetailTenured_Tenure-TrackandTemporaryFacultyFall2017.pdf |title=FALL 2017 FTE-Faculty with Status Detail: Tenued/Tenure-Track and Temporary Faculty |publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona |accessdate=January 17, 2018}}</ref>\n|president = [[Soraya M. Coley]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cpp.edu/~president/|title=Welcome to Cal Poly Pomona|publisher=Office of the President at Cal Poly Pomona |accessdate=January 6, 2014}}</ref>\n|provost = Sylvia A. Alva<ref>{{cite web|title=Office of the Provost|url=http://academic.cpp.edu/academic/|publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona|accessdate=May 13, 2010}}</ref>\n|students = 27,914 (Fall 2019)<ref name=Enrollment>{{cite web |url=http://asd.calstate.edu/dashboard/enrollment-live.html |title=Fall Term Student Enrollment |publisher=The California State University Institutional Research and Analyses |access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n|undergrad = 26,451 (Fall 2019)<ref name=Enrollment/>\n|postgrad = 1,463 (Fall 2019)<ref name=Enrollment/>\n|city = [[Pomona, California|Pomona]]\n|state = [[California]]\n|country = United States\n|coor = {{Coord|34|03|23|N|117|49|18|W|type:edu_region:US-CA|display=inline,title}}\n|campus = Suburban, {{convert|1438|acre|ha}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Cal Poly Pomona |url=https://www2.calstate.edu/attend/campuses/pomona |website=CalState.edu |accessdate=24 July 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170807115110/https://www2.calstate.edu/attend/campuses/pomona|archivedate=August 7, 2017}}</ref>\n|colors = [[Green]], [[Gold (color)|Gold]], and [[Blue]]<ref name=\"Color\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cpp.edu/~brand/ |title=University Brand: A Bold New Look |publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona |accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref><br />{{color box|#198844}}&nbsp;{{color box|#ffc300}}&nbsp;{{color box|#0E426A}}\n|mascot = Billy Bronco<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cpp.edu/~ne/bronco.shtml|title=Get the Bronco Spirit!|publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona|accessdate=November 14, 2008|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150302164040/http://www.cpp.edu/~ne/bronco.shtml|archivedate=March 2, 2015}}</ref>\n|nickname = [[Cal Poly Pomona Broncos|Broncos]]\n|athletics = [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[NCAA Division II|Division II]] \u2013 [[California Collegiate Athletic Association|CCAA]]\n|affiliations = *[[California State University]] (CSU)\n*[[Western Association of Schools and Colleges]] (WASC)\n*[[American Association of State Colleges and Universities]] (AASCU)\n|website = {{url|www.cpp.edu}}\n|logo = Logo of California State Polytechnic University, Pomona.svg\n|logo_size = 250\n}}\n\n'''California State Polytechnic University, Pomona''' ('''Cal Poly Pomona''', '''CPP''', or '''Cal Poly'''<ref group=\"Note\">\"Cal Poly\" may also refer to [[California Polytechnic State University]] in San Luis Obispo; however, the term may also use the term to refer to the Pomona campus. See the ''[[California State Polytechnic University, Pomona#Name|name]]'' section of this article for more information.</ref>) is a [[Public university|public]] [[Institute of Technology (United States)#Polytechnic universities|polytechnic university]] in [[Pomona, California]]. It is one of [[Cal Poly (disambiguation)|two polytechnic universities]] in the [[California State University]] system.\n\nCal Poly Pomona began as the southern campus of the California Polytechnic School (today known as [[California Polytechnic State University|Cal Poly San Luis Obispo]]) in 1938 when the '''Voorhis School for Boys''' and its adjacent farm in the city of [[San Dimas, California|San Dimas]] were donated by Charles Voorhis and his son [[Jerry Voorhis]]. Cal Poly's southern campus grew further in 1949 when the '''University of California, W.K. Kellogg Institute''' also known as '''W.K. Kellogg Institute of Animal Husbandry\u2014University of California, Pomona''' in the neighboring city of Pomona, which had belonged to [[Will Keith Kellogg]], was acquired from the [[University of California]]. Cal Poly Pomona, then known as '''Cal Poly Kellogg-Voorhis''', and Cal Poly San Luis Obispo continued operations under a unified administrative control until they became independent from one another in 1966.\n\nCal Poly Pomona currently offers [[bachelor's degrees]] in 94 majors, 39 [[master's degrees]], 13 [[teaching credential]]s and a doctorate [[California State Polytechnic University, Pomona academics|across 9 distinct academic colleges]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://degrees.calstate.edu/csu_degree_search2?noCache=607:1358369036|title=CSU Degrees|website=CSU Degrees|accessdate=October 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://degrees.calstate.edu/uploads/55/64/5564d4b6ec1584227ca2d1054c759f0f/Credential-Programs-08212012.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=February 14, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150424234126/http://degrees.calstate.edu/uploads/55/64/5564d4b6ec1584227ca2d1054c759f0f/Credential-Programs-08212012.pdf |archivedate=April 24, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to Doctoral Studies |url=http://www.cpp.edu/~education/doctoral/index.shtml|publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona|accessdate=October 21, 2013}}</ref> The university is one among a small group of [[Institute of Technology (United States)#Polytechnic universities|polytechnic universities in the United States]] which tend to be primarily devoted to the instruction of technical arts and applied sciences.\n\nIts sports teams are known as the [[Cal Poly Pomona Broncos]] and play in the [[NCAA Division II]] as part of the [[California Collegiate Athletic Association]] (CCAA). The Broncos sponsor 10 varsity sports and have won 14 NCAA national championships. Current and former Cal Poly Pomona athletes have won 7 Olympic medals ([[List of American universities with Olympic medals|3 gold, 1 silver, and 3 bronze]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cpp.edu/~75th/newsletter/athletics.shtml|title=Top 12 Athletics Achievements|website=www.cpp.edu|language=en|access-date=February 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203075524/https://www.cpp.edu/~75th/newsletter/athletics.shtml|archive-date=February 3, 2017 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{Dablink|See also: [[California Polytechnic State University#History|History of the California Polytechnic in San Luis Obispo, California]].<ref group=Note>From 1938 to 1966 the California Polytechnic (Cal Poly) intermittently operated as one institution in up to three different locations: Pomona, San Dimas and San Luis Obispo.</ref>}}\n{{Quote box |quote = Let it be the [[Cornell University|Cornell]] of the Pacific... where any person can find instruction in any study. |source = <small>Myron Angel, founder of the California Polytechnic School, San Luis Obispo, CA. January 7, 1899.</small><ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=15.}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Angel|1907|p=45.}}</ref> |align = right |width = 300px |fontsize = 90% |bgcolor = #e3e5e5 |quoted = 1}}\n\n[[File:W.K. Kellogg with Antez (1929).PNG|thumb|right|Cal Poly at Pomona stands on the former Arabian horse ranch of cereal magnate [[Will Keith Kellogg|W.K. Kellogg]].]]\n\nEvents leading to the foundation of present-day Cal Poly at Pomona began with the ending of the Voorhis School for Boys in [[San Dimas, California]] and its acquisition by the [[San Luis Obispo, California|San Luis Obispo]]-based California Polytechnic School in 1938.<ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=41.}}</ref><ref name=\"Voorhis\">{{cite web |last1=Strauss |first1=Rob |title=The Finding Aid of the Voorhis Family Collection 0090 |url=https://oac.cdlib.org/findaid/ark:/13030/c8t72q52/entire_text/ |website=Online Archive of California (OAC) |publisher=[[California Digital Library]] |accessdate=24 July 2019 |date=February 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe California Polytechnic School was founded as a [[Vocational education in the United States|vocational]] high school when California Governor [[Henry Gage]] signed the Polytechnic School Bill on March 8, 1901 after its drafting by school founder Myron Angel.<ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=18.}}</ref> Voorhis School, on the other hand, had been established in 1928 as a private vocational school which provided [[Primary education|elementary schooling]] for underprivileged boys and operated under the Christian religious principle, \"education coupled with the Kingdom of God\".<ref name=\"Pflueger 1999 44\">{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=44.}}</ref><ref name=\"Voorhis\" /> Its founder Charles B. Voorhis and [[Head teacher|headmaster]] [[Jerry Voorhis]] maintained the school opened throughout the worst years of the [[Great Depression]] but persistent economic pressures forced them to transfer control to [[Cal Poly San Luis Obispo]] in 1938.<ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=45.}}</ref><ref name=\"Voorhis\" />\n\nVoorhis School became the Cal Poly-Voorhis Unit and its educational offerings were raised to the same level as Cal Poly San Luis Obispo's, then a two-year college.<ref name=\"Cal Poly San Luis Obispo\">{{cite web |url= http://www.alumni.calpoly.edu/alumniinfo/university-history.html |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080616082843/http://www.alumni.calpoly.edu/alumniinfo/university-history.html |archivedate=June 16, 2008 |title= University History |publisher=[[California Polytechnic State University]] | accessdate=February 4, 2010}}</ref> The horticulture program was moved to the new satellite campus and the two units operated as one institution spanning two locations under the leadership of president Julian McPhee.<ref name=\"Campus History, Cal Poly San Dimas?\">{{cite web| url=http://www.cpp.edu/~library/specialcollections/history/sandimas.html| title=Cal Poly San Dimas?| first=Allen| last=Ferreira| year=1985| publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona| accessdate=January 31, 2010| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402202643/http://www.cpp.edu/~library/specialcollections/history/sandimas.html| archive-date=April 2, 2015| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Cal Poly Pomona Winter.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Aerial view of campus]]\n\nDuring World War II most of the student body was called to active military duty; enrollment declined and the campus closed in 1943.<ref name=\"Campus History, Cal Poly San Dimas?\"/><ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=51.}}</ref> Reopening after the war, Cal Poly-Voorhis Unit operated in San Dimas until 1956 when it moved to [[Will Keith Kellogg]]\u2019s former [[Ranch|horse ranch]] in the neighboring city of [[Pomona, California]].<ref name=\"CPP History\">{{cite web | title= Heritage and History at Cal Poly Pomona | url= http://www.cpp.edu/cpp_heritage.php | url-status= dead| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20121204135153/http://www.csupomona.edu/cpp_heritage.php | archivedate= December 4, 2012 | publisher= California State Polytechnic University, Pomona | accessdate= November 11, 2010 }}</ref> Acknowledging its Kellogg legacy, Cal Poly-Voorhis Unit changed its name to Cal Poly Kellogg-Voorhis Unit and offered six programs in agriculture.<ref name=\"CPP History\" /> The inaugural class of 1957 at the new campus consisted of 57 students graduating with bachelor\u2019s degrees in a ceremony held at the Rose Garden in Pomona and religious services at Voorhis Chapel in San Dimas.<ref name=\"Catalog\">{{cite web | title= California State Polytechnic University, Pomona \u2013 Historical Development | url= http://www.cpp.edu/~academic/catalog/gen_info/Univ_Admin.pdf| publisher= California State Polytechnic University, Pomona | format=PDF | accessdate=November 14, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=103.}}</ref> Also in 1957, Cal Poly Kellogg-Voorhis introduced the [[Cal Poly Pomona College of Engineering|College of Engineering]], the second academic unit after the [[Cal Poly Pomona College of Agriculture|College of Agriculture]].<ref name=\"cpp.edu\">{{Citation | title = University Ranks Fifth in West, Engineering Program Ninth in Nation by U.S. News & World Report | newspaper = PolyTrends | page = 2 | year = 2003 | url = http://www.cpp.edu/~advancement/publications/polytrends_fall03.pdf | accessdate = January 31, 2010}}</ref> The [[California Master Plan for Higher Education]] added the two Cal Poly campuses to the new California State College system in 1961 and Cal Poly Kellogg-Voorhis Unit opened its doors for the first time to 329 female students.<ref name=\"CPP History\" /> President McPhee retired in 1966, and Cal Poly split into two different and independent universities. The partnership between the two campuses remains with their involvement in the annual [[Cal Poly Universities Rose Float]].<ref name=\"Cal Poly San Luis Obispo\" /><ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|pp=133\u2013134.}}</ref>\n\nTo better reflect its new ties to the California State College system, Cal Poly Kellogg-Voorhis changed its name to \"California State Polytechnic College, Kellogg-Voorhis\" in 1966 and became the 16th campus to officially join the CSC system.<ref name=\"CPP History\" /> Robert C. Kramer assumed presidency of the independent campus in 1966 (second overall as the university recognizes McPhee as its first) and California State Polytechnic College, Kellogg-Voorhis finally adopted its present-day name California State Polytechnic University, Pomona on June 1, 1972.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cpp.edu/~library/specialcollections/oralhistory/ |title=Voices From Our Past \u2013 Cal Poly Pomona Oral History |publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona |date=March 18, 2009 |accessdate=April 30, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701131456/http://www.cpp.edu/~library/specialcollections/oralhistory/ |archive-date=July 1, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calstate.edu/pa/info/milestones.shtml |title=CSU &#124; Public Affairs &#124; Historic Milestones |publisher=[[California State University]] |date=March 18, 2009 |accessdate=April 30, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, Cal Poly Pomona received criticism when it planned to grant an honorary degree to [[Robert Mugabe]].  Mugabe's negative humanitarian record as president of [[Zimbabwe]] lead to protests from staff, faculty and students, ultimately forcing the university to rescind the award.<ref>{{cite news | title= Cal Poly Pomona Chief Is Focus of Campus Contention\n| url= http://articles.latimes.com/1998/jun/15/local/me-60140|work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=September 2, 2008 | first=Kenneth R. | last=Weiss | date=June 15, 1998}}</ref>\n\nCal Poly Pomona underwent further growth in the late 20th and early 21st centuries, with the construction of the [[CLA Building]] (slated for demolition),<ref name=\"CLA Building\">{{cite web |last1=Ravitz |first1=Anya |title=Predock Defends Doomed Pomona Tower |url=https://archpaper.com/2010/10/predock-defends-doomed-pomona-tower/ |website=ArchPaper.com |publisher=[[The Architect's Newspaper]] |accessdate=26 July 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726182615/https://archpaper.com/2010/10/predock-defends-doomed-pomona-tower/ |archivedate=26 July 2019 |date=October 27, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thepolypost.com/news/2019/04/30/cla-in-limbo/|title=CLA in limbo|date=2019-04-30|website=The Poly Post|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref> academic facilities, expansion to the [[Cal Poly Pomona University Library]] and the addition of programs such as the [[Lyle Center for Regenerative Studies]], the [[International Polytechnic High School|I-Poly High School]] and the [[U.R. Bronco]] undergraduate research program. Under then-president [[J. Michael Ortiz]], Cal Poly Pomona launched its first comprehensive capital campaign in fall of 2008 to increase its permanent endowment. Nevertheless, the negative economic effects caused by the [[late-2000s recession]] has increased student fees, reduced enrollment availability, eliminated two athletic programs and introduced a mandatory [[furlough]] calendar for most of its employees.<ref>{{cite web|title= CSU Trustees Vote to Raise 2010\u201311 Fees by 5 Percent|url= http://polycentric.cpp.edu/2010/06/csu_trustees_raise_fees_5percent/|work= PolyCentric|accessdate = August 27, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190827140605/http://polycentric.cpp.edu/2010/06/csu_trustees_raise_fees_5percent/|archivedate=August 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title= California State University Officials Outline Enrollment Cuts and Preview 2010\u20132011 Budget | url= http://www.calstate.edu/pa/news/2009/enrollment-budget.shtml| publisher= [[California State University]] |accessdate=September 11, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title= Cal Poly Pomona Forced to Drop Men\u2019s and Women\u2019s Tennis | url= http://www.scta.usta.com/News/steve-2010/CalPoly/| publisher= [[United States Tennis Association]] |accessdate=September 11, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title= Cal State approves student fee increases and furloughs | url= https://www.scpr.org/news/2009/07/21/2604/csu-budget-vote-feature/| publisher= [[KPCC]] |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190920183541/https://www.scpr.org/news/2009/07/21/2604/csu-budget-vote-feature/ |archivedate=September 20, 2019 |accessdate= September 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Name===\n{{Dablink|See also: [[California State University#Campus naming conventions|Campus naming conventions in the CSU]] and [[California Polytechnic State University#Name]].}}\nThe campus' office of public affairs recognizes two official names for the university: \"California State Polytechnic University, Pomona\" and \"Cal Poly Pomona\".<ref name=\"Graphic Standard Manual\">{{cite news| url= http://www.cpp.edu/~publicaffairs/graphics/nomenclature.shtml| title= Identity| publisher= Office of Public Affairs at Cal Poly at Pomona| accessdate= February 1, 2010| url-status= dead| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150120025117/http://www.cpp.edu/~publicaffairs/graphics/nomenclature.shtml| archivedate= January 20, 2015| df= mdy-all}}</ref> However, \"Cal Poly\" has also been used to refer to Cal Poly at Pomona, as both itself and [[California Polytechnic State University]] at [[San Luis Obispo, California]] were one institution spanning two locations from 1938 to 1966.<ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=11.}}</ref> Cal Poly's office of public affairs recommends not to abbreviate the university's name merely as \"Cal Poly\".<ref name=\"Graphic Standard Manual\"/> In the years when the [[University of California]] was in charge of Kellogg's donated estate in Pomona (1932\u20131943), the names \"University of California, W.K. Kellogg Institute\" and \"W.K. Kellogg Institute of Animal Husbandry University of California, Pomona\", came into use to describe the site.<ref>{{Harvnb|Parkinson|2001|p=213.}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Parkinson|2001|p=204.}}</ref> Although Cal Poly Pomona is now part of the [[California State University]], its naming convention does not follow that of most campuses within the system (for example, the CSU campus in San Diego bears the full official name \"[[San Diego State University]]\" and the CSU campus in [[Fullerton, California|Fullerton]] uses the name \"[[California State University, Fullerton]]\").<ref>{{cite web| title=The New SDSU Graphic Identity System| url=http://advancement.sdsu.edu/marcomm/logo/SDSU_User_Manual_1.3.pdf| format=PDF| work=[[San Diego State University]]| page=4| accessdate=March 28, 2011| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110518052139/http://advancement.sdsu.edu/marcomm/logo/SDSU_User_Manual_1.3.pdf| archive-date=May 18, 2011| url-status=dead| df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=Editorial Style| url=http://www.fullerton.edu/identity/downloads/guidelines/editorial-style.pdf| format=PDF| work=[[California State University, Fullerton]]| page=3| accessdate=March 28, 2011| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720024850/http://www.fullerton.edu/identity/downloads/guidelines/editorial-style.pdf| archivedate=July 20, 2011| df=mdy-all}}</ref> Thus, \"Pomona State University\" and \"California State University, Pomona\" are seldom used and not in the university's graphic standard's manual.<ref name=\"Graphic Standard Manual\"/>\n\n===Seals and logos===\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" classes=\"center\">\nFile:The University of California W.K. Kellogg Institute.svg|<center>Former seal used by the university during the [[University of California]] years (1932-1943).</center>\nFile:University Seal of Cal Poly in Pomona, CA (mid-1980s-2017).svg|<center>Former seal used by the university from the mid-1980s to the summer of 2018 </center>\n</gallery>\n\n==Campus==\n{{Location map many\n| Los Angeles\n| float      = right\n| caption    = Cal Poly Pomona is located about 30 miles east of [[Downtown Los Angeles]].<ref name=About>{{cite web|title=About Cal Poly Pomona - A brief m\u00e9lange of history, quick facts, and philosophy|url=http://www.cpp.edu/about.php|publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona|accessdate=April 26, 2013}}</ref>\n| label      = Cal Poly at Pomona\n| position   = right\n| mark       = Green sphere.svg\n| marksize   = 10\n| lat1       = 34.05639\n| long1      = -117.82167\n| label2     = Downtown Los Angeles\n| position2  = left\n| mark2      = Blue sphere.svg\n| marksize2  = 10\n| lat2       = 34.054366\n| long2      = -118.243704\n}}\nCal Poly Pomona is situated in [[Pomona, California|Pomona]], a largely suburban city that is part of the [[Los Angeles metropolitan area]]. The city of Pomona is located in the eastern portion of [[Los Angeles County]] and borders the neighboring [[San Bernardino County|county of San Bernardino]] to the east. The university's {{convert|1725|acre|ha|sp=us}} campus<ref name=\"Physical Cal Poly Pomona\">{{cite web  |url= http://www.cpp.edu/~jskoga/physicalcalpoly/ |title= The Physical Cal Poly Pomona |first= James S. |last= Koga |publisher= California State Polytechnic University, Pomona |accessdate=August 27, 2008}}</ref> make it the second largest in the [[California State University]] system,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aaiep.org/schools/show/189/cal_poly_english_language_institute |title=Cal Poly English Language Institute |publisher=American Association of Intensive English Programs |accessdate=August 22, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101015150343/http://aaiep.org/schools/show/189/cal_poly_english_language_institute |archivedate=October 15, 2010  }}</ref> a figure which includes various facilities scattered throughout [[Southern California]] such as a {{convert|53|acre|ha|adj=on}} ranch in [[Santa Paula, California]], {{convert|25|acre|ha|adj=on}} campus at the former Spadra Landfill (now known as \"Spadra Ranch\"),<ref name=\"Facilities\">{{cite web | url= http://www.cpp.edu/~plantsci/facilities.shtml | title=Department Facilities | publisher= California State Polytechnic University, Pomona| accessdate=September 17, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.lacsd.org/about/solid_waste_facilities/spadra/default.asp | title=Spadra Landfill (Post Closure Activities) | publisher=Sanitation Districts of Los Angeles County | accessdate=March 26, 2011}}</ref> and the [[Neutra VDL Studio and Residences]] in [[Silver Lake, Los Angeles]].  The university is currently negotiating the transfer of the 302 acre Lanterman Developmental Center from the State of California.  The land is to be used for academic purposes and expansion of the Innovation Village and also shared by the [[California Highway Patrol]], the [[California Air Resources Board]] and the [[California Conservation Corps]].  The transfer of the land is part of the Governor's 2015-2016 Proposed Budget.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abgt.assembly.ca.gov/sites/abgt.assembly.ca.gov/files/January%209%202015%20Budget%20Highlights.pdf |title=Budget |date=2015 |website=abgt.assembly.ca.gov |format=PDF |access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref>\n\n[[File:CalPoly Stables.jpg|thumb|right|Old horse stables]]\n\nAlthough part of the [[Los Angeles metropolitan area]], the university is in close proximity to two other large metropolitan and culturally-defined regions, the [[Inland Empire (California)|Inland Empire]] and [[Orange County, California|Orange County]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.wilkinguge.com/research/inland-empire-insights.php| title=Inland Empire Insights| work=Wilkin Guge Marketing| year=2008| accessdate=March 28, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081026015649/http://www.wilkinguge.com/research/inland-empire-insights.php |archivedate=October 26, 2008 }}</ref> The university has a tier 1 area, defined as a geographical admissions region surrounding the campus, roughly bounded by the [[San Gabriel Mountains]] to the north, the city of [[Chino Hills, California|Chino Hills]] to the south, [[Interstate 605]] to the west, and [[Interstate 15]] to the east.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.insidesocal.com/educationnow/2010/02/cal-poly-requiring-certain-fre.html |title= Department Facilities |publisher= [[Los Angeles Newspaper Group]] |accessdate= August 22, 2010 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20121023035806/http://www.insidesocal.com/educationnow/2010/02/cal-poly-requiring-certain-fre.html |archivedate= October 23, 2012 |df= mdy-all }}</ref> Cal Poly Pomona's campus buildings vary in age and style from the [[Mission Revival Style architecture|Mission Revival]] Kellogg Horse Stables and the Kellogg House (suggesting the [[Spanish architecture#Spanish Colonial architecture|Spanish colonial architectural heritage]] of [[Southern California]]) built in the 1920s; the modernist box-like portion of [[California State Polytechnic University, Pomona, Library|the library]] completed in 1969; to contemporary dormitories, engineering, science and library-expansion facilities completed in the early 21st century.{{sfn|CPSUSLO|2001|p=68}}\n\nLeisure and recreational locations include a [[rose garden]] which dates back to the Kellogg horse ranch years; the Kellogg House designed by Los Angeles-based architects Charles Gibbs Adams, [[Myron Hunt]] and Harold Coulson Chambers in the 1920s; and a {{convert|1.3|acre|ha}} [[Japanese garden]] built in 2003 and designed by [[Takeo Uesugi]].<ref name=\"UW Arch. Database\">{{cite web| url= https://digital.lib.washington.edu/architect/structures/3836/| title=Kellogg, W.K., Ranch House, Pomona, CA| publisher=[[University of Washington]]| accessdate=August 22, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.jgarden.org/gardens.asp?ID=642| title=George and Sakaye Aratani Japanese Garden at Cal Poly Pomona| last=Cheetham| first=Robert |publisher=Japanese Garden Research Network, Inc.| accessdate=August 22, 2010}}</ref> Kellogg's House features grounds which were initially landscaped by Charles Gibbs Adams but were later completed by [[Florence Yoch & Lucile Council]].<ref name=\"UW Arch. Database\" /> Cal Poly Pomona's George and Sakaye Aratani Japanese Garden is one among three under management by institutions of higher education in the County of Los Angeles, the others being the [[Earl Burns Miller Japanese Garden]] at [[California State University, Long Beach|Cal State Long Beach]], and the Shinwa-En Garden at [[California State University, Dominguez Hills|Cal State Dominguez Hills]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.la.us.emb-japan.go.jp/e_web/e_m06_29.htm |title=Japanese Gardens in Southern California and Arizona |publisher=Consulate General of Japan in Los Angeles |accessdate=March 31, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711012145/http://www.la.us.emb-japan.go.jp/e_web/e_m06_29.htm |archivedate=July 11, 2011  }}</ref> At the center of the campus and atop Horsehill are the buildings of the [[Collins College of Hospitality Management]] and Kellogg West, a hotel and conference center and home of the student/faculty-run Restaurant at Kellogg Ranch.\n\nAt the northwest part of the campus is the Voorhis [[Nature reserve|Ecological Reserve]], which serves as a {{convert|31|ha|acre}} [[wildlife corridor]] containing [[Coastal Sage Scrub]] and [[Quercus agrifolia|Coast Live Oak]] trees among others.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.cpp.edu/~biology/docs/voorhis.shtml |title=Voorhis Ecological Reserve |publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona}}</ref> Contrasting some of these architecturally prominent facilities, there are various [[portable building]]s on campus which are used to accommodate the growing enrollment of recent decades. Cal Poly Pomona operates the [[International Polytechnic High School]], a college preparatory high school located on campus.\n\nThe letters \"CPP\" made of concrete are located on Colt Hill overlooking the campus. The letters \"CP\" were initially added in 1959, with the second \"P\" added in 2004 to distinguish it from the Cal Poly campus in San Luis Obispo.<ref>{{cite journal |title=The CPP  Letters |journal=Cal Poly Pomona Magazine |date=Spring 2019 |page=3}}</ref>\n\nCal Poly Pomona's dominant landmark is a [[Futurist architecture|futurist-styled]] administrative facility known as the [[CLA Building]] which was designed by [[Antoine Predock]] and opened in 1993. The building's peculiar shape (standing out by a triangular-shaped \"skyroom\" atop its eight-story tower<ref>{{cite web |url=http://californiawatch.org/watchblog/iconic-cal-poly-pomona-building-poses-earthquake-hazard |title=Iconic Cal Poly building poses earthquake hazard |first=Erica |last=Perez |date=March 23, 2010 |publisher=[[California Watch]] |accessdate=August 22, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100726153942/http://californiawatch.org/watchblog/iconic-cal-poly-pomona-building-poses-earthquake-hazard |archive-date=July 26, 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>) has become a symbol of the university; in addition, its close location to film studios based in the Hollywood borough of Los Angeles have prompted its inclusion in motion pictures such as ''[[Gattaca]]'' and ''[[Impostor (2002 film)|Impostor]]''.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Brian |last1=Sease |title=Lights, camera, Broncos: Productions filmed on campus |url=https://thepolypost.com/arts-and-entertainment/2019/01/29/lights-camera-broncos-productions-filmed-on-campus/ |website=thepolypost.com |publisher=[[The Poly Post]] |accessdate=20 September 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190203125029/https://thepolypost.com/arts-and-entertainment/2019/01/29/lights-camera-broncos-productions-filmed-on-campus/ |archivedate=February 3, 2019}}</ref> In 2013, the California State University Board of Trustees voted to demolish the building and replace it with a new academic/faculty complex because of severe seismic risks.<ref name=\"CLA Building\"/>\n\n[[File:Cal Poly Pomona South Campus.png|thumb|Cal Poly Pomona's new South Campus]]\n\nNoted [[Modern architecture|modernist]] architect [[James Pulliam, Architect|James Pulliam]] once served as campus architect and instructor and designed the Bookstore, W. Keith and Janet Kellogg Art Gallery, Interim Design Center (IDC) and Student Union building which architectural historian [[David Gebhard]] regarded as the best building on campus.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/2006/jan/01/local/me-pulliam1 | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Valerie J. | last=Nelson | title=James Pulliam, 80; Architect, Teacher Noted for Modernism | date=January 1, 2006}}</ref>\n\n===Academic and research facilities===\nThe [[W. K. Kellogg Arabian Horse Center]] is an academic and research facility serving one of the 22 terms and conditions to the donation of the Kellogg ranch by maintaining Kellogg's purebred [[Arabian horse]]s and their breeding program. Another academic facility highlighting the Kellogg legacy is the Horse Stables (also known as University Plaza) which contains a small research library specializing in equine studies along with offices for student services and various campus organizations.\n\n[[File:Voorev.jpg|thumb|Cal Poly Pomona's Voorhis Ecological Reserve]]\n\nConceived in 1995 by then university president, Bob H. Suzuki, and initially financed by [[NASA]] and the [[Economic Development Administration]], the Innovation Village is a {{convert|65|acre|ha|adj=on}} public/private partnership research and business facility at the southern edge of the campus. Major tenants include the [[American Red Cross]], [[Southern California Edison]], and the [[NASA]] Commercialization Center.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.innovationvillage.org/generalinfo.aspx|title=General Information|publisher=Innovation Village|accessdate=March 3, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110319014859/http://www.innovationvillage.org/generalinfo.aspx|archivedate=March 19, 2011}}</ref> The project is currently at the halfway mark of building and leasing {{convert|1000000|sqft|m2}} of the projected total building space. Once complete, it is estimated that the project would employ 2000 to 3000 people and provide half a billion dollars of economic benefits to the local, regional and state economies.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.labusinessjournal.com/news/2005/dec/19/innovation-park-puts-cal-poly-pomona-on-biotech/|title=Innovation Park Puts Cal Poly Pomona on Biotech Map|work=[[Los Angeles Business Journal]]|accessdate=March 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Campus sustainability and transportation===\n[[File:Cal Poly Main Quad (Pomona, CA).PNG|thumb|The main [[Quadrangle (architecture)|quad]] at Cal Poly Pomona]]\n\nThe university has actively sought to reduce carbon emissions and energy usage on campus. In November 2007, Cal Poly Pomona became a signatory member of the [[Campus Carbon Neutrality#American College and University Presidents' Climate Commitment|American College & University Presidents Climate Commitment]].<ref>{{cite web| url= http://acupcc.aashe.org/ip/195/ |title= Implementation Profile for California State Polytechnic University-Pomona |date= July 13, 2009 |publisher= [[Campus Carbon Neutrality#The Association for the Advancement of Sustainability in Higher Education|Association for the Advancement of Sustainability in Higher Education]] |accessdate=August 22, 2010}}</ref> Among other things, this committed the university to ensure that within one year, it would purchase or produce at least 15% of the institution's electric consumption from [[Renewable resource|renewable sources]]. The university, along with other members in the CSU, is also a member of the [[California Climate Action Registry]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.climateregistry.org/about/members.html |title= Members |date= December 15, 2009 |publisher= [[California Climate Action Registry]] |accessdate= August 22, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100825080455/http://www.climateregistry.org/about/members.html |archive-date= August 25, 2010 |url-status= dead |df= mdy-all }}</ref> and lists on ''[[The Princeton Review]]'s'' ''Guide to 375 Green Colleges''.<ref>{{cite web|title=286 Green Colleges (Full List) |url=https://www.princetonreview.com/college-rankings/green-guide/green-colleges-by-location|publisher=[[The Princeton Review]] in partnership with the U.S. [[Green Building Council]]|accessdate=November 7, 2017}}</ref> As a part of the campus' Climate Action Plan to reduce its carbon footprint, the campus offers incentive parking for students and faculty participating in its Rideshare program.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cpp.edu/~sustainability/pdf/CPP_CAP_091109.pdf |title=Climate Action Plan |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2019-05-15}}</ref> The carpooling initiative gives users the opportunity to park in reserved spaces located closer to campus buildings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cpp.edu/~parking/rideshare/rideshare-how-to/rideshare-permit.shtml|title=Obtain a Rideshare Parking Permit|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nCal Poly Pomona's institute for sustainability education is the [[Lyle Center for Regenerative Studies]]. The center was built adjacent to an old landfill and conducts research in the areas of sustainable technology and agriculture. As an example of [[Cradle to Cradle Design]], it uses solar-powered dormitories, aquaculture ponds, and organic gardens while providing an environmentally-sustainable housing accommodation for 22 graduate students. In 2010, with the installation of a 210,000&nbsp;kW hours [[Concentrated Photovoltaics|CPV]] system by [[Amonix]], the center became the first [[carbon neutral]] facility in the [[California State University]] system.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lyle Center Goes Carbon Neutral with Amonix Solar Energy Systems |url=http://blogs.calstate.edu/cpdc_sustainability/?p=671 |website=CalState.edu |publisher=[[California State University]] |accessdate=20 September 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150920182408/http://blogs.calstate.edu/cpdc_sustainability/?p=671 |archivedate=September 20, 2015 |date=September 30, 2010}}</ref> The center is part of Agriscapes, a {{convert|40|acre|ha|adj=on}} research project that showcases environmental and agricultural sustainable practices including methods to grow food, conserve water and energy and recycle urban waste. Agriscapes is home of the Farm Store at Kellogg Ranch which sells locally and campus grown foods and products. Cal Poly Pomona campus also contains a rainforest greenhouse, a California [[ethnobotany]] garden, and an aquatic biology center collectively known as BioTrek, which provides environmental education to all academic levels.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cpp.edu/~biotrek/ |title=About BioTrek |publisher= California State Polytechnic University, Pomona |accessdate= March 4, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe entire campus community is served by a free campus shuttle system known as \"Bronco Express\". The shuttle system has 3 lines and is run by the office of Transportation Services.<ref name=\"Transportation\">{{cite web |title=Bronco Express Shuttle |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~transportation/commuting-to-campus/bronco-shuttle.shtml |publisher=Cal Poly Pomona |accessdate=20 September 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920193443/https://www.cpp.edu/~transportation/commuting-to-campus/bronco-shuttle.shtml |archivedate=September 20, 2019}}</ref> In addition, PTS also offers a shuttle service known as \"Metrolink\" which provides both students and faculty a direct connection from the Pomona North and Downtown Pomona [[Metrolink (Southern California)|Metrolink]] stations to the [[CLA Building]].<ref name=\"Transportation\" />\n\n[[Foothill Transit]] lines 190, 194, 195, 289, 480, 482, and 486 serve the campus daily.\n\n===Seismic risks and other challenges of campus development===\nAlthough it's believed that the San Jose Fault runs through campus, and geotechnical investigations have been conducted, there is uncertainty regarding its precise [[Fault (geology)#Fault types|type]] and location. The CLA Building suffers from structural flaws, most notably, water intrusion. In 2005, the university filed a lawsuit against a contractor, for which it was compensated $13.3 million in an out-of-court [[Settlement (litigation)|settlement]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archrecord.construction.com/news/daily/archives/2010/09/100927predock_cla_building.asp|title=Antoine Predock\u2019s CLA Building in California May Be Demolished|last=Hill|first=David|date=September 27, 2010|work=[[Architectural Record]]|accessdate=March 4, 2011}}</ref> Amid these concerns, on September 2010, the CSU Board of Trustees approved a proposal to have the building razed.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tacsi |first1=Canan |title=Cal Poly Pomona may demolish iconic building |url=https://www.dailybulletin.com/2010/09/15/cal-poly-pomona-may-demolish-iconic-building-2/ |publisher=[[Inland Valley Daily Bulletin]] |accessdate=27 September 2019 |date=September 15, 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[Hideo Sasaki]]'s architectural firm ''Sasaki Associates, Inc.'' found in the February 2010 [[Comprehensive planning|master plan]] that the campus's [[seismic risk]], uneven terrain, lack of parking spaces, small classrooms, and pedestrian-unfriendly roads are major constraints for future campus development. It also indicated the lack of identity, an undefined sense of arrival, and a desire to build a stronger on-campus community, among others, as recurrent themes among campus's users. Nonetheless, the firm highlights campus ethnic diversity, its location-climate, and the natural beauty of campus, among others, as positive aspects of the physical campus as well as the campus life experience.<ref>{{cite web| title=Cal Poly Pomona Campus Masterplan Forum| url=http://projects.sasaki.com/calpolypomona/Documents/CampusForumVision_002.pdf| format=PDF| work= Sasaki Associates, Inc.| publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona| date=February 11, 2010| pages=3\u20136| accessdate=March 31, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Organization and administration==\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em; font-size:90%; line-height:1.4em; width:280px;\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''College founding'''\n|-\n| '''College''' || <center>'''Year founded'''</center>\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |<hr />\n|-\n| [[Cal Poly Pomona College of Agriculture|Agriculture]] || <center>1938<ref>{{Citation | title = Poly @lumni E-Newsletter | newspaper = Poly Alumni | year = 2009\u20132010 | url = http://www.cpp.edu/~alumni/polyalumni/ | accessdate = January 31, 2010}}</ref></center>\n|-\n| [[Cal Poly Pomona College of Business Administration|Business Administration]] || <center>1967<ref>{{cite web | title = College of Business Interview Transcript | publisher = Office of Diversity and Compliance at California State Polytechnic University, Pomona | date = June 5, 2006 | url = http://www.cpp.edu/~diversity/ca_law/klockscript.shtml | accessdate = January 31, 2010 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref></center>\n|-\n| [[Cal Poly Pomona College of Education and Integrative Studies|Education and Integrative Studies]] || <center>1973<ref>{{cite web | title = Department Philosophy | publisher = Office of Diversity and Compliance at California State Polytechnic University, Pomona | url = http://www.cpp.edu/~ews/mission.htm | accessdate = January 31, 2010 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref></center>\n|-\n| [[Cal Poly Pomona College of Engineering|Engineering]] || <center>1957<ref name=\"cpp.edu\"/></center>\n|-\n| [[Cal Poly Pomona College of Environmental Design|Environmental Design]] || <center>1970<ref>{{cite web | title = History | publisher = College of Environmental Design at California State Polytechnic University, Pomona | url = https://env.cpp.edu/env/history | accessdate = June 26, 2019 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20181015141614/http://env.cpp.edu/env/history | archivedate = October 15, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref></center>\n|-\n| [[Collins College of Hospitality Management|Hospitality Management (Collins)]] || <center>1973<ref>{{cite web  | title =  About The Collins College of Hospitality Management  | publisher =  The Collins College of Hospitality Management  | url =  https://www.cpp.edu/~collins/about/index.shtml  | accessdate =  June 26, 2019  }}</ref></center>\n|-\n| [[Cal Poly Pomona College of Letters, Arts, and Social Sciences|Letters, Arts, and Social Sciences]] ||\n|-\n| [[Cal Poly Pomona College of Science|Science]] ||\n|}\nCal Poly at Pomona is one of [[Cal Poly (disambiguation)|two polytechnics]]<ref>{{Harvnb|Gerth|2010|p=3.}}</ref> in the 23-member [[California State University]] system.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.calstate.edu/search_find/campus.shtml| title=Campus Homepages| publisher=California State University| accessdate=February 1, 2010}}</ref> The CSU system is governed by a 25-member [[board of trustees]], including one faculty trustee, one alumni trustee, and two student trustees, and has authority over curricular development, campus planning, and fiscal management.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.calstate.edu/BOT/ |title=Board of Trustees |publisher=The California State University |accessdate=January 30, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.calstate.edu/bot/overview.shtml |title=Overview \u2013 Board of Trustees |publisher=The California State University |accessdate=January 30, 2010}}</ref> The university system is currently governed by Chancellor [[Timothy P. White]], who assumed the office in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calstate.edu/executive/ |title=Chancellor |publisher=The California State University |accessdate=April 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe chief executive of the Cal Poly Pomona campus is President [[Soraya M. Coley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cpp.edu/~president/ |title=Office of the President| publisher=The California State University|accessdate=January 30, 2010}}</ref>\n\nCal Poly Pomona is a member of the [[American Association of State Colleges and Universities|American Association of State Colleges and Universities (AASCU)]]<ref name=\"American Association of State Colleges and Universities\">{{cite news| title=Members by State & Territories| url= http://www.aascu.org/members/by-state-and-territory/| publisher= [[American Association of State Colleges and Universities]]| accessdate=September 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===University Educational Trust (UET)===\nThe University Educational Trust (UET) was a [[501(c)(3)#501(c)(3)|501 (c)(3)]] tax-exempt organization serving as a source of external fund-raising, funds-management and revenue-distribution at Cal Poly Pomona.<ref>{{cite web | title=New Territory: Cal Poly Pomona Launches Bold Fundraising Campaign | url=http://campaign.cpp.edu/2010/11/cal-poly-pomona-launches-bold-fundraising-campaign.html | publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona | date=November 4, 2010 | accessdate=March 27, 2011 }}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> According to meeting minutes from 2011, the \"Cal Poly Pomona University Educational Trust (UET) Board of Directors, the Chancellor's Office and University Administration made the decision to dissolve the UET and transfer all of its net assets to the Cal Poly Pomona Foundation, Inc.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Storey|first1=G. Paul|title=Cal Poly Pomona Foundation, Inc Audit Committee Meeting Minutes September 21, 2011|url=https://www.foundation.cpp.edu/%5Ccontent%5Cd%5CMeeting%20Packets%5CAudit013112.pdf|website=Cal Poly Pomona Foundation|accessdate=April 13, 2018|page=3|date=September 21, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Endowment===\nCal Poly Pomona [[financial endowment]] was valued at $85.6 million {{as of|2016|June|30|lc=y}}.<ref name=\"Endowment\">As of June 30, 2016. {{cite web |url=http://www.nacubo.org/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2016-Endowment-Market-Values.pdf |title=U.S. and Canadian Institutions Listed by Fiscal Year (FY) 2016 Endowment Market Value and Change in Endowment Market Value from FY 2015 to FY 2016 |publisher=National Association of College and University Business Officers and Commonfund Institute |year=2017 |access-date=March 24, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215040947/http://www.nacubo.org/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2016%2DEndowment%2DMarket%2DValues.pdf |archive-date=February 15, 2017 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> In fall 2010, Cal Poly Pomona embarked on its first comprehensive fundraising campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://polycentric.cpp.edu/news_stories/2010/09/cal-poly-pomona-sets-150-million-fundraising-goal.html|title=Cal Poly Pomona Sets $150 Million Fundraising Goal|year=2010|publisher=Office of Public Affairs at California State Polytechnic University, Pomona|accessdate=December 8, 2010}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Early major donors helped raise more than half of the campaign's goal of $150 million before its formal launch. They included an anonymous benefactor who pledged $12 million,<ref>{{Cite episode |title= Anonymous $12 million gift to Cal Poly Pomona |url= http://www.scpr.org/news/2009/09/03/anonymous-12-million-gift-cal-poly-pomona/ |network= Southern California Public Radio |station= 89.3 KPCC |location= Pasadena |airdate= September 3, 2009 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110628211724/http://www.scpr.org/news/2009/09/03/anonymous-12-million-gift-cal-poly-pomona/ |archivedate= June 28, 2011 }}</ref> and $2 million from 1980 alumni Mickey and Lee Segal.<ref>{{cite news |title= Mickey and Lee Segal Pledge $2 Million to Cal Poly |url= http://blogs.dailybulletin.com/educationnow/2010/06/mickey-and-lee-segal-pledge-2.html |newspaper= Inland Valley Daily Bulletin |accessdate= December 8, 2010 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110708220411/http://blogs.dailybulletin.com/educationnow/2010/06/mickey-and-lee-segal-pledge-2.html |archivedate= July 8, 2011 |df= mdy-all }}</ref> Just before the campaign launch, on July 26, 2010, the [[W. K. Kellogg Foundation]] awarded a $42 million challenge grant to the university to increase educational access to underrepresented communities, making it the largest cash gift in the history of the [[California State University|CSU system]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/27/local/la-me-calpoly-20100727 | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Carla | last=Rivera | title=Cal Poly Pomona receives $42-million cash grant, largest in Cal State history | date=July 27, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite press release| title = Cal Poly Pomona Benefits from Unprecedented Gift from W.K. Kellogg Foundation| publisher = [[W. K. Kellogg Foundation]]| date = July 26, 2010| url = http://www.wkkf.org/news/Articles/2010/07/Cal-Poly-Benefits-from-Unprecedented-Gift-from-WKKF.aspx| accessdate = July 26, 2010| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100729092903/http://www.wkkf.org/news/Articles/2010/07/Cal-Poly-Benefits-from-Unprecedented-Gift-from-WKKF.aspx| archivedate = July 29, 2010| df = mdy-all}}</ref> On February 28, 2011, [[Panda Express]] founders Andrew and Peggy Cherng announced a $2.5 million pledge to Cal Poly Pomona's [[Collins College of Hospitality Management]].<ref>{{Cite press release|title = Panda founders pledge $2.5 million to Cal Poly Pomona|publisher = Pasadena Star-News|date = February 28, 2011|url = http://www.pasadenastarnews.com/business/ci_17504510|accessdate = March 3, 2011|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110305054444/http://www.pasadenastarnews.com/business/ci_17504510|archivedate = March 5, 2011|df = mdy-all}}</ref> The university expects that its permanent endowment at the conclusion of its first comprehensive campaign will top $100 million.<ref>{{cite web|title=Comprehensive Campaign Tops $100 Million|url=http://polycentric.cpp.edu/news_stories/2012/03/campaign-100-million.html|work=polycentric|accessdate=May 12, 2012}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\n{{Main|California State Polytechnic University, Pomona academics}}\n[[File:Cal Poly Library Entrance.jpg|thumb|right|Main entrance of the [[Cal Poly Pomona University Library]]]]\n\nCal Poly Pomona's academic offerings have evolved throughout the years. Prior to the ownership shift to Cal Poly SLO in 1938, the Voorhis School for Boys in San Dimas had been providing educational offerings in \"music, bookkeeping, agriculture, library work, carpentry, nature study, machine shop, and printing\" coupled with Christian religious fundamentals to an all-male student body with poor, underage boys.<ref name=\"Pflueger 1999 44\"/><ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=42.}}</ref> In 1938, the campus became the agricultural branch of Cal Poly SLO when a small staff was transfer from San Luis Obispo along with group of agricultural inspection students.<ref>{{Harvnb|Kennedy|2001|p=23.}}</ref> Thus, Cal Poly at Pomona (then just Cal Poly) began offering [[Associate's degree]]s in 1938 and [[Bachelor's degree]]s in 1940 when, despite legislative opposition from pro-[[University of California]] members in [[Sacramento]], president Julian McPhee asked allied members Armistead B. Carter and Daniel C. Murphy to introduce the bill when two opposing members were not present to vote.<ref>{{Harvnb|Kennedy|2001|p=24.}}</ref> Following the governance breakup with the San Luis Obispo in 1966, and as outlined by the 1960 [[California Master Plan for Higher Education]], Cal Poly Pomona continued \"offer[ing] undergraduate and graduate instruction through the master's degree in the liberal arts and sciences and professional education, including teacher education.\"<ref name=\"Master Plan\">{{cite news | title=California State University mission | url=http://www.ucop.edu/acadinit/mastplan/csumission.htm| work= University of California \u2013 Office of the President | accessdate=April 25, 2010}}</ref> Currently, Cal Poly Pomona promotes a \"learn by doing\" philosophy, where an essential part of the curriculum is hands-on application of knowledge.<ref name=\"Cal Poly\">{{cite news| title=University Vision and Identity Initiative| url=http://www.cpp.edu/~alumni/docs/focus/meeting/University%20Vision%20and%20Identity%20Presentation.pdf| format=PDF| work=University Advancement Division at Cal Poly at Pomona| page=7| accessdate=August 26, 2008}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n[[Merriam-Webster]] mentions that \"polytechnic\" is a word first used in 1801 derived from the French ''[[wikt:polytechnique|polytechnique]]'' which contains the [[Greek language|Greek]]-[[Root (linguistics)|roots]] \"poly\" (''English:many'') and \"techn\u0113\" (''art''). Thus, Merriam-Webster defines \"polytechnic\" as, \"relating to or devoted to instruction in many technical arts or applied sciences\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/polytechnic | title=Polytechnic \u2013 Definition and More from the Free Merriam-Webster Dictionary | work=[[Merriam-Webster]]| accessdate=March 27, 2011}}</ref> Cal Poly Pomona's polytechnic approach, and learn-by-doing philosophy, encourages students in all programs to get real-world experience and skills necessary to join the workforce upon graduation.<ref name=\"Polytechnic Approach\">{{cite web| title= Polytechnic Approach| url= http://www.dsa.cpp.edu/visitors/files/polytechniclbd_153.pdf| format= PDF| publisher= Cal Poly at Pomona| accessdate= August 19, 2008}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn addition, the university is among six other institutions of higher education in California that have been designated a \"Center of Academic Excellence\" by the [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Department of Homeland Security]] and the [[National Security Agency]] (NSA).<ref>{{cite web |title= Student Competition Tests Cyber Security Skills |url= http://campustechnology.com/articles/2009/03/27/student-competition-tests-cyber-security-skills.aspx |last= Schaffhauser |first=Dian |work= Campus Technology |date= March 27, 2009 |access-date= April 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= Centers of Academic Excellence \u2013 Institutions |url= http://www.nsa.gov/ia/academic_outreach/nat_cae/institutions.shtml#ca |work= [[National Security Agency]] |accessdate= April 19, 2009 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130325155724/http://www.nsa.gov/ia/academic_outreach/nat_cae/institutions.shtml#ca |archive-date= March 25, 2013 |url-status= dead |df= mdy-all }}</ref> While all majors are encouraged to participate in [[Cooperative education|co-op]] opportunities and [[Internship#United States|internships]], all students must do a senior research project.<ref>{{cite web |title= Hands-on Activities |url= http://www.cpp.edu/~cosl/hands-on.html |publisher= California State Polytechnic University, Pomona |accessdate= April 9, 2011 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150801031837/http://www.cpp.edu/~cosl/hands-on.html |archivedate= August 1, 2015 |df= mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe {{cvt|300,000|sqft|m2}} [[Cal Poly Pomona University Library]] serves \"as the central intellectual and cultural resource of the campus community\" and contains over 3 million items and serves as an important center for academic research.<ref>{{cite news|title=University Library Briefing Book Detail |url=http://www.cpp.edu/~library/about/briefing_book_detail.html |work=[[Cal Poly Pomona University Library]] |publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona |accessdate=March 28, 2011 }}{{dead link|date=August 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Built in 1969 for $4.2 million, the library underwent a major renovation and expansion completed in the summer of 2008 at a cost of over $46 million.<ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=160.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Evolution of a Library: 1938-2000 |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~library/about/about-the-library/history.shtml |publisher=Cal Poly Pomona |accessdate=20 September 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180804014341/https://www.cpp.edu/~library/about/about-the-library/history.shtml |archivedate=4 August 2018}}</ref> The library participates in the [[Online Computer Library Center]] (OCLC) Enhance program which allows it to correct or add information to bibliographic records in [[WorldCat]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oclc.org/us/en/worldcat/catalog/quality/enhance/default.htm#enhance|title= OCLC Enhance participants  |publisher= [[Online Computer Library Center]] |accessdate=March 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Distinctions===\nThe university boasts many nationally acclaimed academic colleges and programs. With approximately 5,000 students, its college of Engineering is the second largest in the California State University system.<ref name=\"calstate.edu\">{{cite web|url=http://www.calstate.edu/as/stat_reports/2012-2013/fmaj04.htm|title=CSU - AS - Student Enrollment in Degree Programs Report - Fall 2012|first=Monica Malhotra, Lisa|last=Limbeek|website=www.calstate.edu|accessdate=October 13, 2018}}</ref> The university has the largest Mechanical Engineering, Electrical Engineering, Civil Engineering, and Construction Engineering programs in the CSU, and is the only campus to offer an Engineering Technology focus.\n\nJust behind [[Cal State Fullerton]], the university has the second largest Business Administration major in the CSU with nearly 5,000 students. Its Hospitality program is the largest in the CSU and one of the largest in all of the US, with approximately 1,000 students enrolled. Overall, the university holds the fourth largest business college the CSU.<ref name=\"calstate.edu\"/>\n\n===Rankings===\n{{details|topic=college-specific rankings|Cal Poly Pomona academics#Rankings}}\n{{Infobox US university ranking\n| Forbes = 273\n| THE_WSJ = 389\n| USNWR_REG = 14\n| Wamo_MASTERSU = 83\n}}\n\n''[[Money Magazine]]'' ranked Cal Poly Pomona 268th in the country out of the nearly 1500 schools it evaluated for its 2015-2016 Best Colleges ranking.<ref>{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Money's Best Colleges |url=https://best-colleges.time.com/money/full-ranking#/list |magazine= Money|date=2015 |accessdate=November 12, 2015}}</ref> ''[[The Daily Beast]]'' ranked Cal Poly Pomona 159th in the country out of the nearly 2000 schools it evaluated for its 2014 Best Colleges ranking.<ref>{{cite web |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=The Daily Beast's Guide to the Best Colleges 2014 |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/11/06/the-daily-beast-s-down-and-dirty-guide-to-the-best-colleges-2014.4.html |website=The Daily Beast |date=November 6, 2014 |access-date=November 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'''s 2020 \"Best Regional Universities West Rankings,\" Cal Poly Pomona is ranked 2nd in the western United States for regional public schools whose highest degree is a Master's and 2nd for Most Innovative School, and tied for 14th overall (including private schools).<ref name=USNWR>{{cite web |url=https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/california-state-polytechnic-university-pomona-1144/overall-rankings |title=California State Polytechnic University - Pomona Rankings  |access-date=September 9, 2019 |magazine=U.S. News & World Report}}</ref> The same report ranked the College of Engineering tied for 11th out of undergraduate engineering schools in the U.S. where doctorates are not offered, with national program rankings of:<ref name=USNWR/>\n\n*[[Civil Engineering]]: 5th\n*[[Computer Engineering]]: 5th\n*[[Electrical Engineering]]: 11th\n*[[Mechanical Engineering]]: 12th\n\nIn ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine's 2019 list of \"America's Best Colleges\", Cal Poly Pomona was ranked number 273 among the 650 best public and private colleges and universities in the nation.  In the 2012 \"PayScale College Salary Report\" conducted by [[PayScale]] of bachelor's graduates without higher degrees, Cal Poly Pomona ranked 19th among public universities in the country with a starting median salary of $46,800 and a mid-career median salary of $93,000. This places Cal Poly Pomona the fourth highest in California and the second highest in the CSU, while besting every UC with the exception of Berkeley and San Diego.<ref>{{cite news | title=Top State Universities By Salary Potential | url= http://www.payscale.com/best-colleges/top-state-universities.asp| work= PayScale, Inc. | accessdate=January 31, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2014 ''[[Kiplinger]]'' ranked Cal Poly Pomona 94th out of the top 100 best-value public schools in the nation, and 11th in California.<ref>{{cite magazine | url=http://www.kiplinger.com/tool/college/T014-S001-kiplinger-s-best-values-in-public-colleges/index.php |magazine=Kiplinger's Personal Finance |title=Kiplinger's Best College Values 2015 |date=December 2014}}</ref> Furthermore, Cal Poly Pomona is considered one of the top investments for educational value, with a 2013 net 30-year [[return on investment]] (ROI) of $917,100 according to [[PayScale]]. This ROI is the third highest in the CSU and 113th highest of the 1,511 US colleges and universities that were ranked, besting most UC campuses.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.payscale.com/college-education-value-2013 |title = 2013 College Education ROI Rankings |publisher = PayScale, Inc.}}</ref>\n\n===Admissions===\n<div style=\"float:right; text-align:center; font-size:85%; margin:10px\">\n'''Fall Enrolled Freshman Statistics (Fall 2018-Fall 2011)'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!\n\n! 2019<br /><ref name=\"Fast Facts Fall 2019\">{{cite web |title=Fast Facts Fall 2019 |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~data/documents/cpp-facts/fall_2019_fast_facts_v2_12_06.pdf |publisher=Cal Poly Pomona Office of Academic Research and Resources |accessdate=27 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n! 2018<br /><ref name=\"Common Data Set 2018\">{{cite web |title=Common Data Set 2018-2019 |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~arar/CommonDataSet/CommonDataSetDocs/cds2018.pdf |publisher=Cal Poly Pomona Office of Academic Research and Resources |accessdate=27 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Just the Facts 2018\">{{cite web |title=Just the Facts - Fall 2018 |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~arar/just-the-facts/Historical-Reports/just-the-facts-2018.pdf |publisher=Cal Poly Pomona Office of Academic Research and Resources |accessdate=27 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n! 2017<br /><ref name=\"Common Data Set 2017\">{{cite web |title=Common Data Set 2017-2018 |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~arar/CommonDataSet/CommonDataSetDocs/cds2017.pdf |publisher=Cal Poly Pomona Office of Academic Research and Resources |accessdate=30 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Just the Facts 2017\">{{cite web |title=Just the Facts - Fall 2017 |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~arar/just-the-facts/Historical-Reports/Just_the_Facts_F2017.pdf|publisher=Cal Poly Pomona Office of Academic Research and Resources |accessdate=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n! 2016<br /><ref name=\"Common Data Set 2016\">{{cite web |title=Common Data Set 2016-2017 |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~arar/CommonDataSet/CommonDataSetDocs/cds2016.pdf |publisher=Cal Poly Pomona Office of Academic Research and Resources |accessdate=30 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Just the Facts 2016\">{{cite web |title=Just the Facts - Fall 2016 |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~arar/just-the-facts/Historical-Reports/Just_the_Facts_F2016.pdf|publisher=Cal Poly Pomona Office of Academic Research and Resources |accessdate=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n! 2015<br /><ref name=\"Common Data Set 2015\">{{cite web |title=Common Data Set 2015-2016 |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~arar/CommonDataSet/CommonDataSetDocs/cds2015.pdf |publisher=Cal Poly Pomona Office of Academic Research and Resources |accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Just the Facts 2015\">{{cite web |title=Just the Facts - Fall 2015 |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~arar/just-the-facts/Historical-Reports/Just_the_Facts_F2015.pdf|publisher=Cal Poly Pomona Office of Academic Research and Resources |accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n! 2014\n\n! 2013\n\n! 2012\n\n! 2011\n\n|-\n! Applicants\n| {{formatnum:{{#expr:39726}}}} || {{formatnum:{{#expr:19839+16821}}}} || {{formatnum:{{#expr:18273+16646}}}} || {{formatnum:{{#expr:17579+15338}}}} || {{formatnum:{{#expr:18155+15702}}}} || 32,801 || 31,465 || 28,143 || 23,946 \n|-\n! Admitted\n| {{formatnum:{{#expr:21687}}}} || {{formatnum:{{#expr:9697+10643}}}} || {{formatnum:{{#expr:8936+10289}}}} || {{formatnum:{{#expr:9343+10131}}}} || {{formatnum:{{#expr:6198+7109}}}} || 17,014 ||16,636 || 14,685 || 13,191 \n|-\n! % Admitted\n|<center>{{#expr:(((21687)/(39726))*100)round1}}</center>||<center>{{#expr:(((9697+10643)/(19839+16821))*100)round1}}</center>||<center>{{#expr:(((8936+10289)/(18273+16646))*100)round1}}</center>||<center>{{#expr:(((9343+10131)/(17579+15338))*100)round1}}</center>||<center>{{#expr:(((6198+7109)/(18155+15702))*100)round1}}</center>||<center>51.9</center>||<center>52.9</center> || <center>52.2</center> || <center>55.1</center>  \n|-\n! Enrollment\n|<center>{{formatnum:{{#expr:3694}}}} </center> ||<center>{{formatnum:{{#expr:1963+56+1813+31}}}} </center> || <center>{{formatnum:{{#expr:1864+69+1804+49}}}}</center> || <center>{{formatnum:{{#expr:2155+82+1924+43}}}}</center> || <center>{{formatnum:{{#expr:1355+32+1301+19}}}}</center> || <center>3,658</center> || <center>3,257</center> || <center>3,120</center> || <center>3,249</center> \n|-\n! Average GPA<br /><small>(out of 4.0)</small>\n|<center>3.55</center> ||<center>3.51</center> || <center>3.49</center> || <center>3.52</center>||<center>3.50</center>||<center>3.42</center> || <center>3.43</center> || <center>3.41</center>  || <center>3.32</center>  \n|-\n! Average SAT<br /><small>(out of 1600)</small>\n|<center>1139</center> ||<center>1141</center> || <center>1105</center> || <center>1136</center> || <center>1102</center> || <center>1068</center> || <center>1059</center> || <center>1071</center>  || <center>1057</center>  \n|}\n</div>\n\nThe [[Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching]] and ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' describe Cal Poly Pomona's admissions process as \"selective\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Overview of California State Polytechnic University--Pomona |url=https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/california-state-polytechnic-university-pomona-1144 |magazine=U.S. News & World Report |access-date=September 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Carnegie Foundation - Institution Profile|url=http://carnegieclassifications.iu.edu/lookup/view_institution.php?unit_id=110529|publisher=[[Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching]]|access-date=October 15, 2013}}</ref>  The [[California State University|CSU system]] lists Cal Poly Pomona among 16 of its institutions with higher admission standards for first-time freshmen.<ref>{{cite web |title=Campuses That Have Higher Standards |work=[[California State University]] |url=http://www.csumentor.edu/planning/high_school/campuses_that_have_higher_standards.asp|accessdate=September 14, 2008}}</ref> For the Fall of 2016 there were 32,917 first-time, first year applicants: 19,474 were admitted (51.9%) and 4,204 enrolled (an admissions yield of 21.6%).<ref name=CDS2016>{{cite web |url=http://www.cpp.edu/~arar/CommonDataSet/CommonDataSetDocs/cds2016.pdf |title=Common Data Set 2016\u201317 |publisher=Institutional Research & Academic Resources at California State Polytechnic University, Pomona}}</ref>  The middle 50% range of [[SAT]] scores was 440-560 for reading and 460\u2013600 for math, while the middle 50% [[ACT (test)|ACT]] Composite range was 20\u201327.<ref name=CDS2016/> Of the enrolled freshmen, 25.6% had a high school GPA of 3.75 or higher, while the average GPA was 3.45.<ref name=CDS2016/>\n\nFreshmen applicants who graduate high school outside Cal Poly Pomona's Tier 1 area (known as Tier 2 applicants) are rank ordered by eligibility index and granted admission based on a year-specific cutoff score.<ref name=\"dsa.cpp.edu\">{{cite web|url=http://dsa.cpp.edu/admissions/ftf_impaction.asp|title=Cal Poly Pomona Admissions and Outreach \u2013 FTE Impaction |publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona|accessdate=April 8, 2011}}</ref> Since academic year 2010\u20132011, Tier 1 applicants may no longer be guaranteed admissions based on the CSU Eligibility Index and may be subject to similar criteria as Tier 2 applicants.<ref name=\"President message - February 22, 2010\">{{cite web |title=Monday Video \u2013 February 22, 2010 | url=http://polycentric.cpp.edu/news_stories/presidentmessage022210.pdf | work=polycentric | format=PDF | accessdate=March 26, 2011}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n====Demographics====\nCal Poly Pomona is an ethnically and culturally diverse university, self-described as \"Champions of Diversity\", ''[[College Prowler]]'' states that \"Cal Poly is the [[melting pot]] of the [[California State University|Cal States]]\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Diversity|url=http://www.cpp.edu/~diversity/facts/0506_Diversity_3_910.pdf|publisher=Office of Diversity and Compliance at Cal Poly Pomona|accessdate=August 6, 2011|format=PDF|date=November 24, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402203131/http://www.cpp.edu/~diversity/facts/0506_Diversity_3_910.pdf|archivedate=April 2, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Cal Poly Pomona \u2013 Diversity|url=http://collegeprowler.com/cal-poly-pomona/diversity/|publisher=[[College Prowler]]|accessdate=August 6, 2011}}</ref>\nAs of 2018 Cal Poly Pomona has the third largest enrollment percentage of Asian Americans in the Cal State System.<ref name=\"Ethnicity Enrollment Profile\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.calstate.edu/as/stat_reports/2018-2019/feth02.htm|title=Ethnicity Enrollment Profile|website=www.calstate.edu|access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; float:right; font-size:85%; margin-left:2em; margin:auto;\"\n|+ ''Fall 2018 Demographics of student body''<ref name=\"Ethnicity Enrollment Profile\"/>\n! !! * All levels, freshman through graduate   \n|-\n! [[African American]]\n| 3.4%\n|-\n! [[Asian American]]\n| 17.1%\n|-\n! [[Filipino American]]\n| 4.0%\n|-\n! [[Pacific Islander]]\n| 0.2%\n|-\n! [[European Americans|White European Americans]]\n| 16.3%\n|-\n! [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American/American Indian]]\n| 0.2%\n|-\n! [[Mexican American|Mexican American/Chicano]]\n| 36.0%\n|-\n! Other [[Latin Americans|Latino]] American \n| 8.9%\n|-\n! [[Multiracial Americans]]\n| 3.7%\n|-\n! [[Non-resident alien]]\n| 6.6%\n|-\n! Unknown\n| 3.5%\n|-\n|}\n\nCal Poly Pomona has over 1,000 visa-bearing international students.<ref>{{cite web |title=International Students |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~international/international-students/index.shtml |publisher=Cal Poly Pomona College of the Extended University, International Center |accessdate=1 October 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180804014330/https://www.cpp.edu/~international/international-students/index.shtml |archivedate=August 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Impaction====\nDuring the fall admissions filing period, the [[California State University|CSU]] designates academic programs where more applications are received than can be accommodated by the campus, and designates them as \"[[Impacted majors|impacted]]\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Impacted Programs|url=http://dsa.cpp.edu/admissions/impacted_programs.asp|publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona|accessdate=March 4, 2011}}</ref> At Cal Poly Pomona, impacted academic programs include: Animal Health Science, Animal Science, Aerospace Engineering, [[Cal Poly Pomona Department of Chemical and Materials Engineering|Chemical and Materials Engineering]], Civil Engineering, Computer Engineering, Electrical Engineering, Mechanical Engineering, [[Cal Poly Pomona Architecture|Architecture]], Psychology, Sociology, Communication, Biology, Biotechnology, and undeclared programs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Undeclared Students|url=http://dsa.cpp.edu/ssep/undeclared.asp |publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona|accessdate=March 3, 2011}}</ref> As such, applicants are rank ordered by eligibility index regardless of local admissions area and are accepted as space permits.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dsa.cpp.edu/admissions/major_impaction.asp|title=Division of Student Affairs|website=dsa.cpp.edu|accessdate=October 13, 2018}}</ref> Cal Poly Pomona students who wish to change majors to an impacted program must meet supplemental requirements required for that major. Requesting a change to an impacted majors must be received by the end of the initial filing period for the term for which new majors are being accepted (i.e. By February 28, 2010 for summer 2011; November 30, 2010 for fall 2011; June 30, 2011 for winter 2012; or August 31, 2011 for spring 2012).<ref>{{cite web|title=Change of Major|url=http://dsa.cpp.edu/registrar/major_.asp|publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona-Registar's Office|accessdate=September 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\n[[File:Student suites at Cal Poly Pomona.png|thumb|left|upright|Student suites at Cal Poly Pomona]]\n\n===Housing===\n\n{| style=\"float:right;\" \"text-align:center; font-size:85%; margin:auto;\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ ''On Campus Housing Bed Count''\n! !! Beds\n|-\n! Alamitos\n| <center>212</center>\n|-\n! Aliso\n| <center>212</center>\n|-\n! Encinitas\n| <center>212</center>\n|-\n! Montecito\n| <center>212</center>\n|-\n! Cedritos\n| <center>185</center>\n|-\n! Palmitas\n| <center>185</center>\n|-\n! Suites Phase I\n| <center>420</center>\n|-\n! Suites Phase II\n| <center>622</center>\n|-\n! University Village Phase I\n| <center>384</center>\n|-\n! University Village Phase II\n| <center>448</center>\n|-\n! University Village Phase III\n| <center>476</center>\n|-\n! Center for Regenerative Studies\n| <center>20</center>\n|-\n! Total\n| <center>3588</center>\n|}\n\n[[File:Cal Poly Bronco Recreation and Intramural Complex (BRIC).png|right|thumb|Cal Poly's Bronco Recreation and Intramural Complex (BRIC)]]\n\nWith an on-campus housing capacity of 3,519 students, Cal Poly Pomona has the fifth largest housing system in the [[California State University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calstate.edu/cpdc/Facilities_Planning/2015-16-Five-Yr-CapImprovementPgmBk.pdf |title=Facilities planning |date=2016 |website=www.calstate.edu |format=PDF |access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cpp4me.cpp.edu/|title= Future Students |accessdate=December 5, 2010 |work=Cal Poly Pomona}}</ref> In 2016, 39% of first-year students and 10% of all students live in college housing.<ref name=CDS2016/>\n\nThere are three [[dormitory|residential]] styles on the Pomona campus. The oldest housing facilities consist of six residential halls located on University Drive. The four older red-brick halls are named ''Alamitos'', ''Aliso'', ''Encinitas'', and ''Montecito'', each providing accommodation for up to 212 residents.  The other two housing halls (''Cedritos'' and ''Palmitas'') were the result of later housing development and each has room to accommodate up to 185 residents.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cpp.edu/~housing/housing-options/halls-suites.shtml|title=Residence hall/suite information|last=|first=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=February 2, 2017|work=University Housing Services at Cal Poly Pomona}}</ref>\n\nThe two newest residential complexes are the ''Village'' and the ''Suites'' which offer apartment-style living to non-freshman students. The ''Residence Halls'' and the ''Suites'' are managed by the Division of Student Affairs, whereas the ''Village'' is managed by the Cal Poly Pomona Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://foundation.cpp.edu/village/|title=University Village|work=University Village at Cal Poly Pomona|publisher=Cal Poly Pomona Foundation|accessdate=April 7, 2011}}</ref> Phase I of the construction of the Suites, housing 420 students, was completed in 2004 and Phase II, housing 622 students, opened in 2010.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn an effort to reduce commuting and raise academic performance and retention, starting with the 2010\u20132011 academic year, freshmen from outside the Tier 1 Local Admissions area (the area roughly bounded by the San Gabriel Mountains and Chino Hills to the north and south and the 15 and 605 freeways to the east and west), will be required to live on campus.<ref name=\"President message - February 22, 2010\"/>\n\n[[File:CLA Walk.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Students on a walkway leading to the [[CLA Building]]]]\n\n===Bronco Student Center===\n{{Main|Bronco Student Center}}\n[[File:Bronco Student Center.jpg|thumb|right|[[Bronco Student Center]]]]\n\nThe Bronco Student Center is a student activity center for meetings, conferences, meals, recreation, and shopping for students and alumni on the campus of Cal Poly Pomona in Pomona, California. This is where ASI student government offices are located, as well as other various student run departments like facilities and operations, Recreation, Programming and Marketing (RPM), Business Services, Games Room Etc. (GRE).\n\n===LGBT-Friendly campus===\nAccording to the Advocate College Guide for LGBT Students, Cal Poly Pomona is one of the nation's best campuses for lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dsa.cpp.edu/visitors/rankings.asp|title=Division of Student Affairs|website=dsa.cpp.edu|accessdate=October 13, 2018}}</ref> The university offers [[gender-neutral housing]], a pride center for LGBT students, the club oSTEM (out in STEM) and Pride Alliance for faculty and staff members.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dsa.cpp.edu/pride/clubs.asp|title=Division of Student Affairs|website=dsa.cpp.edu|accessdate=October 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Campus media===\nCampus events are covered by the [[student newspaper]], the ''[[The Poly Post|Poly Post]]''. The Bronco Sports Show is a quarterly television broadcast capturing the highlights and statistics from Bronco Athletics along with other featured events around the campus. ''PolyCentric''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://polycentric.cpp.edu |title=PolyCentric &#124; Cal Poly Pomona |publisher=Polycentric.cpp.edu |accessdate=April 30, 2010}}</ref> is the university's official online magazine. PolyCentric features news, announcements of campus events, spotlights on various departments, and resources for faculty and staff. A web site also provides a comprehensive archival search for past articles and photos.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://polycentric.cpp.edu/guide/polycentric-archives.html|title=polycentric Cal Poly Pomona Archives|publisher=Polycentric.cpp.edu|accessdate=April 9, 2011}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Bronco Pep Band===\n{{Main|Bronco Pep Band}}\n\nThe Bronco Pep Band is a student-run band at Cal Poly Pomona. The band is a group within the [[Cal Poly Pomona Broncos|athletic department]]. It follows the tradition of other student-run bands in the sense that it focuses on its members' individuality. The band attends athletic events during the year to encourage the school's athletic teams and audience support/involvement. The pep band is entirely voluntary and all students at Cal Poly Pomona or anyone else in the area are free to join.\n\n===Greek life===\nGreek Life at Cal Poly Pomona consists of 16 fraternities and 11 sororities governed by the Greek Council. From the total male [[Undergraduate education|undergraduate]] population, 2% are enrolled in fraternities and 1% of women in sororities respectively.<ref name=\"College Prowler-Greek Life\">{{cite web|url=http://collegeprowler.com/cal-poly-pomona/greek-life/|title=Cal Poly Pomona \u2013 Greek Life |publisher=[[College Prowler]]|accessdate=September 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dsa.cpp.edu/osl/greeklife/default.asp|title=Welcome to Greek Life at Cal Poly Pomona|publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona|accessdate=March 4, 2011}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sigmanupomona.com/chapter-history|title=Chapter History|publisher=Sigma Nu Fraternity|accessdate=April 11, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120915045857/http://www.sigmanupomona.com/chapter-history|archivedate=September 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\nActive Chapters at include, but are not limited to: [[Nu Alpha Kappa]], [[Sigma Alpha Epsilon]], [[Sigma Chi]], [[Phi Kappa Tau]], [[Pi Kappa Alpha]], [[Pi Kappa Phi]], [[Alpha Xi Delta]], [[Chi Omega]], [[Sigma Kappa]], [[Kappa Delta]], [[Zeta Tau Alpha]], [[Triangle Fraternity|Triangle]], [[Phi Sigma Rho]], [[Alpha Phi Gamma (sorority)|Alpha Phi Gamma]] as well as other multicultural, professional, honor and service societies.\n\n===Rose Parade float===\n{{Main|Cal Poly Universities Rose Float}}\nCal Poly Pomona together with [[California Polytechnic State University|Cal Poly San Luis Obispo]] has participated in the [[Tournament of Roses Parade|Tournament of Roses parade]] since 1949; winning the Award of Merit in their first year. In the period from 1949\u20132005, the floats have won 44 awards. This joint program is one of the longest consecutive running self-built entries in the parade, as well as the only \"self built\" floats designed and constructed entirely by students year-round on both campuses. The Rose Float tradition continues today and marks the partnership between the two Cal Poly campuses.\n\n==Athletics==\n{{Main|Cal Poly Pomona Broncos}}\n\n===Voorhis Vikings===\nBefore the university moved from San Dimas to Pomona, the college had a handful of athletic teams named the '''\"Voorhis Vikings\"'''. They were composed mostly of homeless and orphaned boys of all races who were cared for at the Voorhis School during the ten-year period it operated.<ref>{{cite web | title=Special Collections & University Archives-Voorhis Vikings | url=http://www.cpp.edu/~library/specialcollections/voorhis/vikings/index.html | work=University Library at California State Polytechnic University, Pomona | accessdate=April 26, 2010 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827094416/http://www.cpp.edu/~library/specialcollections/voorhis/vikings/index.html | archive-date=August 27, 2016 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> Despite this historical background, the university's current athletic programs are named the Broncos.\n\n===Cal Poly Pomona Broncos===\nCal Poly Pomona [[varsity team]]s compete in the [[California Collegiate Athletic Association]] of [[NCAA Division II]]. Teams are known as the [[Cal Poly Pomona Broncos]] and field 10 sports for men and women for the fall, winter, and spring quarters. Cal Poly Pomona's most recent national championship came in [[2010 NCAA Men's Division II Basketball Tournament|2010 Division II basketball tournament]] when the university's [[Cal Poly Pomona Broncos men's basketball|men's basketball team]] defeated [[Indiana University of Pennsylvania]] 65\u201353 in the title game.  The Broncos are currently the most successful program in the CCAA having achieved 60 CCAA and 14 NCAA National Championships.<ref>{{cite web | title=All-Time CCAA Champions | url=http://www.goccaa.org/sports/2006/8/11/alltime_ccaa_champs.aspx | work=[[California Collegiate Athletic Association]] | accessdate=April 26, 2010 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100322210007/http://www.goccaa.org/sports/2006/8/11/alltime_ccaa_champs.aspx | archive-date=March 22, 2010 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=History | url=http://www.broncoathletics.com/sports/2009/11/4/Traditions_page.aspx?tab=history| publisher=[[Cal Poly Pomona Broncos]]| accessdate=March 31, 2011}}</ref> University athletes have also claimed individual championships in women's [[women's tennis|tennis]] (1980, 1981, 1991, and 1992).\n\nTeam national championships for the Broncos include the following:\n*[[College Baseball|Baseball]]: 1976, 1980, 1983\n*Men's cross country: 1983\n*Men's [[college basketball|basketball]]: 2010\n*Women's [[women's basketball|basketball]]: 1982, 1985, 1986, 2001, 2002\n\n==Notable people==\n{{Main|List of Cal Poly Pomona people}}\n\n===Faculty===\nSome notable faculty members include: [[Pritzker Prize]] laureate [[Thom Mayne]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography|url=http://www.pritzkerprize.com/laureates/2005/bio.html|publisher=[[Pritzker Prize|The Pritzker Architecture Prize]]|accessdate=March 6, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101221230718/http://pritzkerprize.com/laureates/2005/bio.html <!--Added by H3llBot-->|archivedate=December 21, 2010}}</ref> [[Modernism|modernist]] architect [[Richard Neutra]],<ref>{{cite web|title=P&R Responses for recommendation 121 |url=https://win.webdev.cpp.edu/sppr/response.aspx?id=121|work=[[Cal Poly Pomona Architecture|Department of Architecture at Cal Poly Pomona]]|publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona|accessdate=March 5, 2011}}</ref> poet [[Virginia Hamilton Adair]],<ref name=\"Cal Poly Pomona Collection\">{{cite web| url=http://www.cpp.edu/~library/specialcollections/adair/VHA.html| title=Special Collections and Archives \u2013 Virginia Hamilton Adair Collection| publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona| accessdate=May 5, 2010| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150505003440/https://www.cpp.edu/~library/specialcollections/adair/VHA.html| archive-date=May 5, 2015| url-status=dead| df=mdy-all}}</ref> engineer [[Gabriel Georgiades]],<ref name=\"Cal Poly Pomona Faculty\">{{cite web|\nurl=http://www.cpp.edu/~engineering/ARO/faculty.shtml|publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona|accessdate =October 25, 2017|title=Aerospace Faculty}}</ref> and [[Fulbright Program|Fulbright scholar]] [[Renford Reese]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.insidesocal.com/educationnow/2009/08/cal-poly-pomona-professor-awar.html|title=Cal Poly Pomona professor awarded Fulbright Scholar fellowship|last=Tasci|first=Canan|publisher=[[Los Angeles Newspaper Group]]|accessdate=May 5, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713040745/http://www.insidesocal.com/educationnow/2009/08/cal-poly-pomona-professor-awar.html|archivedate=July 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Alumni===\nMore than 149,000 alumni have graduated from Cal Poly Pomona over the course of its history, and over 15,000 remain active with the university through the [[Cal Poly Pomona Alumni Association]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sanford |first1=Matthew |title=About the Alumni Association |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~alumni/about/index.shtml |publisher=Cal poly Pomona Alumni Association |accessdate=2 October 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180814190555/https://www.cpp.edu/~alumni/about/index.shtml |archivedate=August 14, 2018}}</ref> Some notable alumni include [[Hilda Solis]], former [[United States Secretary of Labor|U.S. Secretary of Labor]]; Former Republican State Senator [[Jim Brulte]], [[The Stooges|Stooges]] guitarist and former [[Sony]] technology executive [[James Williamson (musician)|James Williamson]]; author [[Anthony Amaral]]; [[Academy Award]]-winning actor [[Forest Whitaker]];<ref>{{cite web | title=Resume | url=http://solis.house.gov/biography/resume.shtml| work=Office of the Congresswoman Hilda Solis | accessdate=September 20, 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080730192930/http://solis.house.gov/biography/resume.shtml <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = July 30, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"CSU Mentor\">{{cite web | title=Cal Poly Pomona | url=http://www.csumentor.edu/campustour/undergraduate/1/Cal_Poly_Pomona/Cal_Poly_Pomona5.html| work= CSU Mentor | accessdate=September 12, 2008}}</ref> and popular Twitch streamer Herschel Beahm IV ([[Dr DisRespect]]) who played on the Broncos' basketball team. [[Chi Cheng (athlete)|Chi Cheng]] and [[Kim Rhode]] are Cal Poly Pomona alumni and Olympic medalists.<ref name=\"College Prowler-Alumni & Post-Grads\">{{cite web |url=http://collegeprowler.com/cal-poly-pomona/alumni--and--post--grads/ |title=Cal Poly Pomona-Alumni & Post-Grads |publisher=[[College Prowler]] |accessdate=September 2, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100919225706/http://collegeprowler.com/cal-poly-pomona/alumni--and--post--grads/ |archive-date=September 19, 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Among other notable alumni in athletics are: [[Heisman Trophy]]-winning football player [[Glenn Davis (halfback)|Glenn Davis]], former professional football player and NFL head coach [[Jim Zorn]],<ref>{{cite web | title=Glenn Davis Statistics | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/D/DaviGl01.htm| work= Sports Reference LLC| accessdate=April 4, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/dcsportsbog/2008/02/jim_zorn_plays_viola_and_speed.html |title=Jim Zorn Plays Viola and Speedskates |work=Washington Post |accessdate=September 19, 2008}}</ref> soccer player [[Jonathan Bornstein]],<ref>{{cite web| title=Player Bio:Jonathan Bornstein| url=http://www.uclabruins.com/sports/m-soccer/mtt/bornstein_jonathan00.html| work=[[UCLA Bruins|University of California, Los Angeles athletics]]| accessdate=July 20, 2010| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928135042/http://www.uclabruins.com/sports/m-soccer/mtt/bornstein_jonathan00.html| archivedate=September 28, 2011| df=mdy-all}}</ref> BMX rider [[Dave Mirra]],<ref name=\"College Prowler-Alumni & Post-Grads\" /> and all-time [[PBA Tour]] titles leader [[Walter Ray Williams, Jr.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pba.com/Bowlers/Bowler/11534|work=[[Professional Bowlers Association]]|title=Walter Ray Williams Jr|date=March 3, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Los Angeles}}\n*[[California Master Plan for Higher Education]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{cite book|title=Cal Poly: The First Hundred Years|year=2001|publisher=California Polytechnic State University|location=San Luis Obispo, California|isbn=0944197663 |ref={{harvid|CPSUSLO|2001}}}}\n* {{citation|last=Angel|first=Myron|authorlink=Myron_Angel|title=History of the California Polytechnic School at San Luis Obispo, California|year=1907|publisher=[[The Tribune (San Luis Obispo)]]|location=San Luis Obispo, California|url=https://archive.org/details/historyofcalifor00ange }}\n* {{citation|last=Gerth|first=Donald|year=2010|title=The People's University: A History of the California State University|publisher=University of California, Institute of Governmental Studies|isbn=0-87772-435-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v4J-QwAACAAJ}}\n* {{citation|last=Kennedy|first=Robert E.|year=2001|title=Learn by Doing \u2013 Memoirs of a University President: A Personal Journey with the Seventh President of California Polytechnic State University.|publisher=California Polytechnic State University|location=San Luis Obispo, California }}\n* {{citation|last=Parkinson|first=Mary Jane|title=The Romance of the Kellogg Ranch|year=2001|publisher=South Sea International Press, Ltd|location=Hong Kong, People's Republic of China|isbn=978-0-9777088-0-2|oclc=72525130 }}\n* {{citation|last=Pflueger|first=Donald|authorlink=Donald_H._Pflueger|title=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona: A Legacy and a Mission|origyear=1991| year=1999|publisher=[[Arthur H. Clark Company]]|location=Spokane, Washington|oclc=43853707 }}\n* {{citation|last=Powell|first=Horace B.|year=1956|title=The Original Has This Signature\u2014W.K.Kellogg|publisher=[[Prentice Hall|Prentice-Hall, Inc.]]|location=Englewood Cliffs, New Jersey }}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.broncoathletics.com/ Cal Poly Athletics website]\n\n{{California State Polytechnic University, Pomona}}\n{{Navboxes\n|titlestyle = background:#0E426A; color:#FFFFFF; {{box-shadow border|a|#FFC300|2px}}\n|list =\n{{Pomona, California}}\n{{California_State University}}\n{{Colleges and universities in Los Angeles County}}\n{{Polytechnic Universities}}\n{{Colleges and universities in California}}\n{{California Collegiate Athletic Association navbox}}\n{{Coalition of Urban and Metropolitan Universities}}\n{{Tournament of Roses}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:California State Polytechnic University, Pomona| ]]\n[[Category:California State University|Pomona]]\n[[Category:Education in Pomona, California]]\n[[Category:Technological universities in the United States]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Los Angeles County, California]]\n[[Category:Schools accredited by the Western Association of Schools and Colleges]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1938]]\n[[Category:1938 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Pomona, California]]\n", "text_old": "{{About||the liberal arts college in Claremont, California|Pomona College|Cal Poly San Luis Obispo in San Luis Obispo, California|California Polytechnic State University}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name = California State Polytechnic University, Pomona\n|image_name = Cal Poly Seal.svg\n|image_size = 150px\n|motto = Learn By Doing<ref>{{cite web |title=Undergraduate Program |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~sci/computer-science/undergraduate-program/index.shtml |publisher=[[Cal Poly Pomona]] |accessdate=20 March 2019}}</ref>\n|established = 1938 (as Cal Poly Voorhis Unit in [[San Dimas, California]])<ref name=\"Tracing\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cpp.edu/~library/specialcollections/history/tracing.html |title=Tracing Cal Poly's roots |work=Cal Poly Pomona University Library |accessdate=February 28, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100601164351/http://www.cpp.edu/~library/specialcollections/history/tracing.html |archivedate=June 1, 2010 }}</ref>\n|type = [[Public university|Public]]<br />[[State University|State]]<br />[[Institute of Technology (United States)#Polytechnic universities|Polytechnic]]\n| endowment = $101.6 million (2019)<ref name=NACUBO>As of June 30, 2019. {{cite web |url=https://www.nacubo.org/-/media/Nacubo/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2019-NTSE-Endowment-Market-Values--FINAL-January-30-2020.ashx|title=U.S. and Canadian Institutions Listed by Fiscal Year (FY) 2019 Endowment Market Value and Change in Endowment Market Value from FY 2018 to FY 2019 |publisher=National Association of College and University Business Officers and TIAA |access-date=February 3, 2020}}</ref>\n|faculty = 1,330 (Fall 2017)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cpp.edu/~arar/campus-data/FTES/FTE-FacultyWithStatusDetail/FTE-FacultyWithStatusDetailTenured_Tenure-TrackandTemporaryFacultyFall2017.pdf |title=FALL 2017 FTE-Faculty with Status Detail: Tenued/Tenure-Track and Temporary Faculty |publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona |accessdate=January 17, 2018}}</ref>\n|president = [[Soraya M. Coley]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cpp.edu/~president/|title=Welcome to Cal Poly Pomona|publisher=Office of the President at Cal Poly Pomona |accessdate=January 6, 2014}}</ref>\n|provost = Sylvia A. Alva<ref>{{cite web|title=Office of the Provost|url=http://academic.cpp.edu/academic/|publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona|accessdate=May 13, 2010}}</ref>\n|students = 27,914 (Fall 2019)<ref name=Enrollment>{{cite web |url=http://asd.calstate.edu/dashboard/enrollment-live.html |title=Fall Term Student Enrollment |publisher=The California State University Institutional Research and Analyses |access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n|undergrad = 26,451 (Fall 2019)<ref name=Enrollment/>\n|postgrad = 1,463 (Fall 2019)<ref name=Enrollment/>\n|city = [[Pomona, California|Pomona]]\n|state = [[California]]\n|country = United States\n|coor = {{Coord|34|03|23|N|117|49|18|W|type:edu_region:US-CA|display=inline,title}}\n|campus = Suburban, {{convert|1438|acre|ha}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Cal Poly Pomona |url=https://www2.calstate.edu/attend/campuses/pomona |website=CalState.edu |accessdate=24 July 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170807115110/https://www2.calstate.edu/attend/campuses/pomona|archivedate=August 7, 2017}}</ref>\n|colors = [[Green]], [[Gold]], and [[Blue]]<ref name=\"Color\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cpp.edu/~brand/ |title=University Brand: A Bold New Look |publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona |accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref><br />{{color box|#198844}}&nbsp;{{color box|#ffc300}}&nbsp;{{color box|#0E426A}}\n|mascot = Billy Bronco<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cpp.edu/~ne/bronco.shtml|title=Get the Bronco Spirit!|publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona|accessdate=November 14, 2008|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150302164040/http://www.cpp.edu/~ne/bronco.shtml|archivedate=March 2, 2015}}</ref>\n|nickname = [[Cal Poly Pomona Broncos|Broncos]]\n|athletics = [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[NCAA Division II|Division II]] \u2013 [[California Collegiate Athletic Association|CCAA]]\n|affiliations = *[[California State University]] (CSU)\n*[[Western Association of Schools and Colleges]] (WASC)\n*[[American Association of State Colleges and Universities]] (AASCU)\n|website = {{url|www.cpp.edu}}\n|logo = Logo of California State Polytechnic University, Pomona.svg\n|logo_size = 250\n}}\n\n'''California State Polytechnic University, Pomona''' ('''Cal Poly Pomona''', '''CPP''', or '''Cal Poly'''<ref group=\"Note\">\"Cal Poly\" may also refer to [[California Polytechnic State University]] in San Luis Obispo; however, the term may also use the term to refer to the Pomona campus. See the ''[[California State Polytechnic University, Pomona#Name|name]]'' section of this article for more information.</ref>) is a [[Public university|public]] [[Institute of Technology (United States)#Polytechnic universities|polytechnic university]] in [[Pomona, California]]. It is one of [[Cal Poly (disambiguation)|two polytechnic universities]] in the [[California State University]] system.\n\nCal Poly Pomona began as the southern campus of the California Polytechnic School (today known as [[California Polytechnic State University|Cal Poly San Luis Obispo]]) in 1938 when the '''Voorhis School for Boys''' and its adjacent farm in the city of [[San Dimas, California|San Dimas]] were donated by Charles Voorhis and his son [[Jerry Voorhis]]. Cal Poly's southern campus grew further in 1949 when the '''University of California, W.K. Kellogg Institute''' also known as '''W.K. Kellogg Institute of Animal Husbandry\u2014University of California, Pomona''' in the neighboring city of Pomona, which had belonged to [[Will Keith Kellogg]], was acquired from the [[University of California]]. Cal Poly Pomona, then known as '''Cal Poly Kellogg-Voorhis''', and Cal Poly San Luis Obispo continued operations under a unified administrative control until they became independent from one another in 1966.\n\nCal Poly Pomona currently offers [[bachelor's degrees]] in 94 majors, 39 [[master's degrees]], 13 [[teaching credential]]s and a doctorate [[California State Polytechnic University, Pomona academics|across 9 distinct academic colleges]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://degrees.calstate.edu/csu_degree_search2?noCache=607:1358369036|title=CSU Degrees|website=CSU Degrees|accessdate=October 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://degrees.calstate.edu/uploads/55/64/5564d4b6ec1584227ca2d1054c759f0f/Credential-Programs-08212012.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=February 14, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150424234126/http://degrees.calstate.edu/uploads/55/64/5564d4b6ec1584227ca2d1054c759f0f/Credential-Programs-08212012.pdf |archivedate=April 24, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to Doctoral Studies |url=http://www.cpp.edu/~education/doctoral/index.shtml|publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona|accessdate=October 21, 2013}}</ref> The university is one among a small group of [[Institute of Technology (United States)#Polytechnic universities|polytechnic universities in the United States]] which tend to be primarily devoted to the instruction of technical arts and applied sciences.\n\nIts sports teams are known as the [[Cal Poly Pomona Broncos]] and play in the [[NCAA Division II]] as part of the [[California Collegiate Athletic Association]] (CCAA). The Broncos sponsor 10 varsity sports and have won 14 NCAA national championships. Current and former Cal Poly Pomona athletes have won 7 Olympic medals ([[List of American universities with Olympic medals|3 gold, 1 silver, and 3 bronze]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cpp.edu/~75th/newsletter/athletics.shtml|title=Top 12 Athletics Achievements|website=www.cpp.edu|language=en|access-date=February 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203075524/https://www.cpp.edu/~75th/newsletter/athletics.shtml|archive-date=February 3, 2017 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{Dablink|See also: [[California Polytechnic State University#History|History of the California Polytechnic in San Luis Obispo, California]].<ref group=Note>From 1938 to 1966 the California Polytechnic (Cal Poly) intermittently operated as one institution in up to three different locations: Pomona, San Dimas and San Luis Obispo.</ref>}}\n{{Quote box |quote = Let it be the [[Cornell University|Cornell]] of the Pacific... where any person can find instruction in any study. |source = <small>Myron Angel, founder of the California Polytechnic School, San Luis Obispo, CA. January 7, 1899.</small><ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=15.}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Angel|1907|p=45.}}</ref> |align = right |width = 300px |fontsize = 90% |bgcolor = #e3e5e5 |quoted = 1}}\n\n[[File:W.K. Kellogg with Antez (1929).PNG|thumb|right|Cal Poly at Pomona stands on the former Arabian horse ranch of cereal magnate [[Will Keith Kellogg|W.K. Kellogg]].]]\n\nEvents leading to the foundation of present-day Cal Poly at Pomona began with the ending of the Voorhis School for Boys in [[San Dimas, California]] and its acquisition by the [[San Luis Obispo, California|San Luis Obispo]]-based California Polytechnic School in 1938.<ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=41.}}</ref><ref name=\"Voorhis\">{{cite web |last1=Strauss |first1=Rob |title=The Finding Aid of the Voorhis Family Collection 0090 |url=https://oac.cdlib.org/findaid/ark:/13030/c8t72q52/entire_text/ |website=Online Archive of California (OAC) |publisher=[[California Digital Library]] |accessdate=24 July 2019 |date=February 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe California Polytechnic School was founded as a [[Vocational education in the United States|vocational]] high school when California Governor [[Henry Gage]] signed the Polytechnic School Bill on March 8, 1901 after its drafting by school founder Myron Angel.<ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=18.}}</ref> Voorhis School, on the other hand, had been established in 1928 as a private vocational school which provided [[Primary education|elementary schooling]] for underprivileged boys and operated under the Christian religious principle, \"education coupled with the Kingdom of God\".<ref name=\"Pflueger 1999 44\">{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=44.}}</ref><ref name=\"Voorhis\" /> Its founder Charles B. Voorhis and [[Head teacher|headmaster]] [[Jerry Voorhis]] maintained the school opened throughout the worst years of the [[Great Depression]] but persistent economic pressures forced them to transfer control to [[Cal Poly San Luis Obispo]] in 1938.<ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=45.}}</ref><ref name=\"Voorhis\" /> \n\nVoorhis School became the Cal Poly-Voorhis Unit and its educational offerings were raised to the same level as Cal Poly San Luis Obispo's, then a two-year college.<ref name=\"Cal Poly San Luis Obispo\">{{cite web |url= http://www.alumni.calpoly.edu/alumniinfo/university-history.html |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080616082843/http://www.alumni.calpoly.edu/alumniinfo/university-history.html |archivedate=June 16, 2008 |title= University History |publisher=[[California Polytechnic State University]] | accessdate=February 4, 2010}}</ref> The horticulture program was moved to the new satellite campus and the two units operated as one institution spanning two locations under the leadership of president Julian McPhee.<ref name=\"Campus History, Cal Poly San Dimas?\">{{cite web| url=http://www.cpp.edu/~library/specialcollections/history/sandimas.html| title=Cal Poly San Dimas?| first=Allen| last=Ferreira| year=1985| publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona| accessdate=January 31, 2010| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402202643/http://www.cpp.edu/~library/specialcollections/history/sandimas.html| archive-date=April 2, 2015| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Cal Poly Pomona Winter.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Aerial view of campus]]\n\nDuring World War II most of the student body was called to active military duty; enrollment declined and the campus closed in 1943.<ref name=\"Campus History, Cal Poly San Dimas?\"/><ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=51.}}</ref> Reopening after the war, Cal Poly-Voorhis Unit operated in San Dimas until 1956 when it moved to [[Will Keith Kellogg]]\u2019s former [[Ranch|horse ranch]] in the neighboring city of [[Pomona, California]].<ref name=\"CPP History\">{{cite web | title= Heritage and History at Cal Poly Pomona | url= http://www.cpp.edu/cpp_heritage.php | url-status= dead| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20121204135153/http://www.csupomona.edu/cpp_heritage.php | archivedate= December 4, 2012 | publisher= California State Polytechnic University, Pomona | accessdate= November 11, 2010 }}</ref> Acknowledging its Kellogg legacy, Cal Poly-Voorhis Unit changed its name to Cal Poly Kellogg-Voorhis Unit and offered six programs in agriculture.<ref name=\"CPP History\" /> The inaugural class of 1957 at the new campus consisted of 57 students graduating with bachelor\u2019s degrees in a ceremony held at the Rose Garden in Pomona and religious services at Voorhis Chapel in San Dimas.<ref name=\"Catalog\">{{cite web | title= California State Polytechnic University, Pomona \u2013 Historical Development | url= http://www.cpp.edu/~academic/catalog/gen_info/Univ_Admin.pdf| publisher= California State Polytechnic University, Pomona | format=PDF | accessdate=November 14, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=103.}}</ref> Also in 1957, Cal Poly Kellogg-Voorhis introduced the [[Cal Poly Pomona College of Engineering|College of Engineering]], the second academic unit after the [[Cal Poly Pomona College of Agriculture|College of Agriculture]].<ref name=\"cpp.edu\">{{Citation | title = University Ranks Fifth in West, Engineering Program Ninth in Nation by U.S. News & World Report | newspaper = PolyTrends | page = 2 | year = 2003 | url = http://www.cpp.edu/~advancement/publications/polytrends_fall03.pdf | accessdate = January 31, 2010}}</ref> The [[California Master Plan for Higher Education]] added the two Cal Poly campuses to the new California State College system in 1961 and Cal Poly Kellogg-Voorhis Unit opened its doors for the first time to 329 female students.<ref name=\"CPP History\" /> President McPhee retired in 1966, and Cal Poly split into two different and independent universities. The partnership between the two campuses remains with their involvement in the annual [[Cal Poly Universities Rose Float]].<ref name=\"Cal Poly San Luis Obispo\" /><ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|pp=133\u2013134.}}</ref>\n\nTo better reflect its new ties to the California State College system, Cal Poly Kellogg-Voorhis changed its name to \u201cCalifornia State Polytechnic College, Kellogg-Voorhis\u201d in 1966 and became the 16th campus to officially join the CSC system.<ref name=\"CPP History\" /> Robert C. Kramer assumed presidency of the independent campus in 1966 (second overall as the university recognizes McPhee as its first) and California State Polytechnic College, Kellogg-Voorhis finally adopted its present-day name California State Polytechnic University, Pomona on June 1, 1972.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cpp.edu/~library/specialcollections/oralhistory/ |title=Voices From Our Past \u2013 Cal Poly Pomona Oral History |publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona |date=March 18, 2009 |accessdate=April 30, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701131456/http://www.cpp.edu/~library/specialcollections/oralhistory/ |archive-date=July 1, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calstate.edu/pa/info/milestones.shtml |title=CSU &#124; Public Affairs &#124; Historic Milestones |publisher=[[California State University]] |date=March 18, 2009 |accessdate=April 30, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, Cal Poly Pomona received criticism when it planned to grant an honorary degree to [[Robert Mugabe]].  Mugabe's negative humanitarian record as president of [[Zimbabwe]] lead to protests from staff, faculty and students, ultimately forcing the university to rescind the award.<ref>{{cite news | title= Cal Poly Pomona Chief Is Focus of Campus Contention\n| url= http://articles.latimes.com/1998/jun/15/local/me-60140|work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=September 2, 2008 | first=Kenneth R. | last=Weiss | date=June 15, 1998}}</ref>\n\nCal Poly Pomona underwent further growth in the late 20th and early 21st centuries, with the construction of the [[CLA Building]] (slated for demolition),<ref name=\"CLA Building\">{{cite web |last1=Ravitz |first1=Anya |title=Predock Defends Doomed Pomona Tower |url=https://archpaper.com/2010/10/predock-defends-doomed-pomona-tower/ |website=ArchPaper.com |publisher=[[The Architect's Newspaper]] |accessdate=26 July 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726182615/https://archpaper.com/2010/10/predock-defends-doomed-pomona-tower/ |archivedate=26 July 2019 |date=October 27, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thepolypost.com/news/2019/04/30/cla-in-limbo/|title=CLA in limbo|date=2019-04-30|website=The Poly Post|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref> academic facilities, expansion to the [[Cal Poly Pomona University Library]] and the addition of programs such as the [[Lyle Center for Regenerative Studies]], the [[International Polytechnic High School|I-Poly High School]] and the [[U.R. Bronco]] undergraduate research program. Under then-president [[J. Michael Ortiz]], Cal Poly Pomona launched its first comprehensive capital campaign in fall of 2008 to increase its permanent endowment. Nevertheless, the negative economic effects caused by the [[late-2000s recession]] has increased student fees, reduced enrollment availability, eliminated two athletic programs and introduced a mandatory [[furlough]] calendar for most of its employees.<ref>{{cite web|title= CSU Trustees Vote to Raise 2010\u201311 Fees by 5 Percent|url= http://polycentric.cpp.edu/2010/06/csu_trustees_raise_fees_5percent/|work= PolyCentric|accessdate = August 27, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190827140605/http://polycentric.cpp.edu/2010/06/csu_trustees_raise_fees_5percent/|archivedate=August 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title= California State University Officials Outline Enrollment Cuts and Preview 2010\u20132011 Budget | url= http://www.calstate.edu/pa/news/2009/enrollment-budget.shtml| publisher= [[California State University]] |accessdate=September 11, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title= Cal Poly Pomona Forced to Drop Men\u2019s and Women\u2019s Tennis | url= http://www.scta.usta.com/News/steve-2010/CalPoly/| publisher= [[United States Tennis Association]] |accessdate=September 11, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title= Cal State approves student fee increases and furloughs | url= https://www.scpr.org/news/2009/07/21/2604/csu-budget-vote-feature/| publisher= [[KPCC]] |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190920183541/https://www.scpr.org/news/2009/07/21/2604/csu-budget-vote-feature/ |archivedate=September 20, 2019 |accessdate= September 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Name===\n{{Dablink|See also: [[California State University#Campus naming conventions|Campus naming conventions in the CSU]] and [[California Polytechnic State University#Name]].}}\nThe campus' office of public affairs recognizes two official names for the university: \"California State Polytechnic University, Pomona\" and \"Cal Poly Pomona\".<ref name=\"Graphic Standard Manual\">{{cite news| url= http://www.cpp.edu/~publicaffairs/graphics/nomenclature.shtml| title= Identity| publisher= Office of Public Affairs at Cal Poly at Pomona| accessdate= February 1, 2010| url-status= dead| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150120025117/http://www.cpp.edu/~publicaffairs/graphics/nomenclature.shtml| archivedate= January 20, 2015| df= mdy-all}}</ref> However, \"Cal Poly\" has also been used to refer to Cal Poly at Pomona, as both itself and [[California Polytechnic State University]] at [[San Luis Obispo, California]] were one institution spanning two locations from 1938 to 1966.<ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=11.}}</ref> Cal Poly's office of public affairs recommends not to abbreviate the university's name merely as \"Cal Poly\".<ref name=\"Graphic Standard Manual\"/> In the years when the [[University of California]] was in charge of Kellogg's donated estate in Pomona (1932\u20131943), the names \"University of California, W.K. Kellogg Institute\" and \"W.K. Kellogg Institute of Animal Husbandry University of California, Pomona\", came into use to describe the site.<ref>{{Harvnb|Parkinson|2001|p=213.}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Parkinson|2001|p=204.}}</ref> Although Cal Poly Pomona is now part of the [[California State University]], its naming convention does not follow that of most campuses within the system (for example, the CSU campus in San Diego bears the full official name \"[[San Diego State University]]\" and the CSU campus in [[Fullerton, California|Fullerton]] uses the name \"[[California State University, Fullerton]]\").<ref>{{cite web| title=The New SDSU Graphic Identity System| url=http://advancement.sdsu.edu/marcomm/logo/SDSU_User_Manual_1.3.pdf| format=PDF| work=[[San Diego State University]]| page=4| accessdate=March 28, 2011| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110518052139/http://advancement.sdsu.edu/marcomm/logo/SDSU_User_Manual_1.3.pdf| archive-date=May 18, 2011| url-status=dead| df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=Editorial Style| url=http://www.fullerton.edu/identity/downloads/guidelines/editorial-style.pdf| format=PDF| work=[[California State University, Fullerton]]| page=3| accessdate=March 28, 2011| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720024850/http://www.fullerton.edu/identity/downloads/guidelines/editorial-style.pdf| archivedate=July 20, 2011| df=mdy-all}}</ref> Thus, \"Pomona State University\" and \"California State University, Pomona\" are seldom used and not in the university's graphic standard's manual.<ref name=\"Graphic Standard Manual\"/>\n\n===Seals and logos===\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" classes=\"center\">\nFile:The University of California W.K. Kellogg Institute.svg|<center>Former seal used by the university during the [[University of California]] years (1932-1943).</center>\nFile:University Seal of Cal Poly in Pomona, CA (mid-1980s-2017).svg|<center>Former seal used by the university from the mid-1980s to the summer of 2018 </center>\n</gallery>\n\n==Campus== \n{{Location map many\n| Los Angeles\n| float      = right\n| caption    = Cal Poly Pomona is located about 30 miles east of [[Downtown Los Angeles]].<ref name=About>{{cite web|title=About Cal Poly Pomona - A brief m\u00e9lange of history, quick facts, and philosophy|url=http://www.cpp.edu/about.php|publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona|accessdate=April 26, 2013}}</ref>\n| label      = Cal Poly at Pomona\n| position   = right\n| mark       = Green sphere.svg\n| marksize   = 10\n| lat1       = 34.05639\n| long1      = -117.82167\n| label2     = Downtown Los Angeles\n| position2  = left\n| mark2      = Blue sphere.svg\n| marksize2  = 10\n| lat2       = 34.054366\n| long2      = -118.243704\n}}\nCal Poly Pomona is situated in [[Pomona, California|Pomona]], a largely suburban city that is part of the [[Los Angeles metropolitan area]]. The city of Pomona is located in the eastern portion of [[Los Angeles County]] and borders the neighboring [[San Bernardino County|county of San Bernardino]] to the east. The university's {{convert|1725|acre|ha|sp=us}} campus<ref name=\"Physical Cal Poly Pomona\">{{cite web  |url= http://www.cpp.edu/~jskoga/physicalcalpoly/ |title= The Physical Cal Poly Pomona |author= James S. Koga |publisher= California State Polytechnic University, Pomona |accessdate=August 27, 2008}}</ref> make it the second largest in the [[California State University]] system,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aaiep.org/schools/show/189/cal_poly_english_language_institute |title=Cal Poly English Language Institute |publisher=American Association of Intensive English Programs |accessdate=August 22, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101015150343/http://aaiep.org/schools/show/189/cal_poly_english_language_institute |archivedate=October 15, 2010  }}</ref> a figure which includes various facilities scattered throughout [[Southern California]] such as a {{convert|53|acre|ha|adj=on}} ranch in [[Santa Paula, California]], {{convert|25|acre|ha|adj=on}} campus at the former Spadra Landfill (now known as \"Spadra Ranch\"),<ref name=\"Facilities\">{{cite web | url= http://www.cpp.edu/~plantsci/facilities.shtml | title=Department Facilities | publisher= California State Polytechnic University, Pomona| accessdate=September 17, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.lacsd.org/about/solid_waste_facilities/spadra/default.asp | title=Spadra Landfill (Post Closure Activities) | publisher=Sanitation Districts of Los Angeles County | accessdate=March 26, 2011}}</ref> and the [[Neutra VDL Studio and Residences]] in [[Silver Lake, Los Angeles]].  The university is currently negotiating the transfer of the 302 acre Lanterman Developmental Center from the State of California.  The land is to be used for academic purposes and expansion of the Innovation Village and also shared by the [[California Highway Patrol]], the [[California Air Resources Board]] and the [[California Conservation Corps]].  The transfer of the land is part of the Governor's 2015-2016 Proposed Budget.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abgt.assembly.ca.gov/sites/abgt.assembly.ca.gov/files/January%209%202015%20Budget%20Highlights.pdf |title=Budget |date=2015 |website=abgt.assembly.ca.gov |format=PDF |access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref>\n\n[[File:CalPoly Stables.jpg|thumb|right|Old horse stables]]\n\nAlthough part of the [[Los Angeles metropolitan area]], the university is in close proximity to two other large metropolitan and culturally-defined regions, the [[Inland Empire (California)|Inland Empire]] and [[Orange County, California|Orange County]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.wilkinguge.com/research/inland-empire-insights.php| title=Inland Empire Insights| work=Wilkin Guge Marketing| year=2008| accessdate=March 28, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081026015649/http://www.wilkinguge.com/research/inland-empire-insights.php |archivedate=October 26, 2008 }}</ref> The university has a tier 1 area, defined as a geographical admissions region surrounding the campus, roughly bounded by the [[San Gabriel Mountains]] to the north, the city of [[Chino Hills, California|Chino Hills]] to the south, [[Interstate 605]] to the west, and [[Interstate 15]] to the east.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.insidesocal.com/educationnow/2010/02/cal-poly-requiring-certain-fre.html |title= Department Facilities |publisher= [[Los Angeles Newspaper Group]] |accessdate= August 22, 2010 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20121023035806/http://www.insidesocal.com/educationnow/2010/02/cal-poly-requiring-certain-fre.html |archivedate= October 23, 2012 |df= mdy-all }}</ref> Cal Poly Pomona's campus buildings vary in age and style from the [[Mission Revival Style architecture|Mission Revival]] Kellogg Horse Stables and the Kellogg House (suggesting the [[Spanish architecture#Spanish Colonial architecture|Spanish colonial architectural heritage]] of [[Southern California]]) built in the 1920s; the modernist box-like portion of [[California State Polytechnic University, Pomona, Library|the library]] completed in 1969; to contemporary dormitories, engineering, science and library-expansion facilities completed in the early 21st century.{{sfn|CPSUSLO|2001|p=68}}\n\nLeisure and recreational locations include a [[rose garden]] which dates back to the Kellogg horse ranch years; the Kellogg House designed by Los Angeles-based architects Charles Gibbs Adams, [[Myron Hunt]] and Harold Coulson Chambers in the 1920s; and a {{convert|1.3|acre|ha}} [[Japanese garden]] built in 2003 and designed by [[Takeo Uesugi]].<ref name=\"UW Arch. Database\">{{cite web| url= https://digital.lib.washington.edu/architect/structures/3836/| title=Kellogg, W.K., Ranch House, Pomona, CA| publisher=[[University of Washington]]| accessdate=August 22, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.jgarden.org/gardens.asp?ID=642| title=George and Sakaye Aratani Japanese Garden at Cal Poly Pomona| last=Cheetham| first=Robert |publisher=Japanese Garden Research Network, Inc.| accessdate=August 22, 2010}}</ref> Kellogg's House features grounds which were initially landscaped by Charles Gibbs Adams but were later completed by [[Florence Yoch & Lucile Council]].<ref name=\"UW Arch. Database\" /> Cal Poly Pomona's George and Sakaye Aratani Japanese Garden is one among three under management by institutions of higher education in the County of Los Angeles, the others being the [[Earl Burns Miller Japanese Garden]] at [[California State University, Long Beach|Cal State Long Beach]], and the Shinwa-En Garden at [[California State University, Dominguez Hills|Cal State Dominguez Hills]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.la.us.emb-japan.go.jp/e_web/e_m06_29.htm |title=Japanese Gardens in Southern California and Arizona |publisher=Consulate General of Japan in Los Angeles |accessdate=March 31, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711012145/http://www.la.us.emb-japan.go.jp/e_web/e_m06_29.htm |archivedate=July 11, 2011  }}</ref> At the center of the campus and atop Horsehill are the buildings of the [[Collins College of Hospitality Management]] and Kellogg West, a hotel and conference center and home of the student/faculty-run Restaurant at Kellogg Ranch.\n\nAt the northwest part of the campus is the Voorhis [[Nature reserve|Ecological Reserve]], which serves as a {{convert|31|ha|acre}} [[wildlife corridor]] containing [[Coastal Sage Scrub]] and [[Quercus agrifolia|Coast Live Oak]] trees among others.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.cpp.edu/~biology/docs/voorhis.shtml |title=Voorhis Ecological Reserve |publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona}}</ref> Contrasting some of these architecturally prominent facilities, there are various [[portable building]]s on campus which are used to accommodate the growing enrollment of recent decades. Cal Poly Pomona operates the [[International Polytechnic High School]], a college preparatory high school located on campus.\n\nThe letters \"CPP\" made of concrete are located on Colt Hill overlooking the campus. The letters \"CP\" were initially added in 1959, with the second \"P\" added in 2004 to distinguish it from the Cal Poly campus in San Luis Obispo.<ref>{{cite journal |title=The CPP  Letters |journal=Cal Poly Pomona Magazine |date=Spring 2019 |page=3}}</ref>\n\nCal Poly Pomona's dominant landmark is a [[Futurist architecture|futurist-styled]] administrative facility known as the [[CLA Building]] which was designed by [[Antoine Predock]] and opened in 1993. The building's peculiar shape (standing out by a triangular-shaped \u201cskyroom\u201d atop its eight-story tower<ref>{{cite web |url=http://californiawatch.org/watchblog/iconic-cal-poly-pomona-building-poses-earthquake-hazard |title=Iconic Cal Poly building poses earthquake hazard |author=Erica Perez |date=March 23, 2010 |publisher=[[California Watch]] |accessdate=August 22, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100726153942/http://californiawatch.org/watchblog/iconic-cal-poly-pomona-building-poses-earthquake-hazard |archive-date=July 26, 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>) has become a symbol of the university; in addition, its close location to film studios based in the Hollywood borough of Los Angeles have prompted its inclusion in motion pictures such as ''[[Gattaca]]'' and ''[[Impostor (2002 film)|Impostor]]''.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Brian Sease |title=Lights, camera, Broncos: Productions filmed on campus |url=https://thepolypost.com/arts-and-entertainment/2019/01/29/lights-camera-broncos-productions-filmed-on-campus/ |website=thepolypost.com |publisher=[[The Poly Post]] |accessdate=20 September 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190203125029/https://thepolypost.com/arts-and-entertainment/2019/01/29/lights-camera-broncos-productions-filmed-on-campus/ |archivedate=February 3, 2019}}</ref> In 2013, the California State University Board of Trustees voted to demolish the building and replace it with a new academic/faculty complex because of severe seismic risks.<ref name=\"CLA Building\"/>\n\n[[File:Cal Poly Pomona South Campus.png|thumb|Cal Poly Pomona's new South Campus]]\n\nNoted [[Modern architecture|modernist]] architect [[James Pulliam, Architect|James Pulliam]] once served as campus architect and instructor and designed the Bookstore, W. Keith and Janet Kellogg Art Gallery, Interim Design Center (IDC) and Student Union building which architectural historian [[David Gebhard]] regarded as the best building on campus.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/2006/jan/01/local/me-pulliam1 | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Valerie J. | last=Nelson | title=James Pulliam, 80; Architect, Teacher Noted for Modernism | date=January 1, 2006}}</ref>\n\n===Academic and research facilities===\nThe [[W. K. Kellogg Arabian Horse Center]] is an academic and research facility serving one of the 22 terms and conditions to the donation of the Kellogg ranch by maintaining Kellogg's purebred [[Arabian horse]]s and their breeding program. Another academic facility highlighting the Kellogg legacy is the Horse Stables (also known as University Plaza) which contains a small research library specializing in equine studies along with offices for student services and various campus organizations.\n\n[[File:Voorev.jpg|thumb|Cal Poly Pomona's Voorhis Ecological Reserve]]\n\nConceived in 1995 by then university president, Bob H. Suzuki, and initially financed by [[NASA]] and the [[Economic Development Administration]], the Innovation Village is a {{convert|65|acre|ha|adj=on}} public/private partnership research and business facility at the southern edge of the campus. Major tenants include the [[American Red Cross]], [[Southern California Edison]], and the [[NASA]] Commercialization Center.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.innovationvillage.org/generalinfo.aspx|title=General Information|publisher=Innovation Village|accessdate=March 3, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110319014859/http://www.innovationvillage.org/generalinfo.aspx|archivedate=March 19, 2011}}</ref> The project is currently at the halfway mark of building and leasing {{convert|1000000|sqft|m2}} of the projected total building space. Once complete, it is estimated that the project would employ 2000 to 3000 people and provide half a billion dollars of economic benefits to the local, regional and state economies.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.labusinessjournal.com/news/2005/dec/19/innovation-park-puts-cal-poly-pomona-on-biotech/|title=Innovation Park Puts Cal Poly Pomona on Biotech Map|work=[[Los Angeles Business Journal]]|accessdate=March 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Campus sustainability and transportation===\n[[File:Cal Poly Main Quad (Pomona, CA).PNG|thumb|The main [[Quadrangle (architecture)|quad]] at Cal Poly Pomona]]\n\nThe university has actively sought to reduce carbon emissions and energy usage on campus. In November 2007, Cal Poly Pomona became a signatory member of the [[Campus Carbon Neutrality#American College and University Presidents' Climate Commitment|American College & University Presidents Climate Commitment]].<ref>{{cite web| url= http://acupcc.aashe.org/ip/195/ |title= Implementation Profile for California State Polytechnic University-Pomona |date= July 13, 2009 |publisher= [[Campus Carbon Neutrality#The Association for the Advancement of Sustainability in Higher Education|Association for the Advancement of Sustainability in Higher Education]] |accessdate=August 22, 2010}}</ref> Among other things, this committed the university to ensure that within one year, it would purchase or produce at least 15% of the institution's electric consumption from [[Renewable resource|renewable sources]]. The university, along with other members in the CSU, is also a member of the [[California Climate Action Registry]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.climateregistry.org/about/members.html |title= Members |date= December 15, 2009 |publisher= [[California Climate Action Registry]] |accessdate= August 22, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100825080455/http://www.climateregistry.org/about/members.html |archive-date= August 25, 2010 |url-status= dead |df= mdy-all }}</ref> and lists on ''[[The Princeton Review]]'s'' ''Guide to 375 Green Colleges''.<ref>{{cite web|title=286 Green Colleges (Full List) |url=https://www.princetonreview.com/college-rankings/green-guide/green-colleges-by-location|publisher=[[The Princeton Review]] in partnership with the U.S. [[Green Building Council]]|accessdate=November 7, 2017}}</ref> As a part of the campus' Climate Action Plan to reduce its carbon footprint, the campus offers incentive parking for students and faculty participating in its Rideshare program.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cpp.edu/~sustainability/pdf/CPP_CAP_091109.pdf |title=Climate Action Plan |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2019-05-15}}</ref> The carpooling initiative gives users the opportunity to park in reserved spaces located closer to campus buildings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cpp.edu/~parking/rideshare/rideshare-how-to/rideshare-permit.shtml|title=Obtain a Rideshare Parking Permit|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nCal Poly Pomona's institute for sustainability education is the [[Lyle Center for Regenerative Studies]]. The center was built adjacent to an old landfill and conducts research in the areas of sustainable technology and agriculture. As an example of [[Cradle to Cradle Design]], it uses solar-powered dormitories, aquaculture ponds, and organic gardens while providing an environmentally-sustainable housing accommodation for 22 graduate students. In 2010, with the installation of a 210,000&nbsp;kW hours [[Concentrated Photovoltaics|CPV]] system by [[Amonix]], the center became the first [[carbon neutral]] facility in the [[California State University]] system.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lyle Center Goes Carbon Neutral with Amonix Solar Energy Systems |url=http://blogs.calstate.edu/cpdc_sustainability/?p=671 |website=CalState.edu |publisher=[[California State University]] |accessdate=20 September 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150920182408/http://blogs.calstate.edu/cpdc_sustainability/?p=671 |archivedate=September 20, 2015 |date=September 30, 2010}}</ref> The center is part of Agriscapes, a {{convert|40|acre|ha|adj=on}} research project that showcases environmental and agricultural sustainable practices including methods to grow food, conserve water and energy and recycle urban waste. Agriscapes is home of the Farm Store at Kellogg Ranch which sells locally and campus grown foods and products. Cal Poly Pomona campus also contains a rainforest greenhouse, a California [[ethnobotany]] garden, and an aquatic biology center collectively known as BioTrek, which provides environmental education to all academic levels.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cpp.edu/~biotrek/ |title=About BioTrek |publisher= California State Polytechnic University, Pomona |accessdate= March 4, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe entire campus community is served by a free campus shuttle system known as \"Bronco Express\". The shuttle system has 3 lines and is run by the office of Transportation Services.<ref name=\"Transportation\">{{cite web |title=Bronco Express Shuttle |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~transportation/commuting-to-campus/bronco-shuttle.shtml |publisher=Cal Poly Pomona |accessdate=20 September 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920193443/https://www.cpp.edu/~transportation/commuting-to-campus/bronco-shuttle.shtml |archivedate=September 20, 2019}}</ref> In addition, PTS also offers a shuttle service known as \"Metrolink\" which provides both students and faculty a direct connection from the Pomona North and Downtown Pomona [[Metrolink (Southern California)|Metrolink]] stations to the [[CLA Building]].<ref name=\"Transportation\" />\n\n[[Foothill Transit]] lines 190, 194, 195, 289, 480, 482, and 486 serve the campus daily.\n\n===Seismic risks and other challenges of campus development===\nAlthough it's believed that the San Jose Fault runs through campus, and geotechnical investigations have been conducted, there is uncertainty regarding its precise [[Fault (geology)#Fault types|type]] and location. The CLA Building suffers from structural flaws, most notably, water intrusion. In 2005, the university filed a lawsuit against a contractor, for which it was compensated $13.3 million in an out-of-court [[Settlement (litigation)|settlement]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archrecord.construction.com/news/daily/archives/2010/09/100927predock_cla_building.asp|title=Antoine Predock\u2019s CLA Building in California May Be Demolished|last=Hill|first=David|date=September 27, 2010|work=[[Architectural Record]]|accessdate=March 4, 2011}}</ref> Amid these concerns, on September 2010, the CSU Board of Trustees approved a proposal to have the building razed.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tacsi |first1=Canan |title=Cal Poly Pomona may demolish iconic building |url=https://www.dailybulletin.com/2010/09/15/cal-poly-pomona-may-demolish-iconic-building-2/ |publisher=[[Inland Valley Daily Bulletin]] |accessdate=27 September 2019 |date=September 15, 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[Hideo Sasaki]]'s architectural firm ''Sasaki Associates, Inc.'' found in the February 2010 [[Comprehensive planning|master plan]] that the campus's [[seismic risk]], uneven terrain, lack of parking spaces, small classrooms, and pedestrian-unfriendly roads are major constraints for future campus development. It also indicated the lack of identity, an undefined sense of arrival, and a desire to build a stronger on-campus community, among others, as recurrent themes among campus's users. Nonetheless, the firm highlights campus ethnic diversity, its location-climate, and the natural beauty of campus, among others, as positive aspects of the physical campus as well as the campus life experience.<ref>{{cite web| title=Cal Poly Pomona Campus Masterplan Forum| url=http://projects.sasaki.com/calpolypomona/Documents/CampusForumVision_002.pdf| format=PDF| work= Sasaki Associates, Inc.| publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona| date=February 11, 2010| pages=3\u20136| accessdate=March 31, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Organization and administration==\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em; font-size:90%; line-height:1.4em; width:280px;\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''College founding'''\n|-\n| '''College''' || <center>'''Year founded'''</center>\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |<hr />\n|-\n| [[Cal Poly Pomona College of Agriculture|Agriculture]] || <center>1938<ref>{{Citation | title = Poly @lumni E-Newsletter | newspaper = Poly Alumni | year = 2009\u20132010 | url = http://www.cpp.edu/~alumni/polyalumni/ | accessdate = January 31, 2010}}</ref></center>\n|-\n| [[Cal Poly Pomona College of Business Administration|Business Administration]] || <center>1967<ref>{{cite web | title = College of Business Interview Transcript | publisher = Office of Diversity and Compliance at California State Polytechnic University, Pomona | date = June 5, 2006 | url = http://www.cpp.edu/~diversity/ca_law/klockscript.shtml | accessdate = January 31, 2010 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref></center>\n|-\n| [[Cal Poly Pomona College of Education and Integrative Studies|Education and Integrative Studies]] || <center>1973<ref>{{cite web | title = Department Philosophy | publisher = Office of Diversity and Compliance at California State Polytechnic University, Pomona | url = http://www.cpp.edu/~ews/mission.htm | accessdate = January 31, 2010 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref></center></center>\n|-\n| [[Cal Poly Pomona College of Engineering|Engineering]] || <center>1957<ref name=\"cpp.edu\"/></center>\n|-\n| [[Cal Poly Pomona College of Environmental Design|Environmental Design]] || <center>1970<ref>{{cite web | title = History | publisher = College of Environmental Design at California State Polytechnic University, Pomona | url = https://env.cpp.edu/env/history | accessdate = June 26, 2019 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20181015141614/http://env.cpp.edu/env/history | archivedate = October 15, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref></center>\n|-\n| [[Collins College of Hospitality Management|Hospitality Management (Collins)]] || <center>1973<ref>{{cite web  | title =  About The Collins College of Hospitality Management  | publisher =  The Collins College of Hospitality Management  | url =  https://www.cpp.edu/~collins/about/index.shtml  | accessdate =  June 26, 2019  }}</ref></center>\n|-\n| [[Cal Poly Pomona College of Letters, Arts, and Social Sciences|Letters, Arts, and Social Sciences]] ||\n|-\n| [[Cal Poly Pomona College of Science|Science]] ||\n|}\nCal Poly at Pomona is one of [[Cal Poly (disambiguation)|two polytechnics]]<ref>{{Harvnb|Gerth|2010|p=3.}}</ref> in the 23-member [[California State University]] system.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.calstate.edu/search_find/campus.shtml| title=Campus Homepages| publisher=California State University| accessdate=February 1, 2010}}</ref> The CSU system is governed by a 25-member [[board of trustees]], including one faculty trustee, one alumni trustee, and two student trustees, and has authority over curricular development, campus planning, and fiscal management.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.calstate.edu/BOT/ |title=Board of Trustees |publisher=The California State University |accessdate=January 30, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.calstate.edu/bot/overview.shtml |title=Overview \u2013 Board of Trustees |publisher=The California State University |accessdate=January 30, 2010}}</ref> The university system is currently governed by Chancellor [[Timothy P. White]], who assumed the office in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calstate.edu/executive/ |title=Chancellor |publisher=The California State University |accessdate=April 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe chief executive of the Cal Poly Pomona campus is President [[Soraya M. Coley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cpp.edu/~president/ |title=Office of the President| publisher=The California State University|accessdate=January 30, 2010}}</ref>\n\nCal Poly Pomona is a member of the [[American Association of State Colleges and Universities|American Association of State Colleges and Universities (AASCU)]]<ref name=\"American Association of State Colleges and Universities\">{{cite news| title=Members by State & Territories| url= http://www.aascu.org/members/by-state-and-territory/| publisher= [[American Association of State Colleges and Universities]]| accessdate=September 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===University Educational Trust (UET)===\nThe University Educational Trust (UET) was a [[501(c)(3)#501(c)(3)|501 (c)(3)]] tax-exempt organization serving as a source of external fund-raising, funds-management and revenue-distribution at Cal Poly Pomona.<ref>{{cite web | title=New Territory: Cal Poly Pomona Launches Bold Fundraising Campaign | url=http://campaign.cpp.edu/2010/11/cal-poly-pomona-launches-bold-fundraising-campaign.html | publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona | date=November 4, 2010 | accessdate=March 27, 2011 }}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> According to meeting minutes from 2011, the \"Cal Poly Pomona University Educational Trust (UET) Board of Directors, the Chancellor's Office and University Administration made the decision to dissolve the UET and transfer all of its net assets to the Cal Poly Pomona Foundation, Inc.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Storey|first1=G. Paul|title=Cal Poly Pomona Foundation, Inc Audit Committee Meeting Minutes September 21, 2011|url=https://www.foundation.cpp.edu/%5Ccontent%5Cd%5CMeeting%20Packets%5CAudit013112.pdf|website=Cal Poly Pomona Foundation|accessdate=April 13, 2018|page=3|date=September 21, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Endowment===\nCal Poly Pomona [[financial endowment]] was valued at $85.6 million {{as of|2016|June|30|lc=y}}.<ref name=\"Endowment\">As of June 30, 2016. {{cite web |url=http://www.nacubo.org/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2016-Endowment-Market-Values.pdf |title=U.S. and Canadian Institutions Listed by Fiscal Year (FY) 2016 Endowment Market Value and Change in Endowment Market Value from FY 2015 to FY 2016 |publisher=National Association of College and University Business Officers and Commonfund Institute |year=2017 |access-date=March 24, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215040947/http://www.nacubo.org/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2016%2DEndowment%2DMarket%2DValues.pdf |archive-date=February 15, 2017 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> In fall 2010, Cal Poly Pomona embarked on its first comprehensive fundraising campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://polycentric.cpp.edu/news_stories/2010/09/cal-poly-pomona-sets-150-million-fundraising-goal.html|title=Cal Poly Pomona Sets $150 Million Fundraising Goal|year=2010|publisher=Office of Public Affairs at California State Polytechnic University, Pomona|accessdate=December 8, 2010}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Early major donors helped raise more than half of the campaign's goal of $150 million before its formal launch. They included an anonymous benefactor who pledged $12 million,<ref>{{Cite episode |title= Anonymous $12 million gift to Cal Poly Pomona |url= http://www.scpr.org/news/2009/09/03/anonymous-12-million-gift-cal-poly-pomona/ |network= Southern California Public Radio |station= 89.3 KPCC |location= Pasadena |airdate= September 3, 2009 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110628211724/http://www.scpr.org/news/2009/09/03/anonymous-12-million-gift-cal-poly-pomona/ |archivedate= June 28, 2011 }}</ref> and $2 million from 1980 alumni Mickey and Lee Segal.<ref>{{cite news |title= Mickey and Lee Segal Pledge $2 Million to Cal Poly |url= http://blogs.dailybulletin.com/educationnow/2010/06/mickey-and-lee-segal-pledge-2.html |newspaper= Inland Valley Daily Bulletin |accessdate= December 8, 2010 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110708220411/http://blogs.dailybulletin.com/educationnow/2010/06/mickey-and-lee-segal-pledge-2.html |archivedate= July 8, 2011 |df= mdy-all }}</ref> Just before the campaign launch, on July 26, 2010, the [[W. K. Kellogg Foundation]] awarded a $42 million challenge grant to the university to increase educational access to underrepresented communities, making it the largest cash gift in the history of the [[California State University|CSU system]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/27/local/la-me-calpoly-20100727 | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Carla | last=Rivera | title=Cal Poly Pomona receives $42-million cash grant, largest in Cal State history | date=July 27, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite press release| title = Cal Poly Pomona Benefits from Unprecedented Gift from W.K. Kellogg Foundation| publisher = [[W. K. Kellogg Foundation]]| date = July 26, 2010| url = http://www.wkkf.org/news/Articles/2010/07/Cal-Poly-Benefits-from-Unprecedented-Gift-from-WKKF.aspx| accessdate = July 26, 2010| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100729092903/http://www.wkkf.org/news/Articles/2010/07/Cal-Poly-Benefits-from-Unprecedented-Gift-from-WKKF.aspx| archivedate = July 29, 2010| df = mdy-all}}</ref> On February 28, 2011, [[Panda Express]] founders Andrew and Peggy Cherng announced a $2.5 million pledge to Cal Poly Pomona's [[Collins College of Hospitality Management]].<ref>{{Cite press release|title = Panda founders pledge $2.5 million to Cal Poly Pomona|publisher = Pasadena Star-News|date = February 28, 2011|url = http://www.pasadenastarnews.com/business/ci_17504510|accessdate = March 3, 2011|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110305054444/http://www.pasadenastarnews.com/business/ci_17504510|archivedate = March 5, 2011|df = mdy-all}}</ref> The university expects that its permanent endowment at the conclusion of its first comprehensive campaign will top $100 million.<ref>{{cite web|title=Comprehensive Campaign Tops $100 Million|url=http://polycentric.cpp.edu/news_stories/2012/03/campaign-100-million.html|work=polycentric|accessdate=May 12, 2012}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\n{{Main|California State Polytechnic University, Pomona academics}}\n[[File:Cal Poly Library Entrance.jpg|thumb|right|Main entrance of the [[Cal Poly Pomona University Library]]]]\n\nCal Poly Pomona's academic offerings have evolved throughout the years. Prior to the ownership shift to Cal Poly SLO in 1938, the Voorhis School for Boys in San Dimas had been providing educational offerings in \"music, bookkeeping, agriculture, library work, carpentry, nature study, machine shop, and printing\" coupled with Christian religious fundamentals to an all-male student body with poor, underage boys.<ref name=\"Pflueger 1999 44\"/><ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=42.}}</ref> In 1938, the campus became the agricultural branch of Cal Poly SLO when a small staff was transfer from San Luis Obispo along with group of agricultural inspection students.<ref>{{Harvnb|Kennedy|2001|p=23.}}</ref> Thus, Cal Poly at Pomona (then just Cal Poly) began offering [[Associate's degree]]s in 1938 and [[Bachelor's degree]]s in 1940 when, despite legislative opposition from pro-[[University of California]] members in [[Sacramento]], president Julian McPhee asked allied members Armistead B. Carter and Daniel C. Murphy to introduce the bill when two opposing members were not present to vote.<ref>{{Harvnb|Kennedy|2001|p=24.}}</ref> Following the governance breakup with the San Luis Obispo in 1966, and as outlined by the 1960 [[California Master Plan for Higher Education]], Cal Poly Pomona continued \"offer[ing] undergraduate and graduate instruction through the master's degree in the liberal arts and sciences and professional education, including teacher education.\"<ref name=\"Master Plan\">{{cite news | title=California State University mission | url=http://www.ucop.edu/acadinit/mastplan/csumission.htm| work= University of California \u2013 Office of the President | accessdate=April 25, 2010}}</ref> Currently, Cal Poly Pomona promotes a \"learn by doing\" philosophy, where an essential part of the curriculum is hands-on application of knowledge.<ref name=\"Cal Poly\">{{cite news| title=University Vision and Identity Initiative| url=http://www.cpp.edu/~alumni/docs/focus/meeting/University%20Vision%20and%20Identity%20Presentation.pdf| format=PDF| work=University Advancement Division at Cal Poly at Pomona| page=7| accessdate=August 26, 2008}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n[[Merriam-Webster]] mentions that \"polytechnic\" is a word first used in 1801 derived from the French ''[[wikt:polytechnique|polytechnique]]'' which contains the [[Greek language|Greek]]-[[Root (linguistics)|roots]] \"poly\" (''English:many'') and \"techn\u0113\" (''art''). Thus, Merriam-Webster defines \"polytechnic\" as, \"relating to or devoted to instruction in many technical arts or applied sciences\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/polytechnic | title=Polytechnic \u2013 Definition and More from the Free Merriam-Webster Dictionary | work=[[Merriam-Webster]]| accessdate=March 27, 2011}}</ref> Cal Poly Pomona's polytechnic approach, and learn-by-doing philosophy, encourages students in all programs to get real-world experience and skills necessary to join the workforce upon graduation.<ref name=\"Polytechnic Approach\">{{cite web| title= Polytechnic Approach| url= http://www.dsa.cpp.edu/visitors/files/polytechniclbd_153.pdf| format= PDF| publisher= Cal Poly at Pomona| accessdate= August 19, 2008}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn addition, the university is among six other institutions of higher education in California that have been designated a \"Center of Academic Excellence\" by the [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Department of Homeland Security]] and the [[National Security Agency]] (NSA).<ref>{{cite web |title= Student Competition Tests Cyber Security Skills |url= http://campustechnology.com/articles/2009/03/27/student-competition-tests-cyber-security-skills.aspx |last= Schaffhauser |first=Dian |work= Campus Technology |date= March 27, 2009 |access-date= April 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= Centers of Academic Excellence \u2013 Institutions |url= http://www.nsa.gov/ia/academic_outreach/nat_cae/institutions.shtml#ca |work= [[National Security Agency]] |accessdate= April 19, 2009 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130325155724/http://www.nsa.gov/ia/academic_outreach/nat_cae/institutions.shtml#ca |archive-date= March 25, 2013 |url-status= dead |df= mdy-all }}</ref> While all majors are encouraged to participate in [[Cooperative education|co-op]] opportunities and [[Internship#United States|internships]], all students must do a senior research project.<ref>{{cite web |title= Hands-on Activities |url= http://www.cpp.edu/~cosl/hands-on.html |publisher= California State Polytechnic University, Pomona |accessdate= April 9, 2011 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150801031837/http://www.cpp.edu/~cosl/hands-on.html |archivedate= August 1, 2015 |df= mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe {{cvt|300,000|sqft|m2}} [[Cal Poly Pomona University Library]] serves \"as the central intellectual and cultural resource of the campus community\" and contains over 3 million items and serves as an important center for academic research.<ref>{{cite news|title=University Library Briefing Book Detail |url=http://www.cpp.edu/~library/about/briefing_book_detail.html |work=[[Cal Poly Pomona University Library]] |publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona |accessdate=March 28, 2011 }}{{dead link|date=August 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Built in 1969 for $4.2 million, the library underwent a major renovation and expansion completed in the summer of 2008 at a cost of over $46 million.<ref>{{Harvnb|Pflueger|1999|p=160.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Evolution of a Library: 1938-2000 |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~library/about/about-the-library/history.shtml |publisher=Cal Poly Pomona |accessdate=20 September 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180804014341/https://www.cpp.edu/~library/about/about-the-library/history.shtml |archivedate=4 August 2018}}</ref> The library participates in the [[Online Computer Library Center]] (OCLC) Enhance program which allows it to correct or add information to bibliographic records in [[WorldCat]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oclc.org/us/en/worldcat/catalog/quality/enhance/default.htm#enhance|title= OCLC Enhance participants  |publisher= [[Online Computer Library Center]] |accessdate=March 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Distinctions===\nThe university boasts many nationally acclaimed academic colleges and programs. With approximately 5,000 students, its college of Engineering is the second largest in the California State University system.<ref name=\"calstate.edu\">{{cite web|url=http://www.calstate.edu/as/stat_reports/2012-2013/fmaj04.htm|title=CSU - AS - Student Enrollment in Degree Programs Report - Fall 2012|first=Monica Malhotra, Lisa|last=Limbeek|website=www.calstate.edu|accessdate=October 13, 2018}}</ref> The university has the largest Mechanical Engineering, Electrical Engineering, Civil Engineering, and Construction Engineering programs in the CSU, and is the only campus to offer an Engineering Technology focus.\n\nJust behind [[Cal State Fullerton]], the university has the second largest Business Administration major in the CSU with nearly 5,000 students. Its Hospitality program is the largest in the CSU and one of the largest in all of the US, with approximately 1,000 students enrolled. Overall, the university holds the fourth largest business college the CSU.<ref name=\"calstate.edu\"/>\n\n===Rankings===\n{{details|topic=college-specific rankings|Cal Poly Pomona academics#Rankings}}\n{{Infobox US university ranking\n| Forbes = 273\n| THE_WSJ = 389\n| USNWR_REG = 14\n| Wamo_MASTERSU = 83\n}}\n\n''[[Money Magazine]]'' ranked Cal Poly Pomona 268th in the country out of the nearly 1500 schools it evaluated for its 2015-2016 Best Colleges ranking.<ref>{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Money's Best Colleges |url=https://best-colleges.time.com/money/full-ranking#/list |magazine= Money|date=2015 |accessdate=November 12, 2015}}</ref> ''[[The Daily Beast]]'' ranked Cal Poly Pomona 159th in the country out of the nearly 2000 schools it evaluated for its 2014 Best Colleges ranking.<ref>{{cite web |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=The Daily Beast's Guide to the Best Colleges 2014 |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/11/06/the-daily-beast-s-down-and-dirty-guide-to-the-best-colleges-2014.4.html |website=The Daily Beast |date=November 6, 2014 |access-date=November 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'''s 2020 \"Best Regional Universities West Rankings,\" Cal Poly Pomona is ranked 2nd in the western United States for regional public schools whose highest degree is a Master's and 2nd for Most Innovative School, and tied for 14th overall (including private schools).<ref name=USNWR>{{cite web |url=https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/california-state-polytechnic-university-pomona-1144/overall-rankings |title=California State Polytechnic University - Pomona Rankings  |access-date=September 9, 2019 |magazine=U.S. News & World Report}}</ref> The same report ranked the College of Engineering tied for 11th out of undergraduate engineering schools in the U.S. where doctorates are not offered, with national program rankings of:<ref name=USNWR/>\n\n*[[Civil Engineering]]: 5th\n*[[Computer Engineering]]: 5th\n*[[Electrical Engineering]]: 11th\n*[[Mechanical Engineering]]: 12th\n\nIn ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine's 2019 list of \"America's Best Colleges\", Cal Poly Pomona was ranked number 273 among the 650 best public and private colleges and universities in the nation.  In the 2012 \"PayScale College Salary Report\" conducted by [[PayScale]] of bachelor's graduates without higher degrees, Cal Poly Pomona ranked 19th among public universities in the country with a starting median salary of $46,800 and a mid-career median salary of $93,000. This places Cal Poly Pomona the fourth highest in California and the second highest in the CSU, while besting every UC with the exception of Berkeley and San Diego.<ref>{{cite news | title=Top State Universities By Salary Potential | url= http://www.payscale.com/best-colleges/top-state-universities.asp| work= PayScale, Inc. | accessdate=January 31, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2014 ''[[Kiplinger]]'' ranked Cal Poly Pomona 94th out of the top 100 best-value public schools in the nation, and 11th in California.<ref>{{cite magazine | url=http://www.kiplinger.com/tool/college/T014-S001-kiplinger-s-best-values-in-public-colleges/index.php |magazine=Kiplinger's Personal Finance |title=Kiplinger's Best College Values 2015 |date=December 2014}}</ref> Furthermore, Cal Poly Pomona is considered one of the top investments for educational value, with a 2013 net 30-year [[return on investment]] (ROI) of $917,100 according to [[PayScale]]. This ROI is the third highest in the CSU and 113th highest of the 1,511 US colleges and universities that were ranked, besting most UC campuses.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.payscale.com/college-education-value-2013 |title = 2013 College Education ROI Rankings |publisher = PayScale, Inc.}}</ref>\n\n===Admissions===\n<div style=\"float:right; text-align:center; font-size:85%; margin:10px\">\n'''Fall Enrolled Freshman Statistics (Fall 2018-Fall 2011)'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!\n\n! 2019<br /><ref name=\"Fast Facts Fall 2019\">{{cite web |title=Fast Facts Fall 2019 |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~data/documents/cpp-facts/fall_2019_fast_facts_v2_12_06.pdf |publisher=Cal Poly Pomona Office of Academic Research and Resources |accessdate=27 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n! 2018<br /><ref name=\"Common Data Set 2018\">{{cite web |title=Common Data Set 2018-2019 |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~arar/CommonDataSet/CommonDataSetDocs/cds2018.pdf |publisher=Cal Poly Pomona Office of Academic Research and Resources |accessdate=27 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Just the Facts 2018\">{{cite web |title=Just the Facts - Fall 2018 |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~arar/just-the-facts/Historical-Reports/just-the-facts-2018.pdf |publisher=Cal Poly Pomona Office of Academic Research and Resources |accessdate=27 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n! 2017<br /><ref name=\"Common Data Set 2017\">{{cite web |title=Common Data Set 2017-2018 |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~arar/CommonDataSet/CommonDataSetDocs/cds2017.pdf |publisher=Cal Poly Pomona Office of Academic Research and Resources |accessdate=30 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Just the Facts 2017\">{{cite web |title=Just the Facts - Fall 2017 |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~arar/just-the-facts/Historical-Reports/Just_the_Facts_F2017.pdf|publisher=Cal Poly Pomona Office of Academic Research and Resources |accessdate=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n! 2016<br /><ref name=\"Common Data Set 2016\">{{cite web |title=Common Data Set 2016-2017 |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~arar/CommonDataSet/CommonDataSetDocs/cds2016.pdf |publisher=Cal Poly Pomona Office of Academic Research and Resources |accessdate=30 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Just the Facts 2016\">{{cite web |title=Just the Facts - Fall 2016 |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~arar/just-the-facts/Historical-Reports/Just_the_Facts_F2016.pdf|publisher=Cal Poly Pomona Office of Academic Research and Resources |accessdate=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n! 2015<br /><ref name=\"Common Data Set 2015\">{{cite web |title=Common Data Set 2015-2016 |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~arar/CommonDataSet/CommonDataSetDocs/cds2015.pdf |publisher=Cal Poly Pomona Office of Academic Research and Resources |accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Just the Facts 2015\">{{cite web |title=Just the Facts - Fall 2015 |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~arar/just-the-facts/Historical-Reports/Just_the_Facts_F2015.pdf|publisher=Cal Poly Pomona Office of Academic Research and Resources |accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n! 2014\n\n! 2013\n\n! 2012\n\n! 2011\n\n|-\n! Applicants\n| {{formatnum:{{#expr:39726}}}} || {{formatnum:{{#expr:19839+16821}}}} || {{formatnum:{{#expr:18273+16646}}}} || {{formatnum:{{#expr:17579+15338}}}} || {{formatnum:{{#expr:18155+15702}}}} || 32,801 || 31,465 || 28,143 || 23,946 \n|-\n! Admitted\n| {{formatnum:{{#expr:21687}}}} || {{formatnum:{{#expr:9697+10643}}}} || {{formatnum:{{#expr:8936+10289}}}} || {{formatnum:{{#expr:9343+10131}}}} || {{formatnum:{{#expr:6198+7109}}}} || 17,014 ||16,636 || 14,685 || 13,191 \n|-\n! % Admitted\n|<center>{{#expr:(((21687)/(39726))*100)round1}}</center>||<center>{{#expr:(((9697+10643)/(19839+16821))*100)round1}}</center>||<center>{{#expr:(((8936+10289)/(18273+16646))*100)round1}}</center>||<center>{{#expr:(((9343+10131)/(17579+15338))*100)round1}}</center>||<center>{{#expr:(((6198+7109)/(18155+15702))*100)round1}}</center>||<center>51.9</center>||<center>52.9</center> || <center>52.2</center> || <center>55.1</center>  \n|-\n! Enrollment\n|<center>{{formatnum:{{#expr:3694}}}} </center> ||<center>{{formatnum:{{#expr:1963+56+1813+31}}}} </center> || <center>{{formatnum:{{#expr:1864+69+1804+49}}}}</center> || <center>{{formatnum:{{#expr:2155+82+1924+43}}}}</center> || <center>{{formatnum:{{#expr:1355+32+1301+19}}}}</center> || <center>3,658</center> || <center>3,257</center> || <center>3,120</center> || <center>3,249</center> \n|-\n! Average GPA<br /><small>(out of 4.0)</small>\n|<center>3.55</center> ||<center>3.51</center> || <center>3.49</center> || <center>3.52</center>||<center>3.50</center>||<center>3.42</center> || <center>3.43</center> || <center>3.41</center>  || <center>3.32</center>  \n|-\n! Average SAT<br /><small>(out of 1600)</small>\n|<center>1139</center> ||<center>1141</center> || <center>1105</center> || <center>1136</center> || <center>1102</center> || <center>1068</center> || <center>1059</center> || <center>1071</center>  || <center>1057</center>  \n|}\n</div>\n\nThe [[Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching]] and ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' describe Cal Poly Pomona's admissions process as \"selective\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Overview of California State Polytechnic University--Pomona |url=https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/california-state-polytechnic-university-pomona-1144 |magazine=U.S. News & World Report |access-date=September 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Carnegie Foundation - Institution Profile|url=http://carnegieclassifications.iu.edu/lookup/view_institution.php?unit_id=110529|publisher=[[Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching]]|access-date=October 15, 2013}}</ref>  The [[California State University|CSU system]] lists Cal Poly Pomona among 16 of its institutions with higher admission standards for first-time freshmen.<ref>{{cite web |title=Campuses That Have Higher Standards |work=[[California State University]] |url=http://www.csumentor.edu/planning/high_school/campuses_that_have_higher_standards.asp|accessdate=September 14, 2008}}</ref> For the Fall of 2016 there were 32,917 first-time, first year applicants: 19,474 were admitted (51.9%) and 4,204 enrolled (an admissions yield of 21.6%).<ref name=CDS2016>{{cite web |url=http://www.cpp.edu/~arar/CommonDataSet/CommonDataSetDocs/cds2016.pdf |title=Common Data Set 2016\u201317 |publisher=Institutional Research & Academic Resources at California State Polytechnic University, Pomona}}</ref>  The middle 50% range of [[SAT]] scores was 440-560 for reading and 460\u2013600 for math, while the middle 50% [[ACT (test)|ACT]] Composite range was 20-27.<ref name=CDS2016/> Of the enrolled freshmen, 25.6% had a high school GPA of 3.75 or higher, while the average GPA was 3.45.<ref name=CDS2016/>\n\nFreshmen applicants who graduate high school outside Cal Poly Pomona's Tier 1 area (known as Tier 2 applicants) are rank ordered by eligibility index and granted admission based on a year-specific cutoff score.<ref name=\"dsa.cpp.edu\">{{cite web|url=http://dsa.cpp.edu/admissions/ftf_impaction.asp|title=Cal Poly Pomona Admissions and Outreach \u2013 FTE Impaction |publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona|accessdate=April 8, 2011}}</ref> Since academic year 2010\u20132011, Tier 1 applicants may no longer be guaranteed admissions based on the CSU Eligibility Index and may be subject to similar criteria as Tier 2 applicants.<ref name=\"President message - February 22, 2010\">{{cite web |title=Monday Video \u2013 February 22, 2010 | url=http://polycentric.cpp.edu/news_stories/presidentmessage022210.pdf | work=polycentric | format=PDF | accessdate=March 26, 2011}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n====Demographics====\nCal Poly Pomona is an ethnically and culturally diverse university, self-described as \"Champions of Diversity\", ''[[College Prowler]]'' states that \"Cal Poly is the [[melting pot]] of the [[California State University|Cal States]]\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Diversity|url=http://www.cpp.edu/~diversity/facts/0506_Diversity_3_910.pdf|publisher=Office of Diversity and Compliance at Cal Poly Pomona|accessdate=August 6, 2011|format=PDF|date=November 24, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402203131/http://www.cpp.edu/~diversity/facts/0506_Diversity_3_910.pdf|archivedate=April 2, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Cal Poly Pomona \u2013 Diversity|url=http://collegeprowler.com/cal-poly-pomona/diversity/|publisher=[[College Prowler]]|accessdate=August 6, 2011}}</ref>\nAs of 2018 Cal Poly Pomona has the third largest enrollment percentage of Asian Americans in the Cal State System.<ref name=\"Ethnicity Enrollment Profile\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.calstate.edu/as/stat_reports/2018-2019/feth02.htm|title=Ethnicity Enrollment Profile|website=www.calstate.edu|access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; float:right; font-size:85%; margin-left:2em; margin:auto;\"\n|+ ''Fall 2018 Demographics of student body''<ref name=\"Ethnicity Enrollment Profile\"/>\n! !! * All levels, freshman through graduate   \n|-\n! [[African American]]\n| 3.4%\n|-\n! [[Asian American]]\n| 17.1%\n|-\n! [[Filipino American]]\n| 4.0%\n|-\n! [[Pacific Islander]]\n| 0.2%\n|-\n! [[European Americans|White European Americans]]\n| 16.3%\n|-\n! [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American/American Indian]]\n| 0.2%\n|-\n! [[Mexican American|Mexican American/Chicano]]\n| 36.0%\n|-\n! Other [[Latin Americans|Latino]] American \n| 8.9%\n|-\n! [[Multiracial Americans]]\n| 3.7%\n|-\n! [[Non-resident alien]]\n| 6.6%\n|-\n! Unknown\n| 3.5%\n|-\n|}\n\nCal Poly Pomona has over 1,000 visa-bearing international students.<ref>{{cite web |title=International Students |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~international/international-students/index.shtml |publisher=Cal Poly Pomona College of the Extended University, International Center |accessdate=1 October 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180804014330/https://www.cpp.edu/~international/international-students/index.shtml |archivedate=August 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Impaction====\nDuring the fall admissions filing period, the [[California State University|CSU]] designates academic programs where more applications are received than can be accommodated by the campus, and designates them as \"[[Impacted majors|impacted]]\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Impacted Programs|url=http://dsa.cpp.edu/admissions/impacted_programs.asp|publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona|accessdate=March 4, 2011}}</ref> At Cal Poly Pomona, impacted academic programs include: Animal Health Science, Animal Science, Aerospace Engineering, [[Cal Poly Pomona Department of Chemical and Materials Engineering|Chemical and Materials Engineering]], Civil Engineering, Computer Engineering, Electrical Engineering, Mechanical Engineering, [[Cal Poly Pomona Architecture|Architecture]], Psychology, Sociology, Communication, Biology, Biotechnology, and undeclared programs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Undeclared Students|url=http://dsa.cpp.edu/ssep/undeclared.asp |publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona|accessdate=March 3, 2011}}</ref> As such, applicants are rank ordered by eligibility index regardless of local admissions area and are accepted as space permits.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dsa.cpp.edu/admissions/major_impaction.asp|title=Division of Student Affairs|website=dsa.cpp.edu|accessdate=October 13, 2018}}</ref> Cal Poly Pomona students who wish to change majors to an impacted program must meet supplemental requirements required for that major. Requesting a change to an impacted majors must be received by the end of the initial filing period for the term for which new majors are being accepted (i.e. By February 28, 2010 for summer 2011; November 30, 2010 for fall 2011; June 30, 2011 for winter 2012; or August 31, 2011 for spring 2012).<ref>{{cite web|title=Change of Major|url=http://dsa.cpp.edu/registrar/major_.asp|publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona-Registar's Office|accessdate=September 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\n[[File:Student suites at Cal Poly Pomona.png|thumb|left|upright|Student suites at Cal Poly Pomona]]\n===Housing===\n\n{| style=\"float:right;\" \"text-align:center; font-size:85%; margin:auto;\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ ''On Campus Housing Bed Count''\n! !! Beds\n|-\n! Alamitos\n| <center>212</center>\n|-\n! Aliso\n| <center>212</center>\n|-\n! Encinitas\n| <center>212</center>\n|-\n! Montecito\n| <center>212</center>\n|-\n! Cedritos\n| <center>185</center>\n|-\n! Palmitas\n| <center>185</center>\n|-\n! Suites Phase I\n| <center>420</center>\n|-\n! Suites Phase II\n| <center>622</center>\n|-\n! University Village Phase I\n| <center>384</center>\n|-\n! University Village Phase II\n| <center>448</center>\n|-\n! University Village Phase III\n| <center>476</center>\n|-\n! Center for Regenerative Studies\n| <center>20</center>\n|-\n! Total\n| <center>3588</center>\n|}\n\n[[File:Cal Poly Bronco Recreation and Intramural Complex (BRIC).png|right|thumb|Cal Poly's Bronco Recreation and Intramural Complex (BRIC)]]\n\nWith an on-campus housing capacity of 3,519 students, Cal Poly Pomona has the fifth largest housing system in the [[California State University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calstate.edu/cpdc/Facilities_Planning/2015-16-Five-Yr-CapImprovementPgmBk.pdf |title=Facilities planning |date=2016 |website=www.calstate.edu |format=PDF |access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cpp4me.cpp.edu/|title= Future Students |accessdate=December 5, 2010 |work=Cal Poly Pomona}}</ref> In 2016, 39% of first-year students and 10% of all students live in college housing.<ref name=CDS2016/>\n\nThere are three [[dormitory|residential]] styles on the Pomona campus. The oldest housing facilities consist of six residential halls located on University Drive. The four older red-brick halls are named ''Alamitos'', ''Aliso'', ''Encinitas'', and ''Montecito'', each providing accommodation for up to 212 residents.  The other two housing halls (''Cedritos'' and ''Palmitas'') were the result of later housing development and each has room to accommodate up to 185 residents.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cpp.edu/~housing/housing-options/halls-suites.shtml|title=Residence hall/suite information|last=|first=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=February 2, 2017|work=University Housing Services at Cal Poly Pomona}}</ref>\n\nThe two newest residential complexes are the ''Village'' and the ''Suites'' which offer apartment-style living to non-freshman students. The ''Residence Halls'' and the ''Suites'' are managed by the Division of Student Affairs, whereas the ''Village'' is managed by the Cal Poly Pomona Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://foundation.cpp.edu/village/|title=University Village|work=University Village at Cal Poly Pomona|publisher=Cal Poly Pomona Foundation|accessdate=April 7, 2011}}</ref> Phase I of the construction of the Suites, housing 420 students, was completed in 2004 and Phase II, housing 622 students, opened in 2010.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn an effort to reduce commuting and raise academic performance and retention, starting with the 2010\u20132011 academic year, freshmen from outside the Tier 1 Local Admissions area (the area roughly bounded by the San Gabriel Mountains and Chino Hills to the north and south and the 15 and 605 freeways to the east and west), will be required to live on campus.<ref name=\"President message - February 22, 2010\"/>\n\n[[File:CLA Walk.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Students on a walkway leading to the [[CLA Building]]]]\n\n===Bronco Student Center===\n{{Main|Bronco Student Center}}\n[[File:Bronco Student Center.jpg|thumb|right|[[Bronco Student Center]]]]\n\nThe Bronco Student Center is a student activity center for meetings, conferences, meals, recreation, and shopping for students and alumni on the campus of Cal Poly Pomona in Pomona, California. This is where ASI student government offices are located, as well as other various student run departments like facilities and operations, Recreation, Programming and Marketing (RPM), Business Services, Games Room Etc. (GRE).\n\n===LGBT-Friendly campus===\nAccording to the Advocate College Guide for LGBT Students, Cal Poly Pomona is one of the nation's best campuses for lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dsa.cpp.edu/visitors/rankings.asp|title=Division of Student Affairs|website=dsa.cpp.edu|accessdate=October 13, 2018}}</ref> The university offers [[gender-neutral housing]], a pride center for LGBT students, the club oSTEM (out in STEM) and Pride Alliance for faculty and staff members.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dsa.cpp.edu/pride/clubs.asp|title=Division of Student Affairs|website=dsa.cpp.edu|accessdate=October 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Campus media===\nCampus events are covered by the [[student newspaper]], the ''[[The Poly Post|Poly Post]]''. The Bronco Sports Show is a quarterly television broadcast capturing the highlights and statistics from Bronco Athletics along with other featured events around the campus. ''PolyCentric''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://polycentric.cpp.edu |title=PolyCentric &#124; Cal Poly Pomona |publisher=Polycentric.cpp.edu |accessdate=April 30, 2010}}</ref> is the university's official online magazine. PolyCentric features news, announcements of campus events, spotlights on various departments, and resources for faculty and staff. A web site also provides a comprehensive archival search for past articles and photos.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://polycentric.cpp.edu/guide/polycentric-archives.html|title=polycentric Cal Poly Pomona Archives|publisher=Polycentric.cpp.edu|accessdate=April 9, 2011}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Bronco Pep Band===\n{{Main|Bronco Pep Band}}\n\nThe Bronco Pep Band is a student-run band at Cal Poly Pomona. The band is a group within the [[Cal Poly Pomona Broncos|athletic department]]. It follows the tradition of other student-run bands in the sense that it focuses on its members' individuality. The band attends athletic events during the year to encourage the school's athletic teams and audience support/involvement. The pep band is entirely voluntary and all students at Cal Poly Pomona or anyone else in the area are free to join.\n\n===Greek life===\nGreek Life at Cal Poly Pomona consists of 16 fraternities and 11 sororities governed by the Greek Council. From the total male [[Undergraduate education|undergraduate]] population, 2% are enrolled in fraternities and 1% of women in sororities respectively.<ref name=\"College Prowler-Greek Life\">{{cite web|url=http://collegeprowler.com/cal-poly-pomona/greek-life/|title=Cal Poly Pomona \u2013 Greek Life |publisher=[[College Prowler]]|accessdate=September 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dsa.cpp.edu/osl/greeklife/default.asp|title=Welcome to Greek Life at Cal Poly Pomona|publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona|accessdate=March 4, 2011}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sigmanupomona.com/chapter-history|title=Chapter History|publisher=Sigma Nu Fraternity|accessdate=April 11, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120915045857/http://www.sigmanupomona.com/chapter-history|archivedate=September 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\nActive Chapters at include, but are not limited to: [[Nu Alpha Kappa]], [[Sigma Alpha Epsilon]], [[Sigma Chi]], [[Phi Kappa Tau]], [[Pi Kappa Alpha]], [[Pi Kappa Phi]], [[Alpha Xi Delta]], [[Chi Omega]], [[Sigma Kappa]], [[Kappa Delta]], [[Zeta Tau Alpha]], [[Triangle Fraternity|Triangle]], [[Phi Sigma Rho]], [[Alpha Phi Gamma (sorority)|Alpha Phi Gamma]] as well as other multicultural, professional, honor and service societies.\n\n===Rose Parade float===\n{{Main|Cal Poly Universities Rose Float}}\nCal Poly Pomona together with [[California Polytechnic State University|Cal Poly San Luis Obispo]] has participated in the [[Tournament of Roses Parade|Tournament of Roses parade]] since 1949; winning the Award of Merit in their first year. In the period from 1949\u20132005, the floats have won 44 awards. This joint program is one of the longest consecutive running self-built entries in the parade, as well as the only \"self built\" floats designed and constructed entirely by students year-round on both campuses. The Rose Float tradition continues today and marks the partnership between the two Cal Poly campuses.\n\n==Athletics==\n{{Main|Cal Poly Pomona Broncos}}\n\n===Voorhis Vikings===\nBefore the university moved from San Dimas to Pomona, the college had a handful of athletic teams named the '''\"Voorhis Vikings\"'''. They were composed mostly of homeless and orphaned boys of all races who were cared for at the Voorhis School during the ten-year period it operated.<ref>{{cite web | title=Special Collections & University Archives-Voorhis Vikings | url=http://www.cpp.edu/~library/specialcollections/voorhis/vikings/index.html | work=University Library at California State Polytechnic University, Pomona | accessdate=April 26, 2010 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827094416/http://www.cpp.edu/~library/specialcollections/voorhis/vikings/index.html | archive-date=August 27, 2016 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> Despite this historical background, the university's current athletic programs are named the Broncos.\n\n===Cal Poly Pomona Broncos===\nCal Poly Pomona [[varsity team]]s compete in the [[California Collegiate Athletic Association]] of [[NCAA Division II]]. Teams are known as the [[Cal Poly Pomona Broncos]] and field 10 sports for men and women for the fall, winter, and spring quarters. Cal Poly Pomona's most recent national championship came in [[2010 NCAA Men's Division II Basketball Tournament|2010 Division II basketball tournament]] when the university's [[Cal Poly Pomona Broncos men's basketball|men's basketball team]] defeated [[Indiana University of Pennsylvania]] 65\u201353 in the title game.  The Broncos are currently the most successful program in the CCAA having achieved 60 CCAA and 14 NCAA National Championships.<ref>{{cite web | title=All-Time CCAA Champions | url=http://www.goccaa.org/sports/2006/8/11/alltime_ccaa_champs.aspx | work=[[California Collegiate Athletic Association]] | accessdate=April 26, 2010 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100322210007/http://www.goccaa.org/sports/2006/8/11/alltime_ccaa_champs.aspx | archive-date=March 22, 2010 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=History | url=http://www.broncoathletics.com/sports/2009/11/4/Traditions_page.aspx?tab=history| publisher=[[Cal Poly Pomona Broncos]]| accessdate=March 31, 2011}}</ref> University athletes have also claimed individual championships in women's [[women's tennis|tennis]] (1980, 1981, 1991, and 1992).\n\nTeam national championships for the Broncos include the following:\n*[[College Baseball|Baseball]]: 1976, 1980, 1983\n*Men's cross country: 1983\n*Men's [[college basketball|basketball]]: 2010\n*Women's [[women's basketball|basketball]]: 1982, 1985, 1986, 2001, 2002\n\n==Notable people==\n{{Main|List of Cal Poly Pomona people}}\n\n===Faculty===\nSome notable faculty members include: [[Pritzker Prize]] laureate [[Thom Mayne]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography|url=http://www.pritzkerprize.com/laureates/2005/bio.html|publisher=[[Pritzker Prize|The Pritzker Architecture Prize]]|accessdate=March 6, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101221230718/http://pritzkerprize.com/laureates/2005/bio.html <!--Added by H3llBot-->|archivedate=December 21, 2010}}</ref> [[Modernism|modernist]] architect [[Richard Neutra]],<ref>{{cite web|title=P&R Responses for recommendation 121 |url=https://win.webdev.cpp.edu/sppr/response.aspx?id=121|work=[[Cal Poly Pomona Architecture|Department of Architecture at Cal Poly Pomona]]|publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona|accessdate=March 5, 2011}}</ref> poet [[Virginia Hamilton Adair]],<ref name=\"Cal Poly Pomona Collection\">{{cite web| url=http://www.cpp.edu/~library/specialcollections/adair/VHA.html| title=Special Collections and Archives \u2013 Virginia Hamilton Adair Collection| publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona| accessdate=May 5, 2010| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150505003440/https://www.cpp.edu/~library/specialcollections/adair/VHA.html| archive-date=May 5, 2015| url-status=dead| df=mdy-all}}</ref> engineer [[Gabriel Georgiades]],<ref name=\"Cal Poly Pomona Faculty\">{{cite web|\nurl=http://www.cpp.edu/~engineering/ARO/faculty.shtml|publisher=California State Polytechnic University, Pomona|accessdate =October 25, 2017|title=Aerospace Faculty}}</ref> and [[Fulbright Program|Fulbright scholar]] [[Renford Reese]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.insidesocal.com/educationnow/2009/08/cal-poly-pomona-professor-awar.html|title=Cal Poly Pomona professor awarded Fulbright Scholar fellowship|last=Tasci|first=Canan|publisher=[[Los Angeles Newspaper Group]]|accessdate=May 5, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713040745/http://www.insidesocal.com/educationnow/2009/08/cal-poly-pomona-professor-awar.html|archivedate=July 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Alumni===\nMore than 149,000 alumni have graduated from Cal Poly Pomona over the course of its history, and over 15,000 remain active with the university through the [[Cal Poly Pomona Alumni Association]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sanford |first1=Matthew |title=About the Alumni Association |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~alumni/about/index.shtml |publisher=Cal poly Pomona Alumni Association |accessdate=2 October 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180814190555/https://www.cpp.edu/~alumni/about/index.shtml |archivedate=August 14, 2018}}</ref> Some notable alumni include [[Hilda Solis]], former [[United States Secretary of Labor|U.S. Secretary of Labor]]; Former Republican State Senator [[Jim Brulte]], [[The Stooges|Stooges]] guitarist and former [[Sony]] technology executive [[James Williamson (musician)|James Williamson]]; author [[Anthony Amaral]]; [[Academy Award]]-winning actor [[Forest Whitaker]];<ref>{{cite web | title=Resume | url=http://solis.house.gov/biography/resume.shtml| work=Office of the Congresswoman Hilda Solis | accessdate=September 20, 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080730192930/http://solis.house.gov/biography/resume.shtml <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = July 30, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"CSU Mentor\">{{cite web | title=Cal Poly Pomona | url=http://www.csumentor.edu/campustour/undergraduate/1/Cal_Poly_Pomona/Cal_Poly_Pomona5.html| work= CSU Mentor | accessdate=September 12, 2008}}</ref> and popular Twitch streamer Herschel Beahm IV ([[Dr DisRespect]]) who played on the Broncos' basketball team. [[Chi Cheng (athlete)|Chi Cheng]] and [[Kim Rhode]] are Cal Poly Pomona alumni and Olympic medalists.<ref name=\"College Prowler-Alumni & Post-Grads\">{{cite web |url=http://collegeprowler.com/cal-poly-pomona/alumni--and--post--grads/ |title=Cal Poly Pomona-Alumni & Post-Grads |publisher=[[College Prowler]] |accessdate=September 2, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100919225706/http://collegeprowler.com/cal-poly-pomona/alumni--and--post--grads/ |archive-date=September 19, 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Among other notable alumni in athletics are: [[Heisman Trophy]]-winning football player [[Glenn Davis (halfback)|Glenn Davis]], former professional football player and NFL head coach [[Jim Zorn]],<ref>{{cite web | title=Glenn Davis Statistics | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/D/DaviGl01.htm| work= Sports Reference LLC| accessdate=April 4, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/dcsportsbog/2008/02/jim_zorn_plays_viola_and_speed.html |title=Jim Zorn Plays Viola and Speedskates |work=Washington Post |accessdate=September 19, 2008}}</ref> soccer player [[Jonathan Bornstein]],<ref>{{cite web| title=Player Bio:Jonathan Bornstein| url=http://www.uclabruins.com/sports/m-soccer/mtt/bornstein_jonathan00.html| work=[[UCLA Bruins|University of California, Los Angeles athletics]]| accessdate=July 20, 2010| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928135042/http://www.uclabruins.com/sports/m-soccer/mtt/bornstein_jonathan00.html| archivedate=September 28, 2011| df=mdy-all}}</ref> BMX rider [[Dave Mirra]],<ref name=\"College Prowler-Alumni & Post-Grads\" /> and all-time [[PBA Tour]] titles leader [[Walter Ray Williams, Jr.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pba.com/Bowlers/Bowler/11534|work=[[Professional Bowlers Association]]|title=Walter Ray Williams Jr|date=March 3, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Los Angeles}}\n*[[California Master Plan for Higher Education]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{cite book|title=Cal Poly: The First Hundred Years|year=2001|publisher=California Polytechnic State University|location=San Luis Obispo, California|isbn=0944197663 |ref={{harvid|CPSUSLO|2001}}}}\n* {{citation|last=Angel|first=Myron|authorlink=Myron_Angel|title=History of the California Polytechnic School at San Luis Obispo, California|year=1907|publisher=[[The Tribune (San Luis Obispo)]]|location=San Luis Obispo, California|url=https://archive.org/details/historyofcalifor00ange }}\n* {{citation|last=Gerth|first=Donald|year=2010|title=The People's University: A History of the California State University|publisher=University of California, Institute of Governmental Studies|isbn=0-87772-435-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v4J-QwAACAAJ}}\n* {{citation|last=Kennedy|first=Robert E.|year=2001|title=Learn by Doing \u2013 Memoirs of a University President: A Personal Journey with the Seventh President of California Polytechnic State University.|publisher=California Polytechnic State University|location=San Luis Obispo, California }}\n* {{citation|last=Parkinson|first=Mary Jane|title=The Romance of the Kellogg Ranch|year=2001|publisher=South Sea International Press, Ltd|location=Hong Kong, People's Republic of China|isbn=978-0-9777